<DOCNO> AP880429-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-HolyCity     04-29 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Holy City,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jews, Arabs Vow Never To Leave Holy Ancient City</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian Moslems respond to a prayer call
from a minaret and head for a mosque in the Old City. A few hundred
yards away, ultra-Orthodox Jews dressed in black bow again and
again before a stone wall.
   Arabs and Israelis, enemies but neighbors inside the walls of
ancient Jerusalem, pass without speaking. Israeli riot police stand
guard on rooftops and in alleys, where anti-Israeli graffiti are
scrawled on some walls.
   Jerusalem is a city both Jews and Moslem passionately claim _
and, reluctantly, share.
   For the Jews, it is, as the Old Testament's Psalms say,
``Jerusalem, my highest joy.'' For the Moslems, it is ``Al Quds,''
or ``The Holy.''
   Its name means ``city of peace,'' but it is at the heart of the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   If Secretary of State George P. Shultz is able to persuade the
two sides to sit at a negotiating table, the issue of this city's
future is likely to be a major stumbling block.
   Initially settled about 2,500 years before the birth of Christ,
Jerusalem has been beseiged and conquered 37 times by foreign
forces, including the Romans, the Crusaders and the Arab general
Saladin.
   Today, walled ancient Jerusalem covers a crowded square mile of
narrow cobblestone streets, broad courtyards hidden behind locked
doors, and a colorful Arab market often shuttered by strikes in the
5-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule.
   Nowhere in Jerusalem are Jewish-Arab differences more strongly
felt than in the Old City.
   Hundreds of Palestinian worshipers and Israeli troops converge
each Friday for Moslem prayers at the city's two holiest mosques,
the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa, where angry Arab protests often
erupt.
   Tear gas thrown to quell the demonstrations sometimes disturbs
Jewish prayers at the adjoining Western Wall, the last remnant of
the second Jewish temple destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70 and
Judaism's holiest shrine.
   It is here that Israel seeks to break the back of the uprising
by forcing merchants who supply the occupied West Bank to obey
Israeli rule instead of Palestine Liberation Organization orders.
   Fourteen Arab merchants face up to two years in jail for opening
shops during PLO-ordained hours in violation of army orders.
   As the city grows increasingly tense, however, most of the
17,000 Moslems and 2,000 Jews who live inside ancient Jerusalem say
they grow more determined in their commitment to stay.
   ``The Old City tastes of history. In every stone there is a
book,'' said Palestinian poet Fawzi Bakri, born within Jerusalem's
walls 42 years ago.
   ``I don't live in Jerusalem _ it lives in me,'' he said. ``I can
never leave.''
   For Israeli Evelyn Davis, who has lived here five years, the
soul of the Old City is in its Western Wall, also known as the
Wailing Wall.
   ``The wall offers solace to so many Jewish people. You see them
day after day, talking to God,'' said Mrs. Davis, 44, a native of
Greenbelt, Md.
   ``But the Old City is more than a shrine. It is my home,'' she
said. ``If I am threatened, I will turn into a she-bear.''
   The Old City was held by Jordan for the first 19 years of
Israeli history, until Jewish troops overran it in the 1967 war.
Then Israel proclaimed the city its capital, a decision that Arabs
refuse to recognize.
   Palestinians in Jerusalem still recall Israel's conquest with
bitterness.
   Mahmud Abu Sneineh, 52, said he was forced to leave his
apartment after the war when Israelis bought the building where he
lived. He moved to Hebron on the West Bank but was soon drawn back
to Jerusalem, even though he could afford only two rooms for his
family of six.
   ``Nothing can match the Old City,'' he said. ``We will stay here
and die here, which will surely happen because blood will be shed
over this city.''
   Israeli poet Yehuda Amichai sees the problem in dark terms. In
his book ``Poems of Jerusalem,'' he writes:
   ``Jerusalem stone is the only stone that can
   Feel pain. It has a network of nerves.
   From time to time Jerusalem crowds into
   Mass protests like the tower of Babel.
   And afterward the city disperses, muttering
   Prayers of complaint and sporadic screams from churches
   And synagogues and loud-moaning mosques.
   Each to his own place.''
   Palestinian poet Bakri knows Amichai's poetry and appreciates
that others love this city as he does. But he supports the Arab
revolt.
   ``My only fear,'' Bakri said, fingering worry beads, ``is that
the uprising brings this city closer to more calamity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
