<1ST_LINE>r a PM-High-TechCarts     04-29 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-High-Tech Carts,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grocery Cart Enters The Video Age</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grocery cart of the future is here _ a
high-tech, video-equipped gadget that can say hello and offer
games, shopping tips, sports scores and _ here's the catch _
on-the-spot advertising to the consumer.
   ``We're expecting it to make shopping more fun, less of a hassle
and more efficient for consumers,'' said Forrest Anderson, director
for marketing communications at Information Resources Inc., which
developed the cart.
   The Chicago-based marketing-research company spent two years
inventing the VideOcart, with a liquid-crystal-display video screen
mounted near the kiddie seat to entertain, inform and offer a few
words from the sponsors.
   Shoppers using IRI's VideOcarts will be able to call up store
maps, reserve numbers at the deli counter, find out which checkout
line is shortest, play tic tac toe or trivia games to pass the time
in line, and get the time, weather forecast or sports scores.
   The carts would be provided free to the supermarkets, with costs
paid by advertisers whose commercials could be transmitted
nationally by satellite to local supermarkets.
   The high-tech carts are to be test-marketed this fall in three
stores, Anderson said _ one in the Chicago area, the others in
cities not yet chosen.
   If the test-marketing goes well, IRI plans to introduce the
carts in major-city grocery stores in July 1989 and go national in
1991 with carts in 10,000 supermarkets.
   The video screens will be especially encased to make them
``kid-proof, grape-juice-proof, shock and water resistant,'' with
an alarm system to prevent theft, Anderson said.
   Ads will make up about 15 percent of the programming. The rest
will be entertainment and information services.
   IRI Chairman John Malec, who developed the cart introduced in
Chicago and New York this week, called it ``the most important new
advertising and promotion medium since television.''
   Using sensors in the aisles, an ad for coffee or soda pop can be
automatically triggered when the cart reaches the area where those
products are shelved.
   The use of in-store advertising _ signs attached to shopping
carts, sales pitches on store sound systems and the like _ has
burgeoned in recent years, with spending growing 14 percent a year
over the past decade to an estimated $12.6 billion last year,
according to industry estimates.
   VideOcart offers the advantage of packaging the ads with
entertainment, said Malec.
   IRI plans to invest $200 million over the next three years in
developing the system, Anderson said.
   One food-company official expressed interest in the carts, but
said he would want to see the test-market results before making a
commitment.
   Ronald Frahler, retail trade promotion manager for the
Deerfield, Ill.-based Kitchens of Sara Lee, a major frozen
baked-goods producer, suggested there might be some confusion as
shoppers get used to wheeling and viewing.
   ``There is probably going to be some bumping into each other,''
said Frahler, who viewed the cart in Chicago.
   But he said ``the concept is fascinating and it seems to be well
thought out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
