<DOCNO> AP880429-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HungryMigrants     04-29 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungry Migrants,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Farmers Charging Migrants High Fees To Fill Out Workers'
Forms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in report for Friday AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORNELIUS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of destitute migrant workers
are being victimized by farmers who charge them as much as $400
each to prepare false immigration papers, authorities say.
   As many as 25,000 migrants dependent on social service agencies
for food and shelter are in the state, unemployed and waiting for
Oregon's strawberry harvest, the country's second largest after
California's, to begin about June 1.
   Under the nation's new immigration law, most migrants who picked
crops in the United States for at least 90 days in 1985-86 may
qualify as permanent resident aliens and continue to legally enter
the country to work in future years.
   Some farmers are preparing fraudulent documents for migrants who
otherwise would not qualify under the law, said David Beebe, the
district director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service in Portland.
   Others demand excessive fees to prepare the documents the
migrants must present to federal authorities to fulfill the law's
requirements, he said.
   ``The Immigration Service is aware of unscrupulous employers ...
who are finding new ways to exploit workers,'' Beebe said. He
emphasized, however, that the majority of strawberry growers treat
pickers fairly.
   Beebe declined to comment on what steps his agency is taking to
deal with the dishonest farmers and their allies, including
printers who can prodcuce false rent receipts and other documents.
   The agricultural workers have until Nov. 30 to file the papers.
After that, employers who hire illegal migrant workers will face
stiff penalties.
   The migrants must pay $185 each to apply for amnesty under the
new law. Fees for physical examinations, pictures and other
required documents push the cost to near $300.
   Strawberry farmer Doug Krahmer said he has heard of growers
charging as much as $400 additional to prepare the paperwork.
Another grower, who asked not to be identified, said he's heard
some farmers are charging $250.
   Krahmer estimated that as many as one-fourth of the migrants are
being charged more than $25 to help defray the costs involved. He
said he charges $20 to process paperwork for migrants seeking
documentation at his Lloy-Dene Farms near Cornelius.
   But Matt Unger, chairman of the Oregon Strawberry Commission,
said he knows of no grower charging more than $25.
   ``The ones I know of charge nothing or a nominal fee,'' he said.
   Krahmer said labor contractors, brokers who sign up and deliver
the pickers to growers, are promising the papers to attract
workers. Last year, the strawberry crop was harvested early and 20
percent of the crop was left in the fields because not enough
workers were in the state.
   Many pickers say they were told they must turn in their
documentation by May 4, the deadline for aliens who aren't involved
in agricultural work. Hundreds of migrant pickers, confused by the
heavily publicized May deadline, are rushing to INS offices around
the state.
   The result this year has been an influx of migrants, nearly all
men and teen-age boys, weeks before the crop is ready to be picked.
   Typical of these is 14-year-old Felix Lopez, who is broke, on
his own and a long way from his home.
   Speaking in Spanish, the teen-ager from Ensenada, Mexico, said
he has never picked strawberries in Oregon before, but that a
``friend'' told him growers would sign the papers he needs to keep
returning here to work.
   The Rev. David E. Zegar, of St. Alexander's Catholic Church in
Cornelius, said he believes contractors have drawn migrants to
Oregon early by falsely promising to arrange their immigration
papers. The workers stay in labor camps without money, food and
other essentials, he said, waiting for the strawberries to ripen
while social service agencies struggle to meet their needs.
   ``I don't think anybody has the right to put people into a
situation where they have to beg for food and essentials,'' Zegar
said.
   At Centro Cultural, the community center in Cornelius, migrants
watch Spanish-language television in the lobby and wait for dinner,
served Monday through Thursday at 3 p.m. Each day, Centro Cultural
serves an average of more than 200 free meals of beans, potatoes
and tortillas to the migrants.
   The Salvation Army is meeting the needs of thousands of other
migrants, distributing tons of beans, potatoes, rice and flour.
   The uncertainty over the workforce has led many growers in
Oregon to abandon planting strawberries; plantings for next year
are down 75 percent. Plantings are up in California, the largest
strawberry producer, which has a resident picker population and
isn't reliant on foreign labor.
   Last year, Oregon produced a bumper crop of 94 million pounds
which sold for a record $31.5 million.

</TEXT>
