<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz'sWoes Bjt   04-29 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz's Woes, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Little Headway In Middle East Or On Soviet Front</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instead of slowing down, George Shultz is
stepping on the gas. But the determined secretary of state has
little to show for his vigorous diplomatic efforts in these final
months of the Reagan administration.
   He had hoped to open Mideast peace talks this Sunday, in the
first stage of an ambitious U.S. program aimed at providing some
measure of self-rule to the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs who live
on the Israeli-held West Bank and in Gaza.
   But despite two trips to the area, Shultz was unable to persuade
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir or King Hussein of Jordan to
accept his proposal.
   Shultz says he will keep trying, and will try to find the time
to make another personal appeal to the Middle East leaders. But he
seems less optimistic than ever before.
   On the Soviet front, Shultz is making arrangements for President
Reagan's visit to Moscow May 29-June 2 for a fourth and probably
final summit meeting with General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The centerpiece was supposed to be a treaty to halve the Soviet
and U.S. arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons. But with only a
month left, the two sides are still far apart on such issues as the
U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative and how to monitor the reduction
of mobile missiles and other weapons that are relatively easy to
conceal.
   Even the treaty signed at last year's Washington summit to scrap
intermediate-range nuclear missiles is still awaiting Senate
approval.
   Shultz will try again May 11-12 in Geneva with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze. But he appears to be lowering his
sights to a summit that would be mostly an exchange of views
between Reagan and Gorbachev instead of a historic event.
   Analysts differ on whether Gorbachev's decision to withdraw some
115,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan is a victory for U.S.
foreign policy or a decision taken by Moscow for its own reasons.
   But on other regional fronts there is little opportunity for the
Reagan administration to claim credit.
   The Soviets are resisting a U.S. plea that they help impose a
worldwide arms embargo on Iran. And they decline to accept a benign
role in a Middle East peace conference. ``I didn't achieve any
breakthrough,'' Shultz admitted Thursday to a Senate appropriations
subcommittee about his talks last week in Moscow.
   Taking the long view, he reminded the senators how cool the
U.S.-Soviet relationship was in 1985, before Gorbachev took over.
   Shultz's human rights pleas now get a respectful hearing, and
even some action. Jewish emigration hit a 15-month high last month.
   Giving the subject ``the pride of place'' on his agenda, Shultz
opened his talks with Shevardnadze with human rights and kept at it
for two hours.
   In the past, the Soviets mostly listened impassively to U.S.
pleas. Now American and Soviet lawyers and psychiatrists are
holding meetings to discuss the situation.
   Otherwise, though, even the climate is worsening.
   Gorbachev took sharp exception last week to a speech by Reagan
accusing the Soviets of aggression and other bad behavior.
   He complained the United States was ``sermonizing'' as well as
attributing any improvement in relations to a policy of strength.
   Shultz tried to minimize the criticism. He said there was a
``rhythm'' to U.S.-Soviet relations that had both moments of
progress and of discord.
   Other State Department officials were privately critical of the
tough rhetoric in Reagan's speech. They said it had not been
submitted to the department for review before delivery.
   Ever loyal, though, Shultz told the Senate subcommittee on
Thursday that ``we must call it as we see it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid, head of the AP's State Department
staff, accompanied Shultz on his trips to the Middle East and
Moscow.
</TEXT>
