<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FishDebts Bjt   04-29 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fish Debts, Bjt,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catch of the Day: Accounts Receivable</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the bustling and often chaotic seafood
industry, Neal Workman casts a widening net for what might be the
most prized catch of all: Buyers who refuse to pay up.
   Workman's work has taken him on predawn visits to ramshackle
back offices in New York City's tough Fulton Fish Market, where
prudent debt collectors seldom venture in an industry notorious for
its proliferation of deadbeats.
   Bullhorn in hand, Workman has brazenly entered crowded seafood
restaurants at the height of the lunch hour to announce to patrons
that the fish on their plates may not have been paid for.
   ``It's the No. 1 problem in the industry,'' says the former debt
collector and sales representative for Dun & Bradstreet Inc., who
has carved out a fast-growing and profitable new business, Debt
Management Services.
   ``Fish is in such demand, it's so popular, that it's not hard to
sell. It's certainly not hard to sell a Maine lobster. The hard
part is to get paid for it.''
   Part of the problem is that seafood is a perishable commodity
whose value is at its highest when it hits the dock and then
diminishes rapidly.
   ``To get the most for their product before the value drops they
have to move it very quickly _ and that means they take unusual
risks,'' Workman explained.
   ``They'll sell to people knowing there's maybe only a 50-50
chance they'll get paid, as opposed to a 100 percent chance that
the fish will spoil and become a non-saleable item.''
   Because sellers are reluctant to communicate with each other for
fear of losing a competitive edge, unscrupulous restaurateurs and
wholesalers have been known to switch from supplier to supplier in
order to avoid ever having to pay their accounts due, Workman says.
   To combat such practices, Debt Management semimonthly publishes
SeaScan, a continuously updated list of hundreds of seafood
markets, restaurants, wholesalers, brokers and distributors who are
in arrears on their debts.
   The publication, about 50 pages long, consists of yellow pages
with the names of buyers whose payments are at least 30 days past
due; red pages listing buyers whose accounts have been referred to
the company for collection; and white pages, tagged the ``rubber
sheet,'' which lists buyers whose checks have bounced.
   ``Yellow is slow, red has stopped,'' Workman explains.
``Everyone who has stopped paying his bills slowed down first.''
   SeaScan is distributed to his company's more than 200 clients,
ranging from salmon harvesters in Scotland's Shetland Islands to
catfish producers in the Mississippi Delta to shrimp importers on
the West Coast.
   A seller who purchases the SeaScan report and becomes a Debt
Management client can refer past due accounts to Workman's company,
which receives a percentage of the overdue receivables it collects
in addition to a $2,500 a year membership fee.
   The 33-year-old Nyack, N.Y., native, who began the business
three years ago in his home, today has 17 employees and subsidiary
offices in Boston and Seattle. He says his clients are among the
largest in the industry, accounting for nearly half the dollar
volume of seafood sold in the U.S. market.
   Workman hasn't emerged unscathed from deadbeat raids. He recalls
the time three fish cutters grabbed him by the jacket at a seafood
wholesaler's in Pompano Beach, Fla., and tossed him unceremoniously
onto the sidewalk.
   But while inside the establishment, Workman had spotted some
boxes bearing the name of one of his major clients. He immediately
telephoned the client and apprised him of the situation; the
client, in turn, called the wholesaler and threatened to cut off
future shipments if he didn't pay the debt.
   Waiting for Workman when he returned was an apology and a check
for $15,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-JunkBonds Bjt   04-29 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Drexel Tolerated Employee Sweetheart Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators are portraying
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. as a greedy firm that elbowed its own
clients aside so top employees could profit on hot new issues of
high-yield, high-risk ``junk'' bonds.
   But Drexel chief executive Frederick H. Joseph, in 6{ hours of
testimony Thursday before the investigations subcommittee of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee, steadfastly defended the
firm's practice of permitting employees to form private
partnerships to compete with other investors for bonds underwritten
by Drexel.
   Under questioning from Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of
both the committee and subcommittee, Joseph acknowledged ``the
perception of a conflict is troublesome.''
   Still, he said Drexel not only condones the partnerships, but
believes they benefit corporate bond issuers by making more money
available to buy the bonds.
   However, documents released by the subcommittee showed that on
several occasions Drexel employees purchased bonds from much-sought
issues for their own accounts at the same time the firm's public
customers were being turned away.
   In the case of Texstyrene Corp., a Phoenix, Ariz., manufacturer
of styrofoam products, partnerships owned by Drexel employees
purchased $12 million of an initial $50 million offering in
February 1986, according to the subcommittee.
   Public customers were allowed to buy only some of the bonds they
wanted, and within 17 days Drexel employees made more than $900,000
profits by selling the bonds back to Drexel, subcommittee documents
indicate.
   In another case, the subcommittee said, Drexel employees
purchased $235 million of a $2.5 billion issue in the April 1986
leveraged buyout of Beatrice Cos., a diversified food and consumer
products company.
   Again, other customers were denied the chance to purchase as
many bonds as they had initially ordered. And less than three
months later, the employees made a $2.8 million profit by selling
$61.4 million of the bonds, the subcommittee said.
   ``Any way you slice it, the people on the outside aren't getting
the same deal as the people on the inside,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden,
D-Ore.
   Rep. Dennis E. Eckart, D-Ohio, said Drexel, in effect, ``elbowed
aside'' its own customers and ``cut to the head of the line.'' He
said a telephone survey of five top competitors of Drexel, whom he
declined to identify, showed that none would permit similar
practices.
   Joseph said it is quite common that investors will want to buy
more bonds than are available and said Drexel used the same
criteria for deciding how many bonds employees could purchase as it
did for its other customers.
   He said purchases by Drexel employees are closely monitored for
propriety by the firm's compliance department.
   However, Rep. Norman Lent of New York, ranking Republican on
committee, said the purchases for ``insider accounts'' appear to
violate the regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission
and the National Association of Securities Dealers.
   Joseph argued that the rules applied only to sales of stock
because bond prices are not subject to manipulation in the same way
as are prices of new stock issues.
   Lent said high-quality, investment-grade bonds are exempt from
the rules, but not the risky bonds of the type Drexel issued.
   The subcommittee released a list of 35 so-called ``insider
accounts'' owned by employees including Michael Milken, chief of
Drexel's junk bond trading unit in Beverly Hills, Calif., and
relatives of Milken.
   Also listed as having participated in the partnerships are
Dennis Levine, a former investment banker now serving a prison term
for securities law violations, and Martin Siegel, who also has
pleaded guilty to violations of securities laws.
   Both are former Drexel employees and have cooperated in
government probes of Wall Street corruption.
   Milken, in a subcommittee appearance Wednesday, cited his
constitutional protection against self-incrimination in refusing to
answer questions. He confirmed that he has been under investigation
for 18 months by a New York federal grand jury that is reported to
be probing insider trading.
   Both Drexel and Milken have denied any wrongdoing.
   Milken pioneered use of junk bonds to allow companies without a
track record of earnings to get financing based on whether they had
sufficient cash flow to pay off their debts. The bonds pay higher
interest rates than those of established companies and are
considered riskier investments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
