<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DixonAccident     04-29 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dixon Accident,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FRA Report Cites Alcohol Use, Switch Cutoff In Train Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispatcher in charge of two Chicago and
Northwestern freight trains that collided March 21 in Illinois had
been drinking too much and automatic brakes on one train had been
shut off, the government reported today.
   The Federal Railroad Administration also said two brakemen had
tested positive for marijuana use. Three crewmen were seriously
injured in the accident, which caused $195,000 in damage.
   The accident occurred in Dixon, Ill., when a train consisting of
a locomotive and a single car headed east while a train of four
locomotives and 130 cars headed west on the same track, the FRA
said.
   The smaller, eastbound train was equipped with what is known as
``automatic train control,'' which should have stopped it when the
two entered the same signal block, the FRA said. It said the
engineer had deliberately disabled the device.
   The dispatcher had a blood alcohol level of 0.15 percent, while
the standard for intoxication in Illinois is 0.10 percent, the FRA
said. A brakeman on the eastbound train and one on the westbound
train each tested positive for marijuana, the FRA said.
   The three injured employees _ the conductor and two brakemen _
were on the larger train, the FRA said.
</TEXT>
