<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilSpill     04-29 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Spill,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rising As Wind and Tides Threaten To Spread Slick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong wind and rising tides hampered
the cleanup of a 175,000-gallon oil spill and posed a new threat to
a fragile bird sanctuary where nearly 200 oil-soaked birds and
animals have died.
   ``The good news is the oil is no longer getting out of Peyton
Slough, where 80 percent of it was trapped, but the bad news is
that what's out there in the strait and bays is going to get
swirled around a bit by nature,'' Coast Guard spokesman Dave
Zawadzki said Thursday.
   Meanwhile, a state water quality engineer speculated the size of
Shell Oil Co.'s spill may be even larger than the 175,000 gallons
estimated by the company. The spill occurred Saturday when a
drainpipe that carries off rainwater broke inside an oil tank,
allowing oil to be siphoned out.
   So far workers have recovered some 126,000 gallons of the San
Joaquin crude, a particularly thick oil, from the area 40 miles
northeast of San Francisco, the Coast Guard said.
   Because much of the oil remains in Peyton Slough and nearby
marshes, Kazemi Hossain, an engineer with the state Regional Water
Quality Control board, told reporters he expects Shell ``will
revise upwards their spill estimate, after we do our own
calculations.''
   Earlier Thursday, westerly winds up to 25 mph and increasingly
higher tides pushed up to 1,600 gallons of oil out of remote
sloughs into the Carquinez Strait and into still more waterfowl
nesting areas. Similar gusts were expected today, National Weather
Service forecasters said.
   By the weekend, easterly winds and exceptionally high weekend
tides _ peaking about 5 feet _ are likely to send still more oil
into uncontaminated areas, Zawadzki said.
   Eight skimmer boats on Thursday began removing new oil-sheen
patches stretching six miles from Martinez Marina, where 400 boats
were trapped in the oily harbor, to Ryer Island, where the the oil
got into nesting areas.
   Some 450 oily waterfowl and animals have been recovered. Of
those, 192 have died or were dead when discovered, according to
Brian Hunter, regional manager of the state Fish and Game
Department.
   The Coast Guard advised sport fishing and recreational boats
owners to stay out of Suisun Bay over the weekend, where several
oil sheens were spotted. The bay is about 40 miles northeast of San
Francisco.
   Boat skippers, many of whom make a living by taking out weekend
parties of sports fishermen, were upset they would not be allowed
out to sea Sunday for the opening of the salmon season. They also
could not leave the marina for the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta,
where steelhead trout are approaching the peak of their spawning
season.
   ``This is going to be a big blow to a lot of old timers around
here because they count on getting out to sea and getting a good
catch early in the season when they can get the best price,'' said
Angelo Torliano, 74, whose son operates a family fishing business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
