<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0647EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-29 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railroad Car Shortage Hampers Grain Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robust export demand and failure to add to the
fleet since 1982 have caused a shortage of railroad cars to move
wheat and corn, says a transportation official with the Agriculture
Department.
   Although the car shortages appear to have eased in recent days,
steps need to be taken to avoid a repetition of the crunch that
occurred earlier this year, Martin Fitzpatrick Jr., head of the
department's Office of Transportation, said Thursday.
   Fitzpatrick also defended USDA export policies and programs
which have helped trigger a rebound in farm commodity exports.
   A study released by Fitzpatrick showed a severe disruption of
grain shipments in the United States this year through mid-April
because of shortages of covered hopper cars used by railroads.
   The study was requested by Reps. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., and
Virginia Smith, R-Neb. Fitzpatrick said he planned to cite the
study further at a hearing on Monday, May 2, in Kansas City, Mo.,
conducted by a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee.
   Fitzpatrick said the actual number of cars available for grain
movement has been both shrinking and aging since 1982 when the last
significant number was added to the railroad fleet.
   Also, there has been a large surge in export wheat sales under
the department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP, during the
past few months. Big sales to the Soviet Union, in particular, have
added to the railroad grain traffic.
   Under EEP, exporters can sell wheat or other designated
commodities to an approved foreign country at reduced prices and
then collect subsidies from USDA in the form of government-owned
surplus grain or other agricultural products.
   Fitzpatrick said car shortages meant some local elevators were
unable to take delivery of grain from farmers, grain merchants had
difficulty completing sales, and railroads hiked rates and
restricted use of cars in certain markets.
   Also, he said, the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
``received limited response'' to its weekly auctions of surplus
wheat because of the car shortages.
   Fitzpatrick was asked by a reporter whether the rail car
shortages had interfered with shipments of grain to seaports to the
extent that ships were kept waiting for grain to load.
   ``We do not believe that to be the case, as a general rule,'' he
said. But there may have been ``some specific circumstances'' what
that happened in the last six months. ``It's not a trend, it is not
a significant problem down the road,'' Fitzpatrick said.
   Although reasons are not clear why the hopper car situation has
improved the last 10 days, Fitzpatrick noted that export demand has
slackened somewhat and delivery dates have eased. Also, he said,
railroads had received overbookings for cars from grain companies,
and many of those now are being reconciled.
   Fitzpatrick said that it will take pressure from Congress, farm
groups, the grain trade and USDA to settle the rail car situation.
Ideally, he said, shippers and the railroads should sit down under
auspices of the Interstate Commerce Commission and resolve the
problems.
   The ICC, he said, has the authority to force a settlement.
Fitzpatrick was asked if he thought the ICC was dragging its feet.
   ``All I would say to you is the ICC has full authority to
resolve this issue,'' he said. ``It's been almost six years that
they have had it on their table, so you draw your own conclusion.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm policy could be improved worldwide by
making government support to farmers independent of acreage and
production levels, says the National Center for Food and
Agricultural Policy.
   This policy of decoupling would lead to ``more efficient
production of agricultural goods and lower production costs when
compared to current farm policies,'' the center reported Thursday.
   Some form of decoupling for American farmers has been advocated
unsuccessfully in Congress for a number of years. One example would
be to sign up farmers in a crop program and provide benefits
without tying them to specific acreage or production levels.
   As defined by the center _ a part of the independent, non-profit
Washington-based think tank, Resources for the Future _ decoupling
would mean ``providing government support to farmers in ways that
do not distort production, prices, consumption, resource allocation
or trade.''
   Decoupling doesn't set well with some farm groups. The National
Farmers Union, for example, says it is tantamount to putting
farmers on welfare by substituting direct federal payments for
price supports.
   A statement issued by NFU at its recent annual convention said:
``Farmers want federal program payments to help recover their cost
of producing food. These payments are actually subsidies to
consumers that pass through the hands of farmers.''
</TEXT>
