<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     04-29 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Pulitzer Winners Compose for Ballets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two ballets with music composed by Pulitzer
Prize-winners for the New York City Ballet's American Music
Festival were premiered this week at the New York State Theater.
   Charles Wuorinen, who won the Pulitzer for music in 1970,
conducted Thursday night's premiere of his ``Five,'' written for
cello and orchestra. Cello soloist Fred Sherry's part was often
spiky, without obvious melody or beat, but always listenable.
   Jean-Pierre Bonnefoux, a member of the New York City Ballet from
1970 to '80 and chairman of Indiana University's dance department
since 1985, choreographed in neo-classic style.
   He has his men in gray and women in silver-gray and he moves
them in diagonal patterns and wedge shapes. When Jock Soto lifted
Maria Calegari, she seemed to float. Michael Byars and Damian
Woetzel had some high jumping and several times danced with seven
women around them.
   Wednesday night saw the premiere of ``Tanzspiel'' by Ellen
Taaffe Zwilich, who won the Pulitzer Prize for music in 1983. The
company's co-ballet master in chief Peter Martins choreographed.
   This plotless dance lacked that inner pulse that makes one
movement seem to follow another logically.
   ``Tanzspiel'' had some lovely romantic dancing for Kyra Nichols
and Lindsay Fischer. Martins proved again that he knows how to fill
a stage with dancers. But ``Tanzspiel'' doesn't flow. The music is
ominous much of the time and Fischer often has grim movements in
dim light. There were exits where applause obviously was expected
but there wasn't any.
   Also Wednesday, the company beautifully danced ``Glass Pieces''
choreographed by Jerome Robbins to Philip Glass. ``Glass Pieces''
makes a better impression with each viewing. Miss Nichols and Soto
danced with superlative virtuosity in ``Stars and Stripes,'' George
Balanchine's choreography to John Philip Sousa.
   Thursday's program began with ``Jubilee!'' danced by fresh,
proficient students at the School of American Ballet. Joseph
Duell's choreography to Hershy Kay's music was charming but
repetitious; he should have used less of the music.
   ``Calcium Light Night'' is a series of dazzling modern solos
choreographed by Martins in 1977 to music by Charles Ives. Soto and
Heather Watts were the impressive performers. The evening ended
with the dazzling Darci Kistler and Robert LaFosse, convincing as a
tapdancer, starring in Balanchine's dance to Richard Rodgers'
``Slaughter on Tenth Avenue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
