<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham     04-29 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Can't Pay Mecham Impeachment Expenses Without New Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's attorney general said Thursday
that the state cannot pay former Gov. Evan Mecham's $200,000 legal
bill from his impeachment trial without a new law authorizing such
action.
   Legislators said Thursday they almost certainly will not pass
such a law.
   A spokeswoman in Mecham's office said the former Republican
governor would not comment on the non-binding opinion issued by
Attorney General Bob Corbin, also a Republican, until Mecham and
his lawyers had a chance to review it.
   Two days after Mecham's removal April 4 in a Senate impeachment
trial, the Senate voted 16-13 to pay $202,433 to his attorneys,
Fred Craft and Jerris Leonard. At the time, supporters said it was
a ``healing'' gesture.
   But state Treasurer Ray Rottas balked at writing the check and
asked Corbin for an opinion on whether the payment was permitted.
   ``There is no authority to pay Evan Mecham's costs and
attorneys' fees,'' Corbin concluded. However, he told reporters
that the state could pay Mecham's expenses if a new law were passed
to authorize it.
   ``We are not going to pass, in my estimation, anything in either
house,'' said GOP Sen. John Mawhinney.
   House Speaker Joe Lane, also a Republican, said House
Republicans were not enthusiastic about paying either the legal
fees or Mecham's recall expenses.
   The former governor has asked the state to pay him $231,000 for
his campaign costs before a May 17 recall vote aimed at his removal
was canceled.
   Mecham was convicted by the Senate of trying to thwart a death
threat investigation and misusing $80,000 by loaning it to his auto
dealership. He faces a criminal trial May 19 on charges of
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
