<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget     04-29 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Doesn't Keep Congress From Arguing Over Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last fall's deficit-reduction agreement was
supposed to make this an easy year for passing a budget, but the
House and Senate have managed to get in an argument anyway.
   Talks between the chambers on a compromise $1.1 trillion
spending plan collapsed Thursday amid angry accusations of
bad-faith negotiating.
   ``That which I fear the worst has befallen me,'' said Senate
Budget Committee Chairman Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., who is retiring
after this year, citing ``burnout'' from his three terms.
   Chiles blasted House negotiators for sending an offer on the
fiscal 1989 spending plan not ``in the spirit of what we sent
you.'' He told the House, in colorful words usually impolite in
public meetings, it should not expect a response and should come
back with a new proposal.
   Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., the House budget chairman, took
offense.
   ``I'm not going to sit here and be told, `If you don't like what
we offered, then lump it,''' he said.
   Gray offered to negotiate through the weekend, but Chiles said
he was heading back to Florida for next week, when the Senate is on
recess.
   ``When the House makes an offer that moves as far to the Senate
as the Senate did to the House, send it to me by wire and I'll come
back,'' he told Gray.
   Another meeting was set for May 9 but Chiles warned: ``We'd
better get on our seersucker suits and turn on the air
conditioning. I think we're going into summer.''
   Last fall's deficit-reduction pact between President Reagan and
congressional leaders laid down the outlines for the budget for the
spending year beginning next Oct. 1. It settled what is usually the
biggest fight _ ``guns versus butter'' _ by providing specific
figures for overall military, foreign aid and domestic spending.
   The budgets approved by the House and Senate, however, took
slightly different approaches toward the domestic budget.
   For example, the Senate, led by Chiles, approved a bigger
increase in the space program, which is well-represented in his
home state. The House has refused to go along, favoring more
spending on housing and poverty programs.
   Another issue is a Senate plan to alter the White House
agreement to add more drug-fighting money. House members oppose
breaking the summit pact for drugs alone, and not aid for the
homeless and other needs.
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, senior Republican on the
Senate panel, said House ``nitpicking'' was threatening to ``make
an absolute joke out of this process.''
   ``We were supposed to have a year where the (budget) summit made
it easy,'' he said. Now, he said, ``we're about to destroy it.''
   The House and Senate must compromise on the budget before it
becomes the official guide for Congress' annual spending bills.
   Congress missed its April 15 deadline for completing the budget
resolution. If one isn't approved by the middle of next month the
two chambers will begin passing their spending bills without one.
   Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., a budget committee member, urged
that heads remain cool and emphasized that differences were not
great.
   ``All we've got to do is agree to have an easy time'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
