<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MethodistMeeting     04-29 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Methodist Meeting,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Wants God Personalized In Pronouns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly updated hymnal for United Methodists
has won preliminary approval at the church's governing general
conference _ except for some missing masculine pronouns about God.
   The objections arose over phrases in the accompanying psalter of
psalms, not the hymns themselves.
   Noting that in many cases masculine personal pronouns, such as
``he'' and ``him'' had been replaced by ``God'' or ``God's,'' the
Rev. Riley Case of Marion, Indiana, said:
   ``The truth is that this proposed psalter has no pronouns for
God. It is a depersonalized God. And the feeling in the trenches
will be that the Bible has been changed.''
   Harriett Olson of Morristown, N.J., countered that ``removing
pronouns is not depersonalizing God. It's calling God by God's
name.''
   The issue arose in a hearing Thursday of a legislative
committee. It voted to asked the conference to restore masculine
pronouns in 34 psalms in a lengthy section of them.
   The proposed hymnbook generally got the committee's solid
backing, including the hymns and accompanying prayers, readings and
rituals for communion, baptism, marriage and other observance.
   The conference, the top governing body of about 10 million
members, is concentrating in its early stages on committee
hearings, with most proposed legislation to hit the floor next week.
   Action on the hymnbook may come as early as Saturday by the 996
delegates, half clergy and half laity. The delegates represent the
country's second largest Protestant denomination, next to Southern
Baptists.
   The committee recommended replacing only one of the 624 proposed
hymns, asking that ``Lord of the Dance'' be substituted for ``Awake
O Sleeper.''
   Work on the new hymnbook, revising a 1966 edition, has gone on
for four years and involved Methodists around the country.
Grassroots reaction sometimes toppled committee decisions.
   The new book preserves 329 hymns from the old book, and includes
295 new ones. The lyrics, while using inclusive sexual terms for
people, retains customary masculine pronouns for God.
   But the section of psalms in some cases didn't do so, which
provoked the call for restoration.
   For instance, as in Psalm 46:6, the committee didn't like the
proposed phrase, ``God's voice resounds,'' in place of the usage in
the new Revised Standard Version of the Bible, ``He utters his
voice.''
   Masculine descriptions of God also is an issue in other matters
before the conference, including proposals to allow substitution of
``Creator, Redeemer and Sustainer'' for the traditional usage,
``Father, Son and Holy Spirit.''
   The conference has scheduled action Monday on controversial
proposals to eliminate stands terming homosexual practice
``incompatible with Christian teaching'' and banning active
homosexuals from the ministry.
   Criticizing the focus on homosexuality, Eric St. Clarke,
president of the Carribbean Council of Churches, said, ``There is
no talk about heterosexual sins. Why? Is there nothing else going
on in the church.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
