<DOCNO> AP880429-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LawyerComplaints     04-29 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lawyer Complaints,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Get Low Grades in Handling of Complaints Against Lawyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who complain about their lawyers are
out of luck in most states if they expect help from the agency that
is supposed to regulate the profession, a legal reform group says.
   A ``report card'' issued Thursday by HALT, a consumer advocacy
organization campaigning to reform the attorney discipline process,
gave most states surveyed an ``F'' in policing lawyers.
   ``Nobody is doing a good job _ the question is how bad,'' Kay
Ostberg, HALT's director of research and education, said at news
conference.
   But the American Bar Association, which says it also is working
for reforms, insists there have been improvements in recent years.
   ``I would say that most of the states are doing a reasonably
good job given the resources they have,'' said the ABA's Timothy
McPike, who handles matters involving professional standards.
   HALT says disciplinary agencies often have a conflict of
interest because they are run by lawyers and because the
disciplinary process itself is mired in secrecy. In many states,
the public never learns which lawyers are being investigated or the
outcome of the probe.
   The most common complaints are of excessive legal fees or an
attorney's neglect. Ms. Ostberg said disciplinary agencies don't
usually act unless the offense is shown to be excessive.
   She cited a 1986 ABA survey of 40 states which found that 54,605
complaints were received but only 1,146 or 2 percent resulted in
any form of public discipline. Ninety-five percent were dismissed
without any discipline.
   McPike says those numbers reflect that many complaints are not
serious enough to warrant action.
   ``Ninety percent of the complaints don't even make it past the
first screening. People complain because their lawyer didn't answer
their phone call fast enough,'' he said. ``You have to have a good,
strong case before you can take somebody's license from them.''
   HALT proposed speeding up the process of dealing with
complaints, opening records to the public and having non-lawyers
serve on independent commissions to monitor and investigate
complaints.
   McPike said that in 1985, the most recent year for which figures
are available, 20 states made disciplinary proceedings public after
it was determined there was probable cause to warrant the filing of
charges. Thirty-three states have non-lawyers serving on
disciplinary boards, he said.
   Complaints are handled on the state level by organizations
operated under the state's highest court. These organizations are
run as arms of state bar associations or as separate disciplinary
governing boards.
   The HALT survey, conducted during February and March, graded
disciplinary agencies in five categories: whether the agency is
subject to public review or control, allows public access to its
proceedings, makes disciplinary records public, encourages the
filing of complaints and has a ``fair and responsive'' disciplinary
process.
   Thirty-three states and the District of Columbia responded to
the survey. The rest of the states did not respond.
   HALT gave each state that responded a ``final grade'' based on
the five criteria:
   Alaska, D; Arkansas, F; California, D+; Colorado, F;
Connecticut, D; District of Columbia, F; Florida, F; Hawaii, F;
Idaho, F; Illinois, F; Kentucky, F; Maryland, D; Massachusetts, F;
Minnesota, D; Mississippi, F; Missouri, F; Montana, F; Nevada, F;
New Jersey, F; New Mexico, F; North Carolina, F; Ohio, F; Oregon,
C; Pennsylvania, F; Rhode Island, F; South Carolina, F; Tennessee,
F; Texas, F; Utah, F; Vermont, F; Virginia, F; Washington, C-;
Wisconsin, F; Wyoming, F.
</TEXT>
