<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-29 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHALTO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baptist minister who gathers his flock
with automatic, pre-recorded phone messages says the best thing
about his new telecomputer is that it always turns the other cheek.
   ``It takes no breaks for lunch or a drink of water. If somebody
hangs up, it doesn't get mad,'' said the Rev. Charles West. ``One
person can't make the calls this machine does in the same time
frame.''
   The telecomputer is programmed to dial phone numbers and deliver
West's message of the day to his congregation at the First Baptist
Church in Bethalto.
   If a dialed number isn't answered, his machine will redial every
30 minutes for three hours. If it gets a busy signal, it will
redial every five minutes for 30 minutes.
   The message is changed every Saturday.
   West concedes that a taped message sounds impersonal, but said
it's a good way to keep in touch with his growing congregation of
525 members.
   ``People are actively involved in their own lives,'' he said.
``The church used to be the center of community life, but not any
more.''
   On the day before Easter _ when daylight savings time began _
the church members got this call:
   ``Hello, this is Pastor West calling. I trust you're ready for
Easter. Don't forget to turn your clocks up.''
   The call also offered information about church services, and had
room for parishioners to leave a message.
   West hopes to reach non-parishioners and invite them to attend
First Baptist with the telecomputer, which can be programmed to
call every phone number in Bethalto and the surrounding area.
   The pastor believes he could get two new members out of every 20
calls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Are you an easy mark for door to door
salesmen? Do you lose receipts for cash down payments? Do you buy
wrinkle cream from mail order companies?
   These are the types of questions players face in a new board
game called ``Market Place,'' produced by the Delaware Division of
Consumer Affairs.
   ``We use nuts and bolts as the game pieces because the game
deals with the nuts and bolts of consumer affairs,'' said Nancy
Hebner, division spokeswoman.
   The game was developed as ``a good way for people to increase
their knowledge about the pitfalls of being a consumer,'' Mrs.
Hebner said.
   The object of the game is to be the first to reach the money
tree in the middle of the game board. Players advance around a
winding track on the board by drawing a card and following its
directions.
   Cards that can make players move back one space say things like
``You spent $40 for miracle weight loss pills that `melt away fat
while you sleep.''' Or how about ``You didn't read the fine print
of the record club or book club offer.''
   Cards that can help a player advance one or two spaces include
``You always get three written estimates before hiring a roofing
contractor,'' ``You send all formal complaint letters by certified
mail,'' and ``You never give out your credit card number to sales
people who call you on the telephone.''
   The directions on the cards are based on calls the division
receives daily from consumers, Mrs. Hebner said.
   ``It's a simple game, but if people follow instructions and
think about what they're doing, it will probably save them a lot of
money and a lot of grief in the years ahead,'' Mrs. Hebner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
