<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JetBlast-Boeing     04-29 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Blast-Boeing,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Officials Baffled by Jet Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jet Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blast that ripped a huge hole in an Aloha
Airlines jetliner over the Pacific Ocean appears to be unlike any
previous accident involving Boeing planes, say officials of the
aircraft company.
   Tom Cole and David Jimenez of Boeing Commercial Airplanes, the
main Boeing Co. subsidiary, said Thursday night they had received
only sketchy reports of the explosion, which ripped off the top of
the fuselage just behind the cockpit to about the wing, injuring 60
people and leaving one person missing.
   Both executives said there were no fuel lines or other potential
sources for an explosion in the first-class cabin, just behind the
cockpit, where passengers on the Boeing 737-200 reported that the
blast occurred.
   ``The fuel is in the wing, the engines are in the wing and the
fuel lines are all right there,'' Cole said in a telephone
interview from his home.
   Even in the extremely unlikely event that a turbine blade tore
loose from one of the two engines and ripped into the fuselage in
mid-flight, it could not hit forward from the wing and the effect
would be nothing like what happened to the Aloha plane, he said.
   ``To have it just explode in the air is just unheard of,'' Cole
said. ``I think this is a very unusual circumstance that is not
related to any other accidents we have had.''
   FBI agents were sent from Honolulu to check the possibility that
a bomb might have been put on the plane, said FBI spokesman Robert
Heafner.
   Jimenez, also interviewed from his home, said the plane was one
of nine 737-200s delivered to Aloha in the late 1970s.
   The 737 series is Boeing's smallest jetliner and the company's
all-time best seller, with total orders for 2,031 planes as of
Thursday. Cole said 35 to 37 737s have either crashed or been
disabled by terrorists, lightning or other means.
   The first 737-200 was put into service in April 1968, and nearly
1,100 remain in use today, Cole said. It can carry as many as 120
passengers, depending on the seating configuration, and has a range
of 2,600 miles.
   The 200 was the second version of the 737s and costs $17 million
to $22 million each. Production of the model has ceased, with the
last 737-200 to be delivered later this year, Jimenez said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
