<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra Bjt   04-29 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Changes Demeanor, But Not Threat To Toss Out Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judge Gerhard A. Gesell's angry charge that
the Reagan administration was impeding the trial of Oliver North
and three Iran-Contra co-defendants was a performance familar to
lawyers who frequent his courtroom.
   A day after Gesell accused the administration of intentionally
withholding classified documents that he says the defendants were
entitled to see, the veteran federal judge calmly acknowledged the
government's fears about disclosing some of its most sensitive
secrets.
   Having angrily said Wednesday that ``a stone wall is being built
up between this court and the trial,'' Gesell took the bench in
U.S. District Court on Thursday and discussed the problem in milder
tones.
   He blandly described it as an ``obstacle caused by concerns in
the government generally concerning the confidentiality of
documents'' and offered ``to see if I can be of any help to this
situation.''
   The switch in the judge's courtroom demeanor was described by
one lawyer as ``typical Gesell _ bark, bark bark, meow, meow,
meow.''
   Another lawyer, who also did not want to be personally
associated with a comment about a sitting judge, said Gesell
``blows hot and cold.''
   Despite his changed demeanor, Gesell did not retreat Thursday
from his earlier threat to dismiss the case unless the relevant
classified documents are shown to the defense and made available
for use at trial as evidence.
   That possibility is a very real one, particularly if independent
counsel Lawrence E. Walsh is unable to persuade the CIA, the State
Department or other national security agencies to declassify
sensitive documents Gesell decides are needed as evidence for the
defense.
   ``The government is obliged to make all relevant information
available in some reasonable way to the defense and using the
monolithic term `government' might not be appropriate where the
independent counsel really does not call the shots,'' said Richard
Ben-Veniste, a former Watergate prosecutor.
   Lawyers for North, former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter and businessmen Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord, will be looking closely for material they
can predict won't be declassified.
   As former guardians of some of the nation's most sensitive
secrets, North and Poindexter are in a unique position to help
their lawyers find evidence that is beyond the court's reach.
   A successful search of the 300,000 pages of sensitive material
collected by Walsh could lead to dismissal of charges they
conspired to illegally divert profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales
to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   At an earlier hearing, Gesell referred to the complicated
procedures for handling sensitive documents and remarked that North
``knows more about the methods than those in the classification
system.''
   With secret documents deemed relevant and admissable as evidence
``you end up with the double D's: declassify or dismiss,'' said
defense lawyer E. Lawrence Barcella Jr., who once prosecuted
anti-terrorism cases for the Justice Department.
   ``I don't know of any case since the Classified Information
Procedures Act was passed not quite 10 years ago that has ever had
the volume of relevant classified material that this one does,'' he
said.
   The law contains elaborate procedures for determining whether
classified material is relevant evidence for the prosecution and
the defense. If the government won't declassify a document, it
allows for deletions of secret material of substitution of
summaries to enable the introduction of relevant evidence.
   But not all documents can be easily altered or summarized and
Gesell said he won't spend much time on that process, particularly
since Walsh says 50,000 pages are relevant to the case.
   ``What is the government going to do, or the judge going to do
if the government says `we can't declassify this, It is just too
sensitive'?'' Barcella said.
   The problem is particularly acute in the Iran-Contra case
because ``the essence of some of the crimes that are charged is
classified activity,'' he said.
   Joseph diGenova, who recently resigned as U.S. attorney here,
noted that ``it may very well be that some of that stuff is so
sensitive under no circumstances should it be released.''
   And if Gesell is forced to dismiss the charges because there is
too much classified evidence, ``so be it,'' diGenova said. ``That
was how the statute was designed. That is the way it is supposed to
work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   James Rowley covers the federal district and
appeals courts in Washington.
</TEXT>
