<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0866 04-29 0945</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0866,0964</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Chess,' A New Musical By Tim Rice and ABBA, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with other reviews; no PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life is just a game played out on a big
checkered board, or so they seem to be saying in ``Chess,'' the
heavy-handed British musical hit that lumbered into Broadway's
Imperial Theater on Thursday night.
   In this case, it's the theatergoers who are checkmated, trapped
for more than three hours in a cold and unappealing musical that
ranks as one of the season's biggest disappointments.
   That's surprising considering the show boasts a provocative,
tuneful score with lyrics by Tim Rice and music by Benny Andersson
and Bjorn Ulvaeus, two members of the pop group ABBA. But the
songwriters are shortchanged by director Trevor Nunn and playwright
Richard Nelson who have fashioned a musical that is big on metaphor
and short on credibility, not to mention entertainment.
   The plot, apparently reworked a bit from the London production,
is a romantic triangle involving a volatile and vulgar American
chess champion (Philip Casnoff), his Soviet opponent (David
Carroll) and the American's second (Judy Kuhn), a Hungarian refugee
who falls for the Russian at the drop of a rook.
   The American is sort of the John McEnroe of chess. The
champion's manners _ and politics _ are somewhere to the right of
Genghis Khan. His distastefulness dulls one point of this love
triangle, making it hard for the audience to wonder who will end up
with whom, let alone who will win the big match.
   The triangle eventually becomes a quartet when it is revealed
that the Russian has a wife (Marcia Mitzman) back in Moscow. She
doesn't show up until the second act, and by then the story has
bogged down completely.
   The three chess players are manipulated by an assortment of CIA
and KGB agents as well as public relations types who sing and dance
their way through the show. Everyone is the pawn of someone else, a
soap opera message Nelson reiterates with numbing frequency.
   Nunn, who previously worked wonders on ``Cats,'' ``Les
Miserables'' and ``The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby,''
falters with this show. Like ``Les Miserables,'' ``Chess'' relies
on a turntable to make the musical move. But it doesn't work as
well.
   Set designer Robin Wagner provides a series of gray,
concrete-like columns that glide, swivel and turn around the stage.
Their perpetual motion eventually becomes monotonous and even
irritating.
   Much of the time, the characters just stand on stage and shout _
at each other or toward the audience. There's not much Nunn can do
with these argumentative moments, but when a number cries out for
some musical movement, it doesn't get any help.
   Consider the exotic song ``One Night in Bangkok,'' a sizable pop
success several years ago, and virtually thrown away here in an
embarrassing flesh-peddling scene that looks like it was borrowed
from a summer stock revival of ``The World of Suzie Wong.''
   The show has been cast with strong voices, even down to the
smallest roles. At a result, many of the songs soar in spite of the
story. Miss Kuhn has a radiant voice, and when she doesn't push it,
the sound embraces the theater. Her quiet moments are the best,
particularly ``Heaven Help My Heart,'' a delicate solo, and ``I
Know Him So Well,'' a duet of commiseration that Miss Kuhn sings
with the Russian's neglected wife.
   The songwriters also have provided some memorable music for the
men, particularly the bitter ``Pity the Child,'' which contains
Rice's finest lyrics. It's an explanation by the American grand
master as to why he turned out to be such a rotter. Casnoff
succeeds too well in conveying the character's miserable
personality.
   Carroll, who possesses an even better voice, manages to make the
Russian more than a milquetoast, not an inconsiderable achievement,
considering Nelson's laborious plot. The performer brings the
overlong first act to a thrilling conclusion with a ringing anthem
to his homeland.
   As good as the score is, there is too much of it. The
songwriters added several songs for the American production,
including ``Someone Else's Story,'' one number that has likely pop
potential. But less would have been more.
   The costumes by Theoni V. Aldredge are undistinguished,
all-purpose modern clothes that are remarkably ordinary and, in the
case of Miss Kuhn, unflattering. David Hersey's lighting at least
tries to bathe Wagner's dozen or so behemoth columns in a soft,
humanizing glow.
   It's that humane, personal quality which is missing from the
rest of the production. The musical revels in its political message
and its conceit of a chess game as a microcosm of real life. Not
even the fine handiwork of its three gifted songwriters can make
the sledgehammer symbolism of ``Chess'' palatable.
   In other reviews:
   Howard Kissel writes in the Daily News that Chess is ``a show
without a game plan. ...
   ``The characters are cliches, and not even appropriate ones. ...
Neither of the love stories is emotionally involving. ... Visually
`Chess' is drab. ... The show is shrilly overamplified. ...
   ``The lingering question ... is why anyone imagined
international politics was something to sing about.''
   In The New York Times, Frank Rich writes: ``Rather than
condescend to throwing the audience a bone of genuinely romantic or
melodramatic entertainment _ or even providing a tense chess game _
the authors pass the time pontificating about politics in sweeping
generalities reminiscent of Mr. Rice's `Evita.' ''
   Referring to ``the musical's metaphorical equation of chess and
war,'' Rich says: ``War is hell, and ... `Chess' sometimes comes
remarkably close.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
