<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Cheese Recalled Because of Bacterium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says the
importer of e Castello Danish Blue Cheese has been recalled its
product because some samples showed a bacterium that can cause
flu-like symptoms.
   The agency said Thursday more than 2,000, 35-ounce pieces of the
cheese sent to distributors in New York, New Jersey, California,
Florida, Illinois, Minnesota, Mississippi, Texas, Massachusetts,
Pennsylvania, North Carolina and Oregon are being recalled.
   They recalled cheeses were in cartons coded TCU213 and the
individual pieces have the lot number 02X on their wrappers.
   The cheese was made by Tholstrup Cheese in Copenhagen, Denmark,
and imported by Tholstrup Cheese USA of Warren, N.J.
   The FDA said the bacterium, Listeria monocytogenes, occasionally
can be life-threatening to pregnant women and their fetuses, frail
elderly people and others with weakened immune systems.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Measure Expanding Services To Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed a
multibillion-dollar education measure expanding services to
students.
   In a signing ceremony on Thursday, Reagan said the measure
``reauthorizes and improves a wide variety of federal programs at
the elementary and secondary school level.''
   More than half of the $8.3 billion authorized in the bill will
go to disadvantaged children at risk of failing.
   It contains new programs to prevent dropouts and help high
school students with weak skills, and greatly expands drug abuse
education and magnet schools. New money also was earmarked for
math, science and foreign-language programs.
   The largest single program in the measure will pay for tutoring
and other services to disadvantaged children who are in danger of
failing academically.
   Other initiatives in the bill include $50 million for ``Even
Start,'' to jointly educate poor preschool children and their
illiterate parents; $50 million for dropout prevention
demonstration projects; and $200 million to improve basic skills of
high school students.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congressman Says HUD Sees Defeat in Effort To Cut Aid to Cities</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With Rent Control
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York congressman says an attempt by the
Reagan administration to cut off millions of dollars in federal aid
to cities with rent control has virtually been defeated.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., on Thursday revealed what he said
amounted to an admission of defeat in a letter from Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr.. The letter said
the administration would propose legislation for fiscal 1989 to
restrict rental rehabilitation grants to areas without rent control
laws.
   ``The restriction cannot go into effect until legislation has
been adopted by Congress and signed by the president,'' Pierce
wrote.
   In January, the Office of Management and Budget had suggested
making the change through federal regulation. But HUD spokesman
Jack Flynn said his department ``has always maintained that it
would require legislation'' to change the grant program.
   ``The letter is a carefully worded admission of defeat,''
Schumer said of Pierce's comments. ``Administration officials first
tried to impose their callous plan through regulation because they
knew legislation to interfere with local housing laws would stand
no chance in Congress. Once they saw that Congress would not let
their regulation go into effect, they backed off.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Lendl Olympic Bill, But There May Be No Room On
Team</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to make tennis star Ivan Lendl an
American citizen in time to play for the U.S. Olympic team in Seoul
this summer is moving swiftly through Congress, but the team may
have no room for the world's No. 1 player.
   The House Judiciary Committee on Thursday approved the special
immigration bill for Lendl, which would waive the five-year period
permanent residents are required to wait before receiving
citizenship.
   But the chief spokesman for the U.S. Tennis Association said the
team has already been selected and that it is highly unlikely a
player would be bumped to make room for Lendl even if the Czech
native receives U.S. citizenship and clears another series of
procedural hurdles to become eligible.
   ``This would put us in a very difficult situation,'' said Ed
Fabricius, director of communications for the association. ``I
don't see it happening. We've already selected the team.''
   Lendl, 28, the world's No. 1 ranked tennis player, is a native
of Czechoslovakia, but has lived in Greenwich, Conn., since 1981
and has adopted the United States as his home. Lendl won his
permanent resident status last year and has personally lobbied
lawmakers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Althea Gibson Donates Wimbledon Trophies to Smithsonian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five Wimbledon trophies won by Althea
Gibson, the first black American tennis champion, will be housed at
the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History.
   ``Who could have imagined? Who could have thought?'' the
60-year-old Gibson said at the Smithsonian ceremony where she
presented the trophies Thursday. ``Here stands before you a Negro
woman, raised in Harlem, who went on to become a tennis player ...
and finally wind up being a world champion, in fact, the first
black woman champion of this world.''
   Gibson described herself as ``a born athlete,'' noting her 200
bowling average and membership in the Mysterious Five girls'
basketball team before she met Fred Johnson, the one-armed tennis
coach who taught her to play.
   Gibson began competing in the U.S. championships at Forest
Hills, N.Y., in 1950 and at Wimbledon in 1951, but it was not until
1956 that she began to win major tennis tournaments throughout
Europe, including the women's doubles championship at Wimbledon.
   For the next two years Gibson captured both the singles and
doubles championships at Wimbledon and was voted the Woman Athlete
of the Year for 1957 by The Associated Press.
   Although the trophies will be held in storage, a Harry C. Lee
tennis racket and a tennis dress she used in one of her
championship matches were placed on public view immediately.
</TEXT>
