<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CholesterolAwareness     04-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cholesterol Awareness,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fewer Than One In 10 Americans Knows Cholesterol Level, Study
Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you know your cholesterol level,
congratulations. Most Americans don't.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported Thursday that
only 6 percent of the adults surveyed in 32 states last year could
recall what their cholesterol levels were.
   ``People don't know their numbers,'' said Dr. Patrick L.
Remington, a CDC cholesterol specialist. ``We've got a long way to
go to get people to know their numbers.''
   The federal government's Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance
System regularly asks people about their health and behavior. Last
year, for the first time, interviewers asked randomly selected
adults in 32 states and the District of Columbia about their
cholesterol.
   Less than half the respondents, 47 percent, had ever had a
cholesterol check at all. Less than half of those people, or just
19 percent overall, said they had been told what their cholesterol
level was. And of those people, fewer than one-third, or only 6
percent overall, remembered what the level was.
   ``In the past, a doctor might do a cholesterol check during a
checkup, look at the reading, and tell the patient, `You're
fine,''' Remington said. ``What we're encouraging is for patients
to say, `I'd like to know what my number is.'
   ``And not only should you know your number, but you should know
what it means.''
   A cholesterol level of below 200 _ measured in milligrams per
deciliter of blood _ is considered ``desirable,'' according to the
CDC. More than 200 is considered ``borderline high,'' and over 240
is ``high.''
   Although the survey respondents' cholesterol could not be
independently checked, most people who claim to know their
cholesterol ``do a very good job,'' Remington said. ``And if they
don't know the exact number, they may be able to classify
themselves'' as high or desirable, he added.
   Evidence about the links between cholesterol and heart disease
has grown in the past decade, the CDC noted in its weekly report.
Government researchers believe a 25 percent reduction in
cholesterol can cut a person's risk of heart disease in half.
   Remington said cholesterol specialists want people to know their
exact numbers to avoid misconceptions. An old rule of thumb said
that anything under a figure of 200-plus-patient-age was OK, but
``that's obviously passe,'' he said, citing the current standards.
   In the 32 states and the District of Columbia, the percentage of
people knowing their cholesterol ranged from 1 percent in New
Mexico to a high of 9 percent in Maine, Maryland and Washington
state.
   The percentage of respondents who had ever had a cholesterol
check at all ranged from 29 percent in New Mexico to 57 percent in
Maryland.
   The margin of polling error for the surveys differed from state
to state and question to question, but ranged from 1 percent to 4
percent.
   Differences from state to state ``may reflect differences either
in the availability and use of ... cholesterol testing or in the
respondents' awareness of the results,'' the Atlanta-based CDC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     04-29 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Celebrates 87th Birthday, Reflects On Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people shouted ``Banzai'' and waved
Japanese flags as Emperor Hirohito, the world's oldest and
longest-reigning monarch, appeared briefly on his palace balcony
today to mark his 87th birthday.
   The emperor's birthday is a national holiday.
   ``Thank you for celebrating my birthday with me today. I am
happy that so many of you have come today. I hope you will all have
a happy future,'' Hirohito said from behind bullet-proof glass in a
speech carried live on national television.
   It was his second public appearance since he underwent surgery
last September to bypass a tumor blocking his digestive tract.
Doctors later said the growth was not malignant.
   Hirohito, once worshiped as a living god, also spoke to
well-wishers at the Imperial Palace grounds on New Year's Day.
   Nobuyoshi Shimane, an accountant in Tokyo, was one of the
estimated 35,000 who came in three shifts under a drizzling rain
today and stood in a palace courtyard to see the emperor in his
annual birthday appearance.
   ``I think this will be the last chance to see him because of his
advanced age,'' Shimane said.
   Hirohito has been on the throne since Dec. 25, 1926.
   Despite rumors of ill health, Hirohito appeared relatively
strong today, although he shuffled slowly as he walked. He was
accompanied by Crown Prince Akihito and Princess Michiko and other
members of the imperial family. Missing was Empress Nagako, 85, who
suffers back and leg ailments.
   In a news conference marking his birthday, the emperor said he
was recovering well from surgery and answered questions about his
memories of World War II.
   ``After all is considered, the war was my most unpleasant
memory. I am pleased with people's efforts for peace after the war.
Hereafter, I hope the people do not forget this matter and protect
peace,'' Hirohito said.
   He refused to say what caused Japan to enter the war in the
first place, saying, ``I do not want to answer the question because
this will involve criticism against persons.''
   Foreign reporters were not alowed to attend the news conference,
which was conducted Monday but not released until today. The
remarks were carried in Japanese by the Kyodo News Service and
translated by The Associated Press.
   During two previous news conferences for foreign reporters _ the
last 13 years ago _ the emperor expressed his personal sorrow for
``certain things'' that happened during World War II.
   But he said he acted as a constitutional monarch before and
during the war and did not play a personal role. He also denied
planning the Pearl Harbor attack, but left many other questions
unanswered.
   During this year's news conference, Hirohito praised Yoshihiro
Tokugawa, his former grand chamberlain who retired earlier this
month at the age of 81 after serving for more than half a century.
   ``He protected recordings of the emperor's announcement of
defeat in the war (from soldiers who intruded into the Imperial
Palace on Aug. 15, 1945). With his language abilities, he prepared
well for my friendly visits to Europe and the United States so that
my visits were successful.''
   Soldiers had planned to seize the recording so the war could
continue. They beat Tokugawa with a pistol, but he refused to say
where the recording was hidden. When the disk was finally played,
it was the first time most Japanese heard their emperor's voice.
   During that broadcast, Hirohito urged his subjects ``to open an
era of grand peace for the generations to come, by suffering the
insufferable, bearing the unbearable.''
   However, Hirohito never used the words ``surrender'' or
``defeat.''
   Hirohito also said in the interview that it would take him a
long time to complete his research in marine biology, his favorite
hobby.
   He said he had replanted an endangered plant species and ``it is
growing well because the imperial garden is similar to forest
land.''
</TEXT>
