<1ST_LINE>u a PM-JetBlast-Passengers     04-29 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Blast-Passengers,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passengers Prayed as Crippled Jetliner Flew 15 Minutes to Reach
Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jet Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAHULUI, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers aboard a stricken Aloha
Airlines jetliner prayed and sang hymns while the plane wobbled 25
miles to an emergency landing after an explosion blew away part of
the forward passenger cabin's overhead.
   ``There was big bang when it happened and everybody looked up
and we were looking at blue sky,'' Bill Fink of Honolulu said
Thursday. He was in row 18, not far from the Boeing 737's forward
cabin where the explosion occurred.
   ``Everybody screamed,'' said passenger Dan Dennin of Honolulu.
``However, it was very brief _ the panic. The explosion happened,
the rest of the plane was intact, and we did not go into any
unusual attitudes or anything like that.''
   Sixty people were injured, two critically, and a stewardess was
missing in the explosion aboard the jetliner, which landed at
Kahului Airport with one engine aflame and about 15 to 20 feet of
its front cabin exposed. The plane carried 89 passengers, five crew
members and an air traffic controller.
   ``I think that people realized the plane was still flying and
they quickly went about the business of doing whatever they could
do to save their lives,'' Dennin said. ``I think we flew for almost
15 minutes with half an airplane, so we were all well aware of what
was going on.''
   Fink and Dennin praised the cabin crew for helping calm the
passengers, some of whom hung on to one standing stewardess so she
would not be sucked out of the plane by the howling wind.
   Another stewardess, Clarabelle B. Lansing of Honolulu, who
worked for the airline for 37 years, apparently was swept from the
plane, officials said. An air and sea search coordinated by the
U.S. Coast Guard failed to locate her. The search was scheduled to
resume at first light today.
   ``Well, I think the stewardess (Mrs. Lansing) had just picked up
the microphone to start talking,'' when the explosion occurred,
Fink said.
   Another passenger, Alice Godwin of Boulder City, Nev., said the
wind was so strong she was thankful no infant was aboard the plane
because the child would have been blown away.
   Ms. Godwin said that after the explosion she put on a life
jacket and placed her head between her knees.
   ``We all prayed,'' Ms. Godwin said. ``As long as those engines
were running, the more secure I felt. I sang all the hymns I knew.
That kept me busy.''
   ``I'm alive! I'm alive!'' David Jackson of Hawaii shouted as a
nurse pushed his wheelchair through the hospital.
</TEXT>
