<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfRdp     04-29 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Ship Attack Off Iranian Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said today its warplanes raided two
vessels off the Iranian coast, resuming attacks on commercial
shipping in the Persian Gulf after nearly a month of quiet.
   Baghdad Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the warplanes staged
two raids late Thursday, hitting ``a very large maritime target and
a large maritime target,'' a usual reference to supertankers and
tankers.
   The broadcast quoted an unidentified military spokesman as
saying the planes rerturned safely to base after scoring ``accurate
and effective blows.'' He said the missions were designed to
``destroy the oil supplies of the aggressors who use the oil
revenues to prolong the war.''
   There was no immediate confirmation of either attack from
gulf-based shipping executives.
   Iran never acknowledges Iraqi attacks on vessels ferrying its
oil between the Kharg island oil terminal at the northern tip of
the gulf and safer facilities in the southern part of the waterway.
   Iraq has claimed sinking Iranian warships in the gulf during a
land thrust earlier this month to recapture the Faw peninsula in
southern Iraq.
   But the last confirmed Iraqi attack on a commercial vessel was
March 30, when the Cypriot-flagged Anax was damaged in an air raid
about 70 miles south of Kharg.
   Iran is known to have attacked at least seven ships between
April 12-23.
   The so-called ``tanker war'' is an offshoot of the Iran-Iraq war
that began in September 1980.
</TEXT>
