<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WheelchairDeath     04-29 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wheelchair Death,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheelchair-Bound Man Dies In Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man crippled by multiple sclerosis died
after his power wheelchair caught fire while other wheelchair-bound
residents of a home for the disabled looked on in horror,
authorities said.
   Basil A. Vlahopulos, 37, died Wednesday night before
firefighters arrived at Hollister House. The building's automatic
sprinkler system doused the flames.
   The cause of the fire is undetermined, but is believed to be
accidental, fire investigators said.
   Nina Dalton, a wheelchair-bound neighbor of Vlahopulos', said
she watched as a woman and a man in a wheelchair opened a door
found smoke pouring from the apartment where Vlahopulos lived.
   ``When the fire alarms went off, it scared me to death,'' Ms.
Dalton said.
   Vlahopulos came to Cincinnati from Greece planning to learn to
be a family counselor. In 1980, he was diagnosed as having multiple
sclerosis and he was in a wheelchair a year later.
   But Vlahopulos earned a doctorate in counseling from the
University of Cincinnati. His sister, Maria O'Hearn of Norfolk,
Va., said Thursday her brother worked with agencies that help the
handicapped.
