<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Election     04-29 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Election,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Give Edge to Mitterrand After Debate With Chirac</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand was judged today the
winner of an acrimonious debate with rival conservative Premier
Jacques Chirac televised 10 days before voters return to the polls
for the presidential runoff.
   Thirty-two percent of television viewers gave the socialist
president the edge and 24 percent said Chirac had won Thursday
night's debate. Twenty-one percent called it a draw, 23 percent had
no opinion.
   The poll of 800 adults was conducted immediately after the
debate by the private firm CSA for the newpaper Le Parisien and
Radio France. No margin of error was given.
   Often biting and sarcastic, the debate was the first between
Mitterand and Chirac since they began sharing power in March 1986.
The two drew on detailed figures and weaved sophisticated arguments
in attacking each other's policies.
   Newspapers across France featured the debate on their front
pages today.
   ``With this face to face debate, Francois Mitterrand and Jacques
Chirac confirmed that cohabitation has been more difficult than
either had let be understood before,'' the provincial daily
Courrier de l'Ouest said.
   The leftist daily Liberation said the debate: ``recalled a
quarrel on a luxurious school playground.''
   The conservative Le Figaro, like most newspapers, said it showed
the men to be fairly evenly matched.
   Chirac used the debate to make a clear appeal to the extreme
right, arguing that halting immigration was ``an imperious
necessity.''
   Mitterrand agreed that immigration must be reduced but said he
would not take part in a ``witchhunt of immigrants.''
   For Chirac, 55, the key to winning the May 8 runoff election
could lie with capturing the votes of those who favor Jean-Marie Le
Pen, leader of the extreme-right National Front.
   Le Pen, running on an anti-immigration platform, achieved a
stunning success in Sunday's first round of the presidential
elections, garnering 14.4 percent of the vote, compared to 19.9
percent for Chirac.
   Mitterrand, 71, won with 34 percent.
   On Sunday, Le Pen is to advise his sympathizers how to vote on
May 8.
   He has publicly ruled out votes in Mitterrand's favor. But he
has said he is looking for concrete signs Chirac and his
neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic would implement policies in
keeping with the National Front's goals.
   Thursday night's two-hour forum, in which two well-known
journalists asked the questions, was billed as the major political
event.
   The number of immigrants ``must of course be reduced,''
Mitterrand said during the exchange. But he added that immigration
was ``an exaggerated problem, sometimes purposely complicated ...
that cannot be treated without nuance.''
   ``I will not participate during this presidential election in a
witchhunt of immigrants,'' he said.
   ``Very simply, immigration must be stopped because France no
longer has the means to give work to foreigners,'' Chirac said.
``It is an imperious necessity.''
   Using a term dear to Le Pen, he added, ``It's a problem of
national identity, of the French way of life.''
   ``You didn't wink there, did you?'' Mitterrand interjected.
   The president appeared to command the first half of the debate,
but Chirac responded confidently and with animation on the subjects
of immigration, taxes and security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
