<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0502,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants, Indian Troops Exchange Fire At Golden Temple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with exchange of gunfire. PICKS
up 2nd graf pvs: ``Villagers captured...'' TRIMS thereafter. Adds
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants inside the Golden Temple
exchanged gunfire with paramilitary troops holding one of their
comrades outside the holy shrine today, security officials said.
   One woman visiting the temple was injured in the clash, police
said.
   Police were put on alert throughout the city to counter any
further violence, said Baldev Singh, the police superintendent.
   Nand Lal, commander of the paramilitary Central Reserve Police
Force, said the militants opened fire after a patrol spotted and
tried to stop a wanted Sikh radical as he was heading for the
shrine.
   ``As soon as the gunmen inside the Golden Temple saw us holding
one of their comrades, we were fired upon,'' Lal said. The patrol
returned the fire, he said, and rounds were exchanged for about 20
minutes.
   The Sikh militant, whose name was not given, escaped during the
melee and took shelter inside the temple complex, Lal said.
   The militants were recently reported building bunkers and firing
ports inside the complex, which includes the temple, offices and
guest quarters. It is Sikhism's holiest shrine.
   Security forces have entered the complex on occasion, but they
generally try to avoid it because their presence would offend
devout Sikhs.
   On Thursday, Sikh extremists killed 16 people in separate
attacks throughout Punjab, including raids on two villages and a
farm, security officials said.
   Villagers captured one of the gunmen, but police said the
suspect committed suicide by taking a poison capsule while in
custody, the United News of India reported.
   The slayings raised to at least 850 the number of killings
blamed on Sikh militants in Punjab this year.
   Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed
to the extremists' 6-year-old guerrilla campaign for an independent
homeland in the northern state.
   S.S. Virk, deputy inspector general of the paramilitary Central
Reserve Police Force, said as many as 12 Sikh militants took part
in a raid late Thursday on the village of Ranpura, 30 miles south
of Amritsar.
   He said the gunmen ordered Hindus out of their homes and fatally
shot five of them, including a 17-year-old girl.
   Virk said a letter left at the scene claimed responsibility on
behalf of the Bhindranwale Tiger Force, one of a dozen Sikh
militant groups operating in Punjab.
   Two other Hindus were killed Thursday night by Sikh gunmen in
Mohamadpura village, 18 miles west of Amritsar, police said.
   Sikh radicals also were blamed for a raid on a Sikh farmer's
house in the district late Thursday in which four people, including
a 12-year-old boy, were killed.
   Five other deaths were reported in scattered attacks.
   Sikhs, whose 500-year-old religion has roots in Hinduism and
Islam, claim they are discriminated against by India's majority
Hindus. They make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million
population but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
