<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CopShot     04-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cop Shot,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ballistics Test: Cop Killed by Fellow Officer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police sergeant killed during a raid on an
alleged cocaine den was shot by one of two decorated police
officers, not the pregnant woman blamed immediately after the
shootout, authorities said.
   ``In these kinds of incidents, it's a little difficult to piece
things together,'' Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo told a news
conference Thursday. ``We got most of our information from the
captain, who unfortunately was the last one in the room.''
   Police backed off their earlier version after ballistic tests
showed the bullet that killed Sgt. John F. McCormick came from one
of the two Smith & Wesson revolvers used by police officers who
were at the shooting.
   The bullet was recovered during an autopsy on McCormick, 43, a
19-year veteran who was nearing retirement. McCormick was shot in a
room outside the bedroom where suspect Mercedes Perez scuffled with
police.
   The fatal shot was fired by either Officer John Huvane, 26, or
Officer James Curran, 28, police sources said. Curran has won 35
awards for his performance on duty; Huvane has received six awards.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward, who angrily demanded the
death penalty for Ms. Perez after Wednesday's shooting, was
``distressed and concerned'' when he learned a police bullet had
killed McCormick.
   But Colangelo defended Ward, who was not at Thursday's news
conference. ``The police commissioner yesterday made a generalized
statement, which still holds true,'' Colangelo said.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch said Ms. Perez was still to blame for the
death, and ``the tragedy is a police officer was killed as a result
of the actions taken by drug pushers. ...
   ``So, while she didn't shoot him directly, she's directly
responsible,'' Koch said.
   Ms. Perez, who was shot twice during the spray of gunfire, gave
birth to a baby girl after being taken to Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center. Both mother and child were in stable condition.
   Ms. Perez has been charged with attempted murder, aggravated
assault, criminal possession of a controlled substance and a
weapons violation.
   McCormick, of the Bronx Narcotics Unit, was among a team of
police officers who broke down the door of Ms. Perez's apartment in
upper Manhattan. A search warrant said they were looking for 4{
pounds of cocaine.
   A subsequent search of the apartment turned up scales, four
vials of crack, one marijuana cigarette, half an ounce of white
powder believed to be cocaine, $2,000 in cash, drug sale records
and an assortment of bullets, police said.
</TEXT>
