<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FakePast     04-29 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fake Past,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Convict Who Lived 27-Year Lie Acquitted Of Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former convict who hid his
criminal past for 27 years while he became a civic leader and
businessman was acquitted of fraud and grand theft charges brought
by investors upset over his fake background.
   Robert L. Gipson, 70, had been living under an assumed name for
years and had settled into a busy civic-oriented life here before
his past was disclosed three years ago.
   ``The nightmare is over,'' Gipson said after the Wednesday
verdict in Pasco Circuit Court that cleared him of three theft
counts and one of fraud.
   Gipson's past caught up to him in 1985 when he was revealed to
be convicted felon Gilbert E. Sharby, arrested in at least seven
states on various charges ranging from grand larceny to
impersonating a federal officer.
   The disclosure cost Gipson his job on the Pasco County
Republican Party Executive Committee and left him scrambling to
restore a carefully nurtured reputation as a good citizen. He
gained a federal pardon and one from Nebraska authorities, then had
his civil rights restored by former Gov. Bob Graham.
   But in January 1987, Gipson was arrested after three investors
in his Port Richey locksmith business claimed they wouldn't have
parted with $9,000 had they known Gipson's background.
   The trial focused on whether Gipson deceived three people he met
through the Republican Party at a November 1984 stock sales meeting.
   The state claimed that through his false identity, Gipson
misrepresented himself to the investors. Among other credentials,
Gipson claimed he had degrees from Harvard University, the
University of Kansas and the University of California at Berkeley.
   Etta Breitenbach invested $5,000, Sylvia Wolan $1,000 and
Charles Weber $3,000.
   Defense attorney Marc Salton did not dispute evidence that
Gipson, a former local Chamber of Commerce executive, was a high
school dropout who had a gift of gab and a lengthy record. But he
maintained that Gipson's past was irrevelant to the investors'
commitments in Gipson's Suncoast Locksmiths Corp.
   ``You don't have to have any education to run a locksmith
business,'' Salton said. ``You have to be a good locksmith.''
   He characterized the unhappy investors as ``people who didn't
make as much money as they wanted to make.''
</TEXT>
