<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     04-29 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Democrats Meet Amid Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bitterly divided Christian
Democrats gather today to consider who will be their presidential
candidate and how to prevent the governing party from falling apart
at the seams.
   The centrist party of President Jose Napoleon Duarte, among
America's closest allies in the hemisphere, is suffering one of the
worst crises in its 28-year history.
   It was resoundingly defeated by the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, in legislative and municipal
elections March 20 and appears on the verge of collapse.
   About 1,800 party members are meeting at a hotel in this capital
to discuss who will be their candidate in presidential elections
scheduled for next March.
   Duarte on Tuesday called on the two main rivals _ Julio Rey
Prendes and Fidel Chavez Mena _ to abandon their candidacies for
the sake of party unity. The bitter year-old battle between them
for the nomination has left at least two people dead and several
wounded.
   Chavez Mena and Rey Prendes, both party founders and former
Cabinet members, rejected the president's suggestion on Wednesday
and said they would continue their efforts.
   Duarte proposed Abraham Rodriguez, the party's unsuccessful
presidential candidate in 1967 elections, as a unity nominee.
   The party congress was to have endorsed a candidate in a
non-binding vote and a party convention of 220 delegates had been
expected to then make the final, binding decision.
   But Duarte urged members of the congress and delegates to the
convention not to make their final choice today. It remained to be
seen if his suggestion would be heeded.
   Duarte, who is limited by law to one five-year term, warned that
``we are threatening our very existence from within the party.''
   Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas, the Roman Catholic archbishop of
San Salvador, seconded that assessment during a talk with foreign
journalists Thursday.
   He said the Christian Democrats should resolve the crisis ``in a
peaceful manner if they want to survive as a party. Otherwise the
division will lead them to self-destruction.''
</TEXT>
