<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Fire,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Victims Camp Along Railroad Tracks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 people left homeless by
one of the capital's biggest fires in 40 years pitched camp along
railroad tracks near their razed shantytown, officials said today.
   About 300 children were evacuated to an elementary school in
Pandacan district, the crowded neighborhood where officials said
Thursday's fire destroyed more than 1,000 shacks and left 10,000
homeless.
   Relief workers distributed rice and canned fish today and set up
a community kitchen for the victims, social welfare officials said.
   An arson investigator, Sgt. Jimmy Molina, said police were still
trying to determine the cause of the fire.
   Brig. Gen. Ernesto Madriaga, the fire chief, said the flames
destroyed a candy factory warehouse and virtually every building in
a 25-acre area. The fire broke out about 1{ miles from the
presidential palace.
   Madriaga said the blaze was ``possibly the biggest in Manila
since World War II,'' and that a shift in the winds prevented the
fire from reaching a nearby oil storage area. His deputy said
flames spread within eight yards of the state-owned Philippine
National Oil Co.'s depot.
   Firefighters were unable to move trucks into the crowded
shantytown alleys and concentrated their efforts on preventing the
fire from reaching the oil storage area.
   Troops armed with M-16 rifles were sent to the fire scene after
residents, angry that firefighters were not trying to save their
homes, pelted firetrucks with stones.
</TEXT>
