<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Ferries     04-29 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ferries,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voyagers Warned To Avoid Ports As Strike Enters Fourth Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vacationers heading for the European continent by
water were warned today to expect delays of up to 18 hours as a
long weekend approached and a ferry strike entered its fourth day.
   Problems on the busy Dover-Calais route across the English
Channel began this week when crews of the Sealink car-and-passenger
ferry company refused to cross picket lines mounted by workers of
another ferry firm, P and O, who have been on strike for three
months.
   Sealink management and representatives of the 24,400-member
National Union of Seamen met today through government mediators to
seek a compromise after Sealink sought to curb the strike by having
the union's assets seized.
   Sealink said only its French-crewed ships were sailing, halving
the number of daily round trips to eight.
   No delays were reported this morning, but police cordoned off
lanes of the highway into Dover to accommodate trucks likely to be
stranded.
   ``Today and Saturday are expected to be very busy,'' said a
Sealink statement. It warned that motorists with bookings could
experience delays of about six hours later today.
   The statement said bus passengers could be delayed for up to 18
hours, while truck drivers faced even longer waits.
   Hovercraft services between the English port of Folkstone and
the French port of Boulogne were normal but packed, said Sealink
spokesman Russell Stenhouse. The longer Newhaven-Dieppe and
Weymouth-Cherbourg routes linking Britain and France also were
reported to be unaffected, but Sealink's Wales-Ireland crossings
were disrupted.
   The action came on one of the travel industry's busiest
weekends. Monday is a legal holiday in Britain and Sealink usually
carries 150,000 passengers between Britain and France.
   P and O seamen have been on strike for 12 weeks, resisting an
ultimatum on new pay rules and working conditions.
   This week, P and O strikers mounted pickets at Dover, the
world's busiest ferry port, and Sealink crews have refused to cross
them since Tuesday.
   A woman who crossed the line had ``scab'' daubed on her home in
red paint.
   Under union-curbing laws enacted by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's government, secondary picketing is illegal, and
employers can sue the union involved for damages.
   On Thursday, Sealink made the first move in that direction by
asking the High Court to order the seamen's union assets seized.
   The union threatened an all-out strike if its funds were seized.
   Judge Michael Davies urged Sealink and the union to ``talk, and
talk fast'' before he adjourned the case for a day.
</TEXT>
