<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police On Alert For Terrorist Attack on U.S. Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELES CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stepped up security
after reports that Palestinian terrorists were planning to bomb a
U.S. air base and bars frequented by American servicemen, officials
said today.
   Angeles City police chief Lt. Col. Orlando Macaspac told
reporters the attacks were to be carried out during the weekend by
eight Palestinians, and that four of them already were in Angeles
City, 50 miles north of Manila.
   Macaspac said the report was relayed Thursday to the Philippine
Constabulary's Metropolitan District Command by the Israeli
intelligence service Mossad.
   He said Clark Air Base and bars frequented by U.S. military
personnel were the intended targets of the attacks.
   Clark officials could not be contacted immediately for comment,
but Macaspac said command officials were discussing security
arrangements with Filipino and American authorities on the base.
   There was no unusual security activity visible on the base.
Macaspac said Filipino police had stepped up patrols around the
city, especially in housing areas for American personnel.
   Spokesmen for both the Israeli and U.S. embassies said they had
no knowledge of the purported Israeli intelligence report. A
sergeant who answered the telephone at Clark's information office
declined comment.
   U.S. officials had tightened security around Clark, Subic Naval
Base and four smaller installations after communist rebels killed
three Americans and a Filipino in attacks near Clark in October.
   In December, there were also reports that Palestinian terrorists
had slipped into the country for a series of attacks here, but none
materialized.
   Officials say there are up to 30,000 Palestinians in the
Philippines, many of them in the country illegally. They include
students, businessmen and tourists, officials say.
</TEXT>
