<DOCNO> AP880429-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0828EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     04-29 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Urge West To Exploit Vietnam's Need for Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian guerrillas said the West
should exploit Vietnam's urgent requests for food aid to increase
pressure for the withdrawal of 140,000 Vietnamese troops from
Cambodia.
   ``If aid is given ... it would be like a transfusion of fresh
blood into the body of a blood-starved Vietnam writhing in its
death throes, thus reviving it and enabling it to carry on its war
of aggression in Cambodia,'' said the text of a guerrilla
broadcast, obtained today from a Western embassy in Bangkok.
   ``We appeal to them instead to take advantage of this moment ..
. to bring greater pressure to bear on it and force it to quickly
end its war of aggression in Cambodia,'' said the Tuesday broadcast.
   The broadcast came over the radio of the Khmer Rouge, the
largest of three guerrilla groups fighting Vietnamese troops that
invaded Cambodia in late 1978. A Western diplomat, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, recently said Vietnamese officials appealed
for aid in a March 14 meeting in Hanoi with representatives of
foreign countries and relief agencies.
   According to official Vietnamese media reports, bad weather,
disease, and insect plagues also have seriously damaged the rice
crop early this year.
   Rice is the staple crop in Vietnam. Aid officials say they see
no signs of starvation on any significant scale but there is
widespread malnutrition.
   The Western envoy said the Vietnamese officials asked for
fertilizer and insecticides to protect this year's harvests. The
envoy said that would cost about $100 million and it was doubtful
the international community would be able to provide it.
   The envoy, based in Hanoi, spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier this month, Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach
suggested to visiting Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., that food aid
could be offered to peasants in areas where they were asked to help
search for remains of Americans killed in the Vietnam War. The
State Department said it was outraged at the suggestion the two
issues should be linked.
   The Khmer Rouge broadcast said the food shortages were due not
to mistakes in agricultural policy, as the Vietnamese government
has claimed, but to Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia in an attempt to
dominate all of Indochina.
   The Khmer Rouge governed Cambodia from 1975 to 1978, and an
estimated 1 million to 2 million of Cambodia's 8 million people
died from Khmer Rouge executions, famine and civil unrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
