<DOCNO> AP880429-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BillyGraham     04-29 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Billy Graham,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billy Graham Sees Better Future For China's Christians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American evangelist Billy Graham said today he
was encouraged by the growing but still limited religious freedom
in China and was optimistic about Christianity's future in the
communist nation.
   Graham also said he had been unable to substantiate reports that
a Chinese itinerant preacher who spreads the Gospel in defiance of
the state-sponsored church was arrested after arriving in Beijing
to hear the Southern Baptist minister.
   Graham, speaking at a news conference in this British colony at
the end of his 16-day visit to China, said he contacted high-level
Chinese authorities and the U.S. Embassy to get information about
the reported arrest of Xu Yongzhe, but received neither
verification nor denial of the report.
   ``My wife and I have been praying daily for him if he indeed has
been detained,'' Graham said. He said he could not intervene in the
matter but could ``relate my feelings about it and I have already
done that.'' He did not elaborate.
   According to the director of the Chinese Church Research Center
in Hong Kong, Xu was arrested April 16 after traveling to Beijing
from central China to hear Graham. The center has links to
Protestants in China who worship in unofficial ``house churches.''
   A source in Beijing with links to preachers outside the
state-sanctioned church has confirmed Xu's arrest.
   Graham said he did not know Xu and had not heard of him before
his reported detention.
   The 69-year-old Graham spoke with government leaders and
Christians from inside and outside the official Chinese church
during his first China trip, which took him to Beijing, Nanking,
Shanghai and Canton.
   Christians form a tiny minority of China's 1 billion people. The
official Protestant church has about 4 million members, as does the
official Catholic church, which does not recognize Vatican
authority.
   Millions of other Christians are believed to practice their
faith independently in the privacy of their homes.
   Graham said some people told him of persecution during the
ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, during which religion
was banned. Graham also heard of Christians still suffering
discrimination in income, housing, education and social status
because of their faith.
   The evangelist said he was ``encouraged that there is now a
limited, I'd like you to underscore the word `limited,' ... measure
of religious freedom and that thousands of churches have reopened
in recent years. I expressed the hope there will be steady progress
toward greater religious freedom for all believers.''
   Graham said he was ``very optimistic about the future of the
Christian faith in China. Christians in China could be salt and
light in Chinese society, and could be a great moral and spiritual
force for good in the nation where God has placed them.''
   Graham said he would like to return to China but indicated he
probably would not speak before huge stadium crowds as he has done
in many of the nearly 70 other countries he has visited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
