<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoriegaIndictment     04-29 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Indictment,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Wins Legal Round in Cocaine Indictment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian Gen. Antonio Manuel Noriega doesn't have
to surrender to U.S. authorities in order to challenge his drug
indictment, a federal judge has ruled.
   ``The best way to avoid the appearance that this indictment has
assumed the character of a political proceeding, rather than a
legal one, is to determine its legal validity upon the arguments of
counsel,'' U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler said Thursday.
   The judge gave Noriega's attorney, Neal Sonnett, 10 days to
submit challenges to the Feb. 4 indictment. Hoeveler said he would
set a hearing date after the government responded.
   Sonnett hailed the ruling, which does not affect a separate
Noriega drug indictment in Tampa.
   ``I think it is an outstanding legal victory for Gen. Noriega,
and a well-reasoned opinion on the part of Judge Hoeveler,'' the
attorney said.
   The lead prosecutor in the case, Chief Assistant U.S. Attorney
Richard Gregorie, was traveling Thursday and unavailable for
comment.
   Gregorie has said that if Noriega wants to challenge the
indictment he should surrender himself.
   Noriega is accused in the 12-count indictment of taking at least
$4.6 million in payoffs from members of the Medellin Cartel to
protect cocaine shipments, launder money, supply drug laboratories
and shelter the Colombian gang leaders from law enforcement.
   Sonnett, who has traveled to Panama to meet with Noriega, cited
New York draft resister cases in which attorneys were allowed to
make arguments while their clients were in Canada.
   The judge agreed, noting that the Justice Department ``has not
yet sought extraditon of Gen. Noriega, and it does not appear
likely that it will seek extradition in the near future.''
   In another development, it was disclosed Thursday that the
federal prosecutor whose office issued the Feb. 4 indictment naming
Noriega will resign June 17 and rejoin his former law firm.
   U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner, whose office is responsible for the
southern district of Florida, the nation's busiest in terms of
caseload, will resign for personal reasons, said his executive
assistant, Ana Barnett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
