<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Takeshita     04-29 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Takeshita,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita Leaves For First European Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita departed for
Western Europe today to meet with leaders of Italy, Britain and
West Germany in a bid to improve political and trade links with the
region.
   The prime minister is making his first trip to Europe since he
became prime minister in November, although he has visited Europe
seven times in other capacities.
   Takeshita told reporters Wednesday that there are imbalances in
Japan's relations with Europe and the United States.
   ``In the area of trade, it is true that significant imbalances
still exist,'' he said. ``It is necessary for us to turn the
existing structure of an uneven triangle into a right triangle.''
   Japan's trade with the European Economic Community accounted for
less than 10 percent, or $28.9 billion of the country's total trade
of $305 billion in 1985. Trade with the United States amounted to
$71.1 billion or 23.3 percent of the country's overall trade in the
same year, according to Japanese figures.
   At the same time, trade imbalances between Japan and the EEC
countries continued to grow.
   In 1987, Japan chalked up a surplus of $20 billion in trade with
the EEC, according to Finance Ministry statistics. In 1986, it was
$16.7 billion.
   Bowing to pressure from the EEC and Britain to lower tariffs and
non-tariff barriers, such as taxes and restrictions, on imported
liquor and wine, the Japanese government decided in January to
revise its liquor tax system to boost imports of foreign liquor.
   Trade relations have improved in recent months.
   Between January and March this year, Japanese imports from
Europe increased by 52.3 percent, Takeshita said.
   ``We wish to further encourage this trend,'' he added.
   During his 11-day trip, the Japanese leader will meet with Pope
John Paul II in the Vatican on April 30, and his Italian
counterpart Ciriaco DeMita in Rome on May 2. Then he will fly to
London on May 3 to meet with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on
May 4.
   In London, Takeshita is scheduled to give a major speech on May
4 in a luncheon in The City, London's financial district, in which
he will outline his plan to have Japan play a larger role in world
affairs.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service said the ``Takeshita plan'' calls for
Japan to increase its official development assistance and to
provide money and personnel for United Nations peacekeeping forces.
   He will wrap up his tour with a meeting with West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl in Bonn on May 5 and hold a press conference
on May 6. He will leave Munich, West Germany May 8 and return home
on May 9.
   Takeshita is also sceduled to visit France, Belgium and the
Netherlands in early June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0087 </DOCNO>
