<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0475 04-29 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,580</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 7 grafs new material from Dukakis speech; edits thruout
to tighten; changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM W. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis
today urged President Reagan not to veto legislation requiring
companies to give notice before closing plants, telling union
members that workers ``deserve better from America.''
   ``I hope the president will take the time to think about the
three million American workers who lose their jobs in this country
every year through plant shutdowns,'' Dukakis said. ``In at least
half those cases, those plants shut down with little or no notice
to those most affected _ their own employees.''
   Dukakis referred to trade legislation passed by Congress this
week but which the White House says Reagan will veto because of an
amendment requiring notice before plants are closed. Republican
opponents say the measure does not belong in the trade bill and
would be undue government interference with business.
   ``These people are our neighbors,'' said Dukakis in prepared
remarks. ``They deserve better from their employers. They deserve
better from America.''
   Dukakis began campaigning in Ohio and Indiana where primaries
are scheduled next Tuesday.
   After taking a break back home in Boston following his huge
victory in Pennsylvania over his only remaining rival for the
Democratic presidential nomination, Jesse Jackson, Dukakis was
speaking to a meeting of Ohio labor leaders at the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 683 Hall in Columbus.
   He resumed attacks on corporate mergers and acquisitions which
he said provide profits for ``Wall Street pirates and corporate hit
teams'' while costing workers their jobs.
   Dukakis, who arrived in Columbus on Thursday night, had stops
today including a rally in Dayton and a visit to a high school in
Youngstown.
   Dukakis' backers here expressed confidence that momentum from
victories in New York and Pennsylvania will help him roll up a big
win in Ohio as well.
   State Sen. Harry Meshel of Youngstown, Dukakis' Ohio campaign
chairman, pointed to a statewide network of 170 public officials
supporting the Massachusetts governor. However, Gov. Richard
Celeste has not taken sides.
   Celeste was to appear with Dukakis but also planned to join
Jackson for a church service on Sunday in Cleveland. Jackson has
been in the state most of the week.
   Ohio has 159 delegates up for grabs Tuesday, with another 24 to
be added at the convention by various Democratic procedures.
   Before leaving for Ohio, the Massachusetts governor released
copies of letters sent to Reagan and congressional leaders urging
enactment of the trade bill.
   ``Mr. President, I believe that our record trade deficit
requires that we put partisan politics aside and take action that
will be in the best interest of all Americans,'' Dukakis said in
the letter. He said the bill ``will help return the United States
to a position in the world where we can once again compete
successfully with all of our trading partners.''
   At a news conference, Dukakis said he would make the trade bill
a major part of his attack on Bush if Reagan vetoes the measure.
   ``I think the issues of workers being laid off, what is
happening to the industrial base of this country, and the failure
of this administration to do much to deal with that and what a new
president would do to work hard with business and labor and
community leaders to restore our competitive edge and rebuild our
industrial base will be very much one of the major issues,'' he
told reporters.
   Dukakis has made the plant-closing issue a campaign theme in the
industrial states. He has called on Bush, the certain Republican
nominee, to publicly urge Reagan to sign the trade bill.
</TEXT>
