<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Gibraltar 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Gibraltar, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0516,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documentary Contradicts Official Account On IRA Guerrillas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher, Howe comments.
Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `Gerry Adams...' TRIMS thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today denounced a
television documentary that contradicted the official version of
the killing of three unarmed IRA guerrillas by British commandos.
   ``The freedom of people depends on the rule of law, a fair legal
system,'' she told a Japanese television interviewer. ``The place
to have trials is a court of law. Trial by TV or guilt by
accusation is the day that freedom dies.''
   Television authorities rejected a government request to delay
the broadcast, and the hourlong documentary ``Death on the Rock''
aired Thursday night.
   The program said the guerrillas died while trying to flee or
surrender to the commandos in Gibraltar. Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe had said the guerrillas ``made movements which led
security personnel to believe their lives were in danger.''
   Thames Television said it received scores of calls after the
broadcast, running about 3-2 against the decision to screen the
film.
   Howe called the broadcast ``grossly and wholly improper'' and
said in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview that it had
``inevitably'' been shown on satellite TV in Gibraltar, where it
might influence an inquest jury.
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, legal political arm of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army, said the allegations showed clearly
the guerrillas were ``summarily executed.''
   The Foreign Office said the Thames Television program featured
people due to testify at the inquest in Gibraltar and complained
that their accounts would influence the hearing. It had asked Lord
Thomson, chairman of the controlling Independent Broadcasting
Authority, to delay broadcasting the program.
   Thomson turned down the request, denied the documentary would
prejudice the inquest and said postponement would give the IRA more
``oxygen of publicity.''
   Thames TV said the documentary was the result of a seven-week
investigation which included interviews with 150 residents of
apartments overlooking the area where the guerrillas were shot
March 6.
   In the documentary, translator Carmen Proetta said she saw the
shootings from her apartment window in the British colony that
borders Spain.
   Mrs. Proetta said she saw three armed men in plainclothes get
out of a police car, jump over a metal barrier in the road and open
fire on two of the guerrillas, later identified as Mairead Farrell,
31, and Daniel McCann, 30.
   ``When they (Ms. Farrell and McCann) saw these men had guns in
their hands, they just put their hands up ... There was no chance.
I mean they went to the floor immediately, they dropped,'' Mrs.
Proetta said.
   She described the guerrillas' action in putting their hands up
as ``like giving themselves up.''
   Mrs. Proetta said that after the initial shooting, which she
said occurred without warning, ``a blond gunman bent down and with
the two hands he got his gun like that and went on shooting at
them.''
   Others described seeing the third guerrilla, Sean Savage, 24,
shot in the back as he tried to run away.
   Mrs. Proetta's account appeared to contradict Howe's March 7
statement to Parliament that the guerrillas were challenged as they
walked toward the nearby Spanish border and were slain because they
``made movements which led security personnel to believe their
lives were in danger.''
   The IRA said at the time that the guerrillas had been on
``active service,'' meaning they were planning an attack.
   The Gibraltar killings triggered a fresh outbreak of violence in
Northern Ireland in which nine people, including two British
soldiers, died.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
