<DOCNO> AP880429-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0527,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall As Cartel Talks Lag</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with ministers saying no
agreement was reached, comments by Santos; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`The oil ...' INSERTS new grafs 8-10 to UPDATE with latest oil
trading; picks up 6th graf pvs, `Prices have...' Also moving on
financial wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC talks aimed at shoring up oil prices
bogged down early today in a technical debate that one cartel
leader called a ``waste of time.''
   A nearly four-hour meeting over a proposal to cut oil exports in
conjunction with independent producers broke up early today without
any agreements, and leaders of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries said they would reconvene this evening.
   They said no agreements had been reached.
   Fernando Santos, the oil minister of Ecuador, told reporters
later that it was impossible to predict whether an accord could be
reached, since ``there's a wide divergence'' of views among the 13
OPEC members.
   The oil ministers are considering a proposal from six non-OPEC
oil producers to cut both groups' exports by 5 percent in an effort
to push OPEC oil prices back to $18 a barrel.
   The non-OPEC group says it will cut its exports only if OPEC
does likewise.
   But opinions differ sharply within the cartel over whether
further cutbacks are needed, and there are indications some members
_ including influential Saudi Arabia _ favor enforcement of
existing output quotas over new cuts.
   World oil prices continued sliding early today as the OPEC
leaders struggled to resolve their differences.
   On the European market, Brent crude oil from the North Sea was
down 35 cents a barrel, at $16.80, at mid-afternoon after having
lost 30 cents on Thursday. The U.S. oil markets hadn't yet opened.
   Traders said the declines reflected doubts that the oil
ministers' meeting would produce a concrete agreement on measures
designed to boost the oil market.
   Prices have fallen this year because supplies have risen faster
than demand.
   Most OPEC crudes are selling for $16 a barrel or less, although
oil traded in the West usually sells for more.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, June contracts for West
Texas Intermediate, the most widely traded U.S. crude, fell 29
cents to $17.98 dollars a barrel on Thursday after dropping 33
cents the day before. Prices on European markets fell about 30
cents a barrel on Thursday.
   Some industry analysts believe prices would rebound if OPEC
accepted the non-OPEC offer. But others doubt that OPEC could agree
on reductions large enough to make a difference in the global
balance of supply and demand.
   OPEC's opening debate focused more on differing views of the oil
market's supply and demand balance than on the merits of the
non-OPEC group's proposal, according to sources who spoke on
condition they not be identified by name or nationality.
   In an apparent effort to bridge the gap in these views, the oil
ministers instructed a team of experts from each member country to
meet today to assess the present and near-term market balance.
   Arturo Hernandez Grisanti, Venezuela's oil minister, told
reporters he was unhappy that time was being devoted to a meeting
of experts, which he said only would highlight the differing views
between OPEC countries.
   ``This is, in some sense, a waste of time,'' he said.
   Hernandez said one suggestion under consideration was to forego
the proposed export cuts in favor of recommitting the 13 members to
existing oil production quotas, which often are violated.
   ``We know that several countries have been overproducing for
years,'' he said, without naming the countries.
   ``...If we can have a full guarantee that these countries are
going to abide by their quotas, that would improve the market
situation. But I have a lot of doubt about that,'' he said.
   Iran was alone among the OPEC members in stating its clear
support for the non-OPEC offer. None have rejected it outright.
   Hisham Nazer, the Saudi Arabian oil minister, declined to say
whether his country favored the non-OPEC proposal, made Wednesday
by Mexico, Egypt, China, Oman, Angola and Malaysia.
   But Saudi King Fahd on Thursday bolstered the impression of many
industry analysts that he would not accept any cuts in OPEC
production or exports. He said the cartel's main goal should be to
stick to its existing production limits.
   ``I believe prices will go up if we adhere to the output ceiling
and convince non-OPEC producers of the feasibility of limiting
their production,'' he said in an interview published by a Kuwaiti
newspaper.
   Bryan Jacoboski, who was observing the OPEC meeting for the
investment firm PaineWebber Inc., said Fahd's statement was ``the
real nail in the coffin'' of expectations that the cartel would
accept the non-OPEC proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
