<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     04-29 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Ends in Cyanide Drug-Tampering Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By her daughter's account, Stella Nickell put
cyanide in pain relief capsules to poison her husband of 12 years
for as much as $176,000 in life insurance benefits.
   Mrs. Nickell, however, says she loved Bruce Nickell more than
money, and her defense lawyer notes that her daughter, Cindy
Hamilton, 28, came forward after pharmaceutical companies offered a
$300,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of whoever
was responsible for the tampering.
   A U.S. District Court jury will likely begin deciding between
those two accounts Monday in the nation's first
death-by-product-tampering trial.
   Testimony before the 12-member panel and Judge William Dwyer
ended Thursday after a government witness supported part of Ms.
Hamilton's version.
   Closing arguments were set for Monday, followed by instructions
to the jury and the start of deliberations.
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, is charged with five counts of tampering with
over-the-counter medicine, including two involving the death of her
52-year-old husband and Sue Katherine Snow, 40, in June 1986. Both
died after swallowing cyanide-laced capsules of Extra-Strength
Excedrin.
   Government lawyers claim she tampered with other pain-relief
capsules and put them on store shelves to cover up the killing of
her husband.
   The last witness, Katherine Parker, said she was rooming with
Ms. Hamilton in November 1985 when Ms. Hamilton reported what she
thought were her mother's plans.
   ``Cindy came home and said `Katy, do you know what my mother
just said to me? She asked me how much cocaine it would take to
kill a person,''' Ms. Parker testified. ``She said that her mother
had been talking about getting rid of her (step)father ... she was
getting tired of him.''
   Ms. Hamilton had testified Tuesday that her mother discussed
putting cocaine in Nickell's iced tea to make his death look like
an overdose.
   In cross-examination earlier Thursday, assistant U.S. attorney
Joanne Maida noted that shortly before Nickell's death, Mrs.
Nickell had twice written a bank to which they owed money to say
she was taking over the finances and that the couple's ``marriage
problems'' would soon be resolved.
   Mrs. Nickell responded that she loved her husband and did not
try to hide insurance policies, all signed by her, from FBI
investigators.
   She confirmed that she and her husband owed three banks and an
investment company $8,553 at the time, plus a lot more to clear
titles on their land and mobile home, but she denied that their
financial situation was getting worse and noted that both were
employed.
   Her lawyer, Tom Hillier, asked if she were responsible for the
crimes.
   ``No,'' she replied. ``The thought never entered my mind and
never would because I loved Bruce too much. There's no way I'd ever
think of getting rid of him.''
   The prosecution also introduced evidence showing that Mrs.
Nickell had checked out library books on poisonous plants in 1983
and 1984. She said she had borrowed the books to make sure that
plants on her rural property weren't harmful to her grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
