<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand 1stLd-Writethru a0508 04-29 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0508,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Dissolves Cabinet, Calls New Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Prem dissolving Cabinet and
Parliament and calling new elections.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda
dissolved his Cabinet and the Parliament today and called new
elections in a dispute over legislation to protect U.S. copyrights.
   The official Radio Thailand said general elections would be held
July 24.
   Earlier today, 16 Cabinet ministers belonging to the main party
in Prem's coalition government submitted their resignations after
failing to stop party dissidents from voting against the
government-backed bill to protect American copyrights.
   The Democrat Party ministers _ representing about a third of the
Cabinet _ resigned because ``they could not control'' the party
dissidents, said Col. Sanan Kachornprasat, the party's secretary
general.
   The radio announcement said Prem and would continue at his post
until the election.
   Prem, Thailand's longest-serving prime minster, has headed five
Cabinets since assuming his post in 1980. The last general election
was held in 1986.
   The dissolution of Parliament forestalled a probable opposition
motion to censure the government over its handling of various
issues, including economic problems and recent border clashes with
Laos. The censure motion had been expected May 9.
   The House of Representatives passed the copyright bill 183-134
on Thursday, but 32 legislators in the dissident group joined
members of opposition parties in voting against it.
   The dissidents said the legislation, which protects U.S.
copyrights of artistic and literary works, would force Thailand to
bow to U.S. bullying. The United States had indicated that it might
be forced to cut duty privileges for Thai imports if the measure
wasn't passed.
   Music and videocassettes and other U.S. products are widely
pirated in Thailand. The legislation is expected to be approved by
the government-appointed Senate.
   The U.S. Embassy today welcomed passage of the copyright bill,
although it didn't meet an American demand that it specifically
protect computer software. The legislation left that question to
the Thai courts.
   ``We are prepared to await the determination of the Thai courts
as to whether or not software is covered under the existing Thai
copyright law,'' said Embassy spokesman Ross Petzing. ``We believe
computer software should receive copyright protection.''
   The 67-year-old prime minister has been criticized for
indecision on a number of issues, but others have noted his
contribution to Thailand's general stability and economic progress
in recent years.
   The former military commander was preceded by a procession of
military-led coups and major government changes. Prem survived two
major coup attempts by dissident military officers in 1981 and 1985.
   But he has maneuvered quietly and deftly to undercut potential
opposition from the military and is widely believed to enjoy the
backing of King Bhumibol, the country's highly respected and
powerful monarch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
