<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LehderTrial     04-29 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests After Presenting 115 Witnesses in 22 Weeks in
Lehder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys, after listening to
22 weeks of government testimony and 115 witnesses, will begin
presenting their case Monday in the cocaine-smuggling trial of
Carlos Lehder Rivas.
   Edward R. Shohat, one of Lehder's two attorneys, said earlier
this week that the defense case may only take two weeks, but
estimates in this marathon trial have been notoriously conservative.
   When the jury selection started in October, attorneys said they
expected the trial to last from six weeks to three months. But,
counting jury selection and a two-week Christmas recess, the trial
has ended its 30th week.
   Lehder, 38, accused of being one of the leaders of Colombia's
violent Medellin cocaine cartel, and Jack Carlton Reed, 57, are
being tried on charges of conspiring to smuggle some 3.3 tons of
cocaine into the United States through Lehder's private island in
the Bahamas, Norman's Cay, from 1978 to 1980.
   The prosecution wrapped up its case shortly after noon Thursday
following the presentation of interviews Lehder gave earlier this
decade on Colombian radio and television.
   U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle had argued that the presentation
of the tapes was essential to his case, although U.S. District
Judge Howell W. Melton ordered references to Adolf Hitler and the
slaying of Colombian Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla edited
from the tapes.
   The judge denied motions from defense attorneys for directed
judgments of acquittal to the charges contained in the 11-count
federal indictment.
   In the tapes, the jury heard Lehder deny several times that he
was a drug smuggler.
   ``I have never admitted that I have dealt or done any business
with drugs,'' Lehder said in a jungle interview in 1985.
   In the same interview, however, he said, ``This is about
political action, and cocaine has become _ and marijuana has become
_ a revolutionary weapon in the struggle against North American
imperialism.
   ``Stimulants from Colombia are the Achilles' heel of
imperialism. That's why the persecution against us is not legal, it
is political. But I have never been arrested in possession of any
drug whatsoever.''
   The Colombian also made anti-American statements, calling the
United States ``a country guided by Playboy magazine ... guided by
a society, let us say, drunken on pornography.''
   He also opposed the extradition treaty that eventually resulted
in his arrest on the charges for which he is being tried.
   ``So then they say I conspired against the United States. I say
that not only did I conspire but that I conspire now and that I
shall continue to conspire until the day the .... extradition
treaty is canceled.''
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with being a member of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
