<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Reported Unaware Slain Armenian Terrorist Was in Athens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with government statement. Pick
up 6th graf pvs: `Police at...' TRIMS thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it didn't know
the leader of an Armenian terrorist group who was assassinated
outside his Athens home had lived in Greece for the past year.
   Agop Agopian was gunned down before dawn Thursday as he waited
for a taxi in front of his suburban apartment. Police sources said
Agopian lived in Greece for at least a year, posing as a Lebanese
businessmen. He was founder and chief of the Armenian Secret Army
for the Liberation of Armenia.
   ``Authorities in Greece didn't know his identity,'' government
spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said.
   Agopian also carried a South Yemen diplomatic passport in the
name of Abdul Mohammed Kasim.
   Kostopoulos said Agopian, who was not registered as a diplomat
here, had not been working in Greece.
   Agopian and a woman identified as his sister-in-law were
standing in front of Agopian's home when two masked men emerged
from a car.
   One man shot Agopian twice with a sawed-off shotgun and fired
again when the victim tried to run. The assailants fled. The woman
was unhurt.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the killing.
   The assassination could have been the work of a rival extremist
group, said Armenian sources in Athens who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Police at first identified the victim as 39-year-old Abdul
Mohammed Kashim, born in Aden, based on the South Yemeni diplomatic
passport he carried.
   ``He'd lived in Athens for at least a year _ possibly longer _
as Henri Titizian, but he traveled abroad very frequently on the
Yemeni passport,'' said a police source who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   But after reports from Paris said the dead man was the
long-sought leader of the terrorist group, his wife, Janil
Titizian, confirmed he was Agop Agopian, the Ministry of Public
Order said in a statement.
   Police said Ms. Titizian told them her husband recently arrived
from South Yemen and was on his way to Yugoslavia.
   The group, founded by Agopian in 1975, has claimed more than 60
attacks against Turkish targets, including the killings of about 30
Turkish diplomats and dependents in western Europe and the United
States.
   The Marxist organization seeks the foundation of an independent
Armenian state in eastern Turkey and vengeance for what they claim
was the massacre of 1.5 million Armenians by Ottoman Turks in
1915-1916.
   The Armenian sources said Agopian was born in Iraq in 1945, and
that his name was most likely a pseudonym.
   He ran the group from Beirut with funding from the Palestine
Liberation Organization and leftist groups but dropped out of sight
in July 1982.
   His group claimed responsibility for the July 1983 bombing of
the Turkish Airlines desk at Orly Airport in Paris that killed
eight people and injured 56.
   Agopian's former second-in-command, Monte Melkonian, formed a
splinter group called ASALA-Revolutionary Movement after the Orly
bombing, complaining that ASALA had abandoned its original policy
of focusing only on Turkish targets.
   ASALA has claimed only one attack in Athens, the killing of
Turkish diplomat Galip Ozman and his daughter in August 1980. The
group's political wing, the Armenian Popular Movement, has operated
an office in the Greek capital for several years.
   Turkish officials say 300,000 Armenians died after Ottoman
Empire officials deported the country's 1.4 million Armenians to
Syria during World War I. Independent historians say at least
600,000 Armenians died during the journey.
</TEXT>
