<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Award     04-29 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Award,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Human Rights Awards Slated For South Korean Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prominent South Korean dissidents
will be presented with the Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award in
a special ceremony here May 5, a South Korean human rights group
said today.
   Dissident Kim Keun-Tae and his wife, In Jae-keun, will each
receive an award to be delivered by representatives of the Robert
F. Kennedy Memorial Center for Human Rights, due to visit Seoul May
3-6.
   Kim has been in prison since his arrest in 1985, and In now
leads Mingahyop, an association of families of political prisoners.
   The dissident couple was to have received the 1987 Kennedy
awards in Washington. But the South Korean government refused to
allow the two to visit the United States, human rights group
members said in a statement.
   The U.S. delegation will include two daughters of slain Sen.
Robert F. Kennedy, Rose Styron of Amnesty International and Patt
Derian, former Assistant Secretary of State for Human Rights, the
statement said.
   The group plans to meet with South Korean government officials,
human rights activists, Cardinal Stephen Kim and opposition leaders
Kim Dae-jung and Kim Young-sam.
</TEXT>
