<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AcneDrug     04-29 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acne Drug,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Group Plans To Push For Stronger Restrictions On Accutane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group affiliated with Ralph Nader plans to
push the Food and Drug Administration to more severely restrict a
powerful anti-acne drug that causes birth defects, a doctor
representing the organization said today.
   ``We have an FDA with strong laws but weak enforcement,'' said
Dr. Sidney Wolfe of the Health Research Group of Public Citizen, an
organization that has long been critical of the FDA.
   ``American families are too important to be left to a Reagan
administration that seems to give deference to the drug industry,''
Wolfe said in an interview on NBC-TV's ``Today.''
   An FDA advisory panel recommended earlier this week that the
drug Accutane remain on the market because it is the only effective
cure for severe acne. But it urged that additional warnings be
added to new packaging to further discourage use by pregnant women
and that the FDA find a way to legally restrict the drug's
distribution.
   The FDA is not bound by the advisory panel's recommendations.
   Wolfe said Public Citizen would file a petition with the FDA to
implement strong restrictions and is considering filing a lawsuit.
He recommended that dermatologists who prescribe the drug be
required to sign a sworn statement that they will not misuse it.
   Accutane's manufacturer, LaRoche Laboratories of New Jersey, had
proposed new packaging that would more effectively warn against its
use by pregnant women.
   The manufacture acknowledges 62 U.S. cases of birth defects
caused by Accutane since the drug was introduced in 1982. Wolfe
said there could be several hundreds more and thousands of
abortions induced because of fear of the drug's side effects. A
confidential FDA memorandum reported last week by The New York
Times estimated that between 900 and 1,300 cases of birth defects
were caused by Accutane between 1982 and 1986.
   ``The company has sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
this drug and the FDA seems resistant to doing something that would
significantly reduce the sales,'' Wolfe said.
   ``It's a very important drug,'' he said, ``and the question is
why can't it be limited carefully to the smaller number of people
who really need it without giving it to a larger number of people
and allowing pregnant women to get the drug?''
</TEXT>
