<HEAD>Secret Service Agents Visit Dukakis Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Gov. Michael Dukakis may
soon get the Secret Service protection he has up to now rejected.
   On Thursday, the Boston Globe quoted an unnamed source and a
campaign aide confirmed that Secret Service agents recentl have
visited the Brookline home of the Massachusetts governor as
preparation for providing protection.
   The aide said the decision on whether to accept Secret Service
protection is still officially ``under review.''
   Dukakis has said Secret Service agents would make it difficult
for him to have personal contact with voters and he objected to the
intrusiveness of protection at home.
   The governor, who regularly travels by public transportation, is
protected by Capitol Police at the statehouse in Boston and was
protected by local police, including plainclothed officers, in New
York and Pennsylvania during those states' recent primaries.
   Presidential candidates, under federal law, do not have to
accept Secret Service protection.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top Foreign Policy Concerns: Drugs, Trade Imbalance, Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are just as concerned about drug
trafficking and foreign economic power as they are about
U.S.-Soviet nuclear weapons according to a recent survey.
   Given a choice of seven national security goals, 22 percent of
those surveyed picked combatting international drug traffic as the
No. 1 priority. Another 18 percent said correcting America's
growing trade imbalance was the most important goal. Reducing U.S.
and Soviet long range missiles was chosen by 15 percent of those
surveyed.
   The poll said 59 percent of the American people believe economic
competitors like Japan pose more of a threat to national security
than traditional military adversaries like the Soviets.
   The survey, issued Thursday, was conducted by a group that
includes pollsters for presidential candidates Michael Dukakis and
George Bush.
   Tom Kiley, who polls for Dukakis, said the Democrats are pleased
that the survey shows a ``broadening prism'' through which
Americans look at security issues.
   Fred Steeper, whose Market Opinion Research company works for
Bush, said it ``is a blow against a protectionist stance,'' that 61
percent of Americans chose ``improved efficiency'' as the key to
reducing the trade deficit compared to 24 percent who chose
``fairer trade practices.''
   It was the fourth poll in a 10-series survey called ``Americans
Talk Security.'' The polls are a collaborative effort by four
organizations, including Martilla & Kiley, of Boston, and Market
Opinion Research of Detroit. They are funded by Boston millionaire
Alan F. Kay, president of the Institute for Defense and Disarmament
Studies, a pro-nuclear freeze group.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Campaign Given Two Weeks to Give IRS Financial Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson's presidential campaign has
until May 12 to submit financial records in a federal investigation
of the tax-exempt status of the former television evangelist's
broadcasting network.
   U.S. Magistrate Rebecca B. Smith on Thursday extended a
show-cause order for two weeks for documents originally requested
by the Internal Revenue last December.
   Robert L. O'Donnell, attorney for Americans for Robertson, said
the records would be available within five days.
   ``We have not opposed any of the requests and have made records
available as quickly as possible,'' he said in asking for a
continuance of an order filed late last month.
   In addition to financial data, the IRS asked for copies of
fund-raising letters and ``records of any transactions with the
Freedom Council or Christian Broadcasting Network.''
   CBN was founded by Robertson who was its president until last
October, when he announced his candidacy for the Republican
presidential nomination.
   The Freedom Council was established in 1981 with seed money from
CBN, and sought tax exempt status from the IRS saying it was
created to educate Christians on how to get involved in politics.
   The organization received nearly $3 million from the network in
1985, according to former council officials and critics contend the
council, which disbanded in 1986 shortly after Americans for
Robertson was formed, acted as a front for the Robertson campaign.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Toy Gun Taken From Teen-Ager Before Jackson Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secret Service agents and Canton police
confiscated a plastic gun found in the knapsack of a high school
student entering a rally by Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson.
   Canton police Lt. Tom Thomas said Thursday although the toy gun
could not fire ammunition it could shoot plastic pellets and was a
convincing replica of a .357-caliber Magnum.
   Thomas said the unidentified teen-ager, was not held but said
the case would be referred to the Police Department's Juvenile
Bureau.
   Secret Service agents who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the teen-ager told them he forgot he had the plastic gun in his bag
when he tried to enter the Canton Civic Center.
</TEXT>
