<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 4thLd-Writethru a0537 04-29 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0537,0792</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Major Plant On Strike, Workers Say _ Government Denies It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UDPATE with government comments. Pick
up 4th graf pvs: `The strike...' Edits thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers today struck a heavy machinery
plant in southeastern Poland in an escalation of the nation's worst
labor unrest in six years, opposition leaders said.
   The government denied a strike had begun at the Stalowa Wola
plant and threatened to fire anyone who did strike.
   Thousands of steelworkers at the giant Lenin mills outside
Krakow continued their strike for a fourth day demanding higher pay
and union rights.
   Opposition spokesman Jacek Kuron in Warsaw said 21 Solidarity
activists were detained across the country today, an indication
communist authorities' tolerance for worker defiance was waning.
   ``The situation in Poland is not dramatic,'' government
spokesman Jerzy Urban said at a hastily called news conference. He
said ``an attempt to organize a strike'' failed at Stalowa Wola.
   Urban said plant management would fire any workers who took part
in a strike.
   Contacted by telex, the plant was repeating a recorded message
that work was ``going on normally'' and that a rally by workers had
ended.
   Labor Minister Ireneneusz Sekula said at the news conference
with Urban that the government would announce in a few days tax law
changes and other measures to allow enterprises to meet growing
worker pressure for higher pay. Consumer prices have gone up by 42
percent so far this year.
   Urban also said there had been an unspecified number of
``preventative detentions.'' He did not elaborate.
   The strike at the 18,000-worker machinery plant in Stalowa Wola
began with the first shift this morning, according to opposition
activists and the Rev. Edward Frankowski, a priest in the town 150
miles southeast of Warsaw.
   The priest said workers rallied outside plant headquarters.
   The police presence was heavy in Stalowa Wola and at least four
local Solidarity activists were detained, according to Frankowski
and Solidarity spokesman Zbigniew Romaszewski, who was in Warsaw.
   Strikers were demanding $50 monthly pay raises and the
reinstatement of dismissed Solidarity activists.
   Thousands of workers continued their occupation of the Lenin
steel mill, outside the southern city of Krakow.
   The strikers began their action Tuesday, demanding higher wages,
recognition of union rights and more money for retirees, teachers,
and industrial and health care workers nationwide.
   Strike committee member Maciej Mach said today that about 13,000
strikers were inside the steelworks, around which the Krakow suburb
of Nowa Huta was built in the 1950s. He said his committee had not
negotiated with management since talks broke off early Thursday.
   The steelworkers were warned Thursday that their strike was
illegal. Their leaders said management had threatened to use force
to end it.
   The head of the government-sanctioned union at the 32,000-worker
plant, Wladyslaw Sitkowski, said he planned to resume today talks
with management that began Thursday. Mach said the strike committee
rejected the official union taking any role in the dispute.
   Organizers said at least 16,000 people had stopped work at the
plant in Nowa Huta, or New Steel Mill, staying on premises for two
shifts and going home to rest for one.
   The government was clearly concerned the labor unrest might
spread. Sunday is May Day, international Labor Day and a
traditional time of anti-government protest in Poland.
   Alfred Miodowicz, a member of the ruling Communist Party
Politburo, was dispatched Thursday to the Lenin mill. He is
national head of the officially sanctioned trade unions.
   Deputy Prime Minister Zdzislaw Sadowski, who the official new
agency PAP said would appear on television to discuss the economy,
postponed a visit today to Washington to meet with International
Monetary Fund officials.
   Sadowski is chief architect of the government's effort to make
the economy more market-oriented through reforms that have included
the price increases.
   The unofficial strike committee at Nowa Huta, whose 16 members
include Solidarity activists, have demanded a 50 percent increase
of the average monthly pay of $105.
   It also said the $15 paid monthly in compensation nationwide for
recent price increases should be doubled for industrial workers,
teachers, health care workers and retirees.
   This week's labor unrest is the most serious in Poland since
strikes in 1980 over food price increases that spawned Solidarity
and brought down a government. The unrest ended with the December
1981 imposition of martial law.
   On Monday, transit workers in the northwestern city of Bydgoszcz
staged an 11-hour strike and won a 60 percent raise. A day later,
the strike began at the Lenin works.
</TEXT>
