<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Man Claiming to be Father of Mystery Toddler Contacts Authorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man claiming to be the father of an
18-month-old boy found wandering in traffic a month ago has
contacted authorities.
   The man, Theodore Kenneth Shirley of Zephyrhills, northeast of
Tampa, said he last had contact with the toddler last fall in
central Florida, Lakeland Police Detective Miles Watson said
Thursday.
   ``He said he was the child's father. And he provided information
that leads us to believe he could be,'' Watson said. If the
identity checks out, the reason for the separation probably will be
revealed as being domestic-related, the detective said.
   ``Apparently he heard about the case on the news. It triggered
his interest. And more things began to fit,'' said Watson.
   ``Little Kenny'' has been in protective custody since March 25
when he was rescued from traffic. Since photos of the child were
published last week, more than a dozen people have offered to adopt
him.
   The day after the boy was taken into custody, a man claiming to
be the toddler's uncle reported his 18-month-old nephew missing
from the same area.
   The man, Michael ``Smokey'' Kwil, told Lakeland police he first
saw the boy on March 23 in a bar. The child was with Kwil's
half-brother, Kwil told police. During the night the half-brother
borrowed a motorcycle and left for Washington state, Kwil said.
   Watson said although Kwil has told conflicting stories as to
what happened to the boy, it appeared the child wandered away from
Kwil's trailer not far from where he was found in traffic.
   Shirley, who met with police and with child-care officials of
the Florida Department of Health and Rehabilatative Services, told
authorities he had not known the whereabouts of his son.
   Health service officials had listed the toddler with ``Child
Find'' in Tallahassee and the national registry for missing
children.
</TEXT>
