<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0570,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Searches For Border Guerrillas; Arabs Stage Sabbath Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `They said...' to UPDATE with militiamen
killed. Pick up 6th pvs, `The interrogations...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Palestinians demonstrated on the
Moslem Sabbath today. Sources said Israeli troops were scouring
south Lebanon in a crackdown on Arab guerrillas who sneak across
the border into Israel.
   Israel radio reported that a small Israeli army force entered
the Lebanese villages of Kfar Hamam and Rachaiya el Foukhar, both
about five miles north of the Israeli border, and questioned
several dozen residents.
   Security sources in Lebanon confirmed that Israeli troops and
their Lebanese allies were carrying out searches but said most were
not in villages but in the rocky terrain in south Lebanon's eastern
sector.
   The sources, who spoke to The Associated Press on condition of
anonymity, said five Lebanese villagers had been detained.
   An army spokesman said two militiamen from the Israeli-allied
South Lebanon Army were killed today when their vehicle ran over a
land mine on a side road in Israel's self-declared security zone
north of the border.
   The interrogations came after two guerrilla infiltrations within
two days this week in which two Israeli soldiers and five
Palestinian guerrillas were killed.
   In Jerusalem, several hundred Arabs demonstrated outside the Al
Aqsa mosque after the noon Moslem prayers, chanting ``Palestine is
Arab'' and ``Jews leave because the Prophet Mohammed's army is
returning.''
   The demonstrators dispersed without confronting police, who were
stationed nearby.
   Some of the protesters waved outlawed Palestinian flags and
shouted slogans about PLO military leader Khalil Wazir, who was
assassinated April 16. Israeli sources have said Israeli commandos
killed him, but the government has not confirmed it.
   In the surrounding streets of Old Jerusalem, Palestinian
shopkeepers began opening their stores promptly at 2 p.m., the hour
that leaders of the five-week-old uprising have dictated for shops
to open during the Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   Israeli police have tried to force Arab merchants to open all
day, or not at all, in a move to break the hold of uprising leaders
on the shopkeepers.
   Underground leaders of the five-month Palestinian uprising in
the occupied lands had called for marches and symbolic funerals
today, the Moslem Sabbath, to honor Arabs killed in anti-Israeli
protests.
   But the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip appeared quiet today.
   In a new step aimed at curbing Arab demonstrations, the army
announced Thursday that parents in the occupied lands would be held
liable for offenses of children under the age of 12.
   Despite claims by Israeli leaders that the Arab rebellion was
waning, the death toll rose again Thursday with the killing of a
protester in Malek, a village near the West Bank city of Ramallah.
   Soon after entering the village to search for rioters, troops
were surrounded by hundreds of young Arabs who hurled stones and
then a firebomb, the army spokesman said. The troops fired in the
direction of the firebomb thrower, killing a Palestinian, he said.
   It was not immediately clear if the slain youth threw the
firebomb.
   The killing raised the Arab death toll to 175 since the violence
began in the territories last Dec. 8. An Israeli soldier and
Israeli teen-ager have also died.
   A general strike Thursday in the occupied lands, called for by
the PLO, seemed to be as widely observed as any such strike since
the uprising began. Arab reporters noted that in many areas even
bakeries and street vendors, who normally stay open during strikes,
were shut.
   Arab protesters blocked roads in several cities in Gaza and the
West Bank, and taxi and bus stands in Arab east Jerusalem were
empty.
</TEXT>
