<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CoastGuard 1stLd-Writethru a0454 04-29 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coast Guard, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 3 grafs new with Wright comments; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, ``It's not</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today he doesn't
like the idea of taking Coast Guard patrol boats off anti-drug
patrols and moving them to the Persian Gulf.
   ``I think the average American citizen feels more threatened by
drugs'' than by events in the gulf, the Texas Democrat told
reporters. ``I don't think it's a good idea to rob the Coast Guard
of its principal missions here, one of them being anti-drug
efforts.''
   Wright's comments came a day after the chairman of the House
Armed Services Committee predicted that the House will
overwhelmingly vote to block tentative plans to send Coast Guard
patrol boats to the gulf.
   ``It's not going to even be close'' said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
referring to a proposal introduced to stop the plan now being
considered by the Pentagon.
   The ban will be voted upon by the House next week as the chamber
continues consideration of the Pentagon budget bill.
   Even though the bill won't become law for several months because
the Senate hasn't yet considered its version of the same measure, a
strong House vote against the plan will likely kill it, Aspin said
Thursday.
   ``As a practical political matter, the administration would not
be wise to do something that a large majority of Congress is
against, and this amendment will win easily,'' Aspin explained.
   The tentative plan calls for taking six of the Coast Guard's
110-foot Island-class patrol boats off anti-drug duty and sending
them to the Persian Gulf. Built for shallow waters, the boats would
help the Navy patrol the war-torn area.
   The Navy is escorting 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers, raising
fears in Congress that the United States will be drawn into the
Iran-Iraq war because of Kuwait's ties with Iraq. There have been
several U.S.-Iran naval clashes, most recently April 18 when Navy
ships and planes sank or damaged six Iranian vessels.
   Adm. Paul A. Yost, Coast Guard commandant, told a Senate
subcommittee Thursday that he ``would be delighted'' to send the
ships to the gulf if ordered to do so.
   Yost said the move would have only ``a minimal impact'' on
anti-drug efforts because new Island-class builts are being built
and other ships could be pulled into the anti-drug effort off the
Florida coasts and in the Caribbean.
   But the plan has run into heavy fire on Capitol Hill.
   Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., a co-sponsor of the measure to which
Aspin referred, said, ``the Reagan administration should use the
Coast Guard's scarce resources to fight the war on drugs, not the
Iran-Iraq war.''
   The Coast Coast is strapped for money, and has responded to a
$100 million shortfall in its current budget by closing more than
30 shore installations and cutting anti-drug patrols by 55 percent.
   But the Navy has offered to pay any costs of sending the Coast
Guard vessels to the gulf, said Yost. Though part of the
Transportation Department, the Coast Guard also has national
security responsibilities and Coast Guard ships often operate with
Navy vessels.
   Yost appeared before the Senate Appropriations transportation
subcommittee, where he defended the plan. But when questioned
earlier about anti-drug efforts, he admitted, ``You can always use
more'' money and boats.
   ``It seems to me we're going to hurt our drug efforts'' by
sending the boats to the gulf, said Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., was even more critical. ``I think
it's an incredible policy,'' he told Yost. ``We kind of bumbled our
way into this.''
   But Yost said: ``This is not an idea off the top of somebody's
head. It was well thought out and researched.''
   Lowry disagreed. ``Sending the Coast Guard to the gulf would be
just another tragic, dangerous and poorly conceived move by the
administration,'' he said.
</TEXT>
