<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TestBanTest     04-29 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Test Ban Test,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Scientists Study Simulated Nukes in the Nevada Desert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GERLACH, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of American and Soviet scientists
headed into the Nevada desert today to begin a series of
experiments they hope will prove that a cheat-proof ban on all
testing is possible.
   The experiments today and Saturday come on the heels of the
House's passage of a bill Thursday forbidding all but the smallest
nuclear tests, if the Soviet Union agreed to do the same.
   Scores of seismic monitors have been set up to record three
non-nuclear explosions in remote areas of the state to try to
demonstrate that if a U.S.-Soviet test ban treaty is signed, any
infraction could be detected.
   If the experiments are successful, they would show that ``any
chance for cheating are about excluded'' under a test ban, Evgeni
Velikhov, vice president of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, said
Thursday.
   Velikhov, an adviser to Mikhail Gorbachev, said, ``We think the
comprehensive test ban is very important. It is extremely important
to stop the arms race.''
   The experiment is part of an agreement between the Soviet
Academy of Sciences and the privately-funded Natural Resources
Defense Council of the United States.
   The Nevada tests will set off 10 tons of TNT in the Black Rock
Desert 15 miles northeast of here and 100 miles north of Reno today
and another 10-ton blast tonight in Lathrop Wells, 50 miles south
of the Nevada Test Site. A 15-ton charge was to be detonated
Saturday in Broken Hills, 100 miles east of Carson City.
   The blasts will be monitored at three permanent centers
surrounding the Test Site, including one in Deep Springs, Calif.,
25 miles east of Bishop, Calif., where the Soviet technicians have
installed a ton of their own scientific devices for the first time
in this country.
   ``Typical underground nuclear explosions are measured in
hundreds or thousands of tons of TNT,'' Dr. Thomas Cochran, senior
staff scientist of the Natural Resources Defense Council told the
news conference. ``By detonating only 10-15 tons, we will show that
it is possible to detect very small explosions.''
   By comparison, the bill passed in the House on Thursday called
for a ban on all underground nuclear explosions equivalent to more
than 1,000 tons of TNT if the Soviet Union agreed to do the same.
   One objection to a test ban has been that low-yield blasts could
go virtually undetected, particularly if they were muffled in deep
caverns. The equipment being used in Nevada is designed to be
sophisticated enough ``to feel the difference between nuclear and
industrial explosions and ... very small earthquakes,'' Cochran
said.
   In addition to the equipment from the Soviet Academy of Sciences
and the Natura Resources Defense Center, the University of
Nevada-Reno and the University of Wisconsin are taking readings at
23 sites and the U.S. Geological Survey has installed 120
seismometers and recorders along a line from the northwest corner
of the state to its southern tip 450 miles away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0106 </DOCNO>
