<HEAD>Thunderstorms Plague Northwest; Heavy Rains Soak Northeast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 5th graf with 2 grafs to update with N.H. flooding.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms raced across the Northwest today, bringing heavy
rain and strong winds that ripped down trees and power lines.
Lingering April showers continued to drench the Northeast, with
flood warnings posted in two states.
   The thunderstorms developed Thursday night across eastern
Washington and Idaho with winds gusting to 63 mph at Hanford, Wash.
In northern Idaho, winds whipped down power lines and trees,
sparking a fire east of Coeur d'Alene.
   Scattered showers fell elsewhere across western portions of
Washington and Oregon.
   In the Northeast, heavy rains moved into New Hampshire and
southern Maine on Thursday night bringing some small rivers and
streams to bank-full.
   High water closed some roads in northern new Hampshire and the
Pemigewasset River was expected to crest at three feet above flood
stage late today in Plymouth. At least one family was briefly
stranded by high water and one house was moved off its foundation,
authorities said.
   Up to two inches of rain was reported in southwest Maine. Flood
warnings were in effect until noon today for parts of Maine and New
Hampshire.
   Very cold air in the lower atmosphere in the Northeast helped
produce snow in parts of West Virginia and Pennsylvania.
   Skies were mostly clear this morning over a large part of the
nation from Florida across the southeast and the Mississippi valley
to North Dakota. Skies also were clear over most of Nevada and
California.
   Today's forecast called for showers from eastern Ohio across the
northern and central Appalachians to the middle and northern
Atlantic coastal states; showers and thunderstorms from the
northern and central Rockies to the Pacific Northwest, extending
over the southern half of the Plains and Louisiana.
   High temperatures will be in the 40s and 50s from New England
across the northern and central Appalachians to the Great Lakes
region; in the 50s over much of Oregon and Washington; in to the
80s across southern Florida and Texas; in the 60s or 70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Duluth, Minn., and Yellowstone, Wyo., to 77 degrees at
Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 fair; Boston 48 drizzle; Buffalo 42 rain;
Charleston, S.C. 50 fair; Cincinnati 38 fair; Cleveland 43 cloudy;
Detroit 42 partly cloudy; Miami 73 fair; New York 47 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 43 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 39 cloudy; Portland,
Maine 44 rain; Washington 44 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 48 fair; Chicago 43 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
69 cloudy; Denver 55 cloudy; Des Moines 46 fair; Indianapolis 39
fair; Kansas City 55 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 45 fair; Nashville
44 fair; New Orleans 58 partly cloudy; St. Louis 48 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 53 cloudy; Anchorage 39 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 64 fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 71 fair; Salt Lake City
58 partly cloudy; San Diego 60 fair; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle
49 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 rain; Toronto 41 showery.
</TEXT>
