<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MurderVerdict     04-29 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Murder Verdict,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mentally Retarded Man Convicted Of First-Degree Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally retarded man who lived on
Duluth's streets was convicted of first-degree murder in the death
of another street person who was borderline mentally retarded.
   A jury delivered the verdict Thursday against Robert Webb, 30,
after 13 hours of deliberation. The conviction carries a mandatory
life sentence.
   The body of the victim, 33-year-old Barbara Ann Ward, was found
in an alley a year ago. She had been suffocated.
   The two-week trial included testimony from about 50 people,
including street people, neighborhood residents, social workers and
police detectives. Among those testifying were people with mental
disabilities who were on medication and had difficulty remembering
events.
   Webb's attorney, Fred Friedman, said he will seek to get the
verdict dismissed on the grounds that the evidence was insufficient
to sustain a conviction.
</TEXT>
