<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-SovietDrugs 1stLd-Writethru a0564 04-29 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Soviet Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0564,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First-Ever Anglo-Soviet Drug Bust Nets 3.5 Tons of Hashish</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `He said ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with all
those arrested in Britain being British. PICKS up 5th graf, `The
spokesman ...' DELETES last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs investigators in London seized 3.5 tons of
Afghan hashish in the first-ever narcotics bust involving Britain
and the Soviet Union, authorities said today.
   ``The drugs came from Afghanistan, overland through the Soviet
Union. The Soviet authorities got wind of that and agreed to
cooperate in tracking them, letting them out of the Soviet Union
and to the United Kingdom so that we were able to seize them
here,'' said Home Office Minister Peter Lilley.
   Officers tracked the drugs from Kabul, the Afghan capital, by
rail across the Soviet Union and by sea from Leningrad to London's
Tilbury docks, said a Customs and Excise spokesman who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said five men, all British, were arrested Thursday night. It
was not known whether the Soviets made any arrests on their own
territory.
   The spokesman said the seizure, codenamed Operation Diplomat,
arose from a visit by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to Moscow
last year. During the visit, British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey
Howe and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze discussed ways
of cooperating against drugs.
   In July, officials from both countries got together to work out
practical arrangements for fighting drug smuggling, and a
memorandum of understanding was signed in February.
   Just before this, Soviet authorities intercepted the hashish,
hidden in 400 sacks of liquorice root and packed in two containers.
   A British customs agent traveled to Moscow and plans were made
to find the drug traffickers. The Soviets agreed to let the
containers continue their journey under surveillance.
   British investigators took over the watch when the containers
left Leningrad, and when they reached Tilbury a month ago the drugs
were secretly removed from the cargo, which was then repacked and
kept under observation, the spokesman said.
   Last Thursday, officers watched as the containers were collected
from Tilbury and driven to a warehouse in an industrial zone on an
abandoned U.S. Air Force base in Warrington, northwest England.
   The load was then moved to storehouses in London, and the
customs investigators began making the arrests, the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
