<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SovietMilitary 1stLd-Writethru a0579 04-29 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Military, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf, By comparison, to update with
Carlucci comments; EDITS thruout to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, despite a new emphasis on
arms control initiatives and economic improvements, continues to
build and modernize its military might in pursuit of an advantage
over the West, the Pentagon said today.
   Releasing its seventh annual assessment of Soviet forces, the
Defense Department reported there were signs the military
competition between the two superpowers would soon expand into new
fields _ for example, the development of high-tech conventional
weapons instead of nuclear arms.
   Indeed, the strategic nuclear balance ``is essentially stable,''
the report states.
   To date, however, ``we have seen no evidence of the USSR
changing the offensive nature of its force structure and deployment
patterns,'' wrote Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci in a preface.
   ``Military output has not been reduced nor has military spending
decreased. On the contrary, the Soviet military budget under
General Secretary (Mikhail) Gorbachev continues to grow at a rate
of 3 percent per year at a level representing 15 to 17 percent of
their GNP.''
   By comparison, Pentagon spending consumes about 6 percent of
America's GNP.
   Carlucci, appearing at a Pentagon press confidence, cited
several other developments, including the fact the Soviets now have
two operational long-range nuclear missiles that use mobile
launchers _ the SS-24 and the SS-25 _ while the United States has
none.
   He also highlighted what he said was the first extensive,
unclassified review of a Soviet program to construct underground
bunkers, command centers and secret subways to protect their
leaders in the event of a war.
   ``There can be only one purpose for these shelters _ to provide
the Soviet leadership the ability to fight a protracted, nuclear
conflict,'' Carlucci asserted. ``These facilities contradict in
steel and concrete Soviet protestations that they share President
Reagan's view that nuclear war can never be won and must never be
fought.''
   But while Soviet military power is ``formidable,'' Carlucci
continued, ``we must not be overawed.''
   ``Rather, we must strengthen our resolve to preserve our
security and our freedoms. There is no mystery as to what America
should do in the face of Soviet military power,'' he said.
   This year's review is the last to be prepared by the Reagan
administration.
   The 175-page glossy booklet differs substantially from the
earlier reports in that it tries harder to gauge who's leading in
various technologies and regions of the world, rather than just
reporting what weapons have been added to the Soviet arsenal over
the last year.
   Indeed, the report for the first time carries a subtitle: ``An
Assessment of the Threat,'' and acknowledges that in areas such as
naval power and high technology the United States and its Western
allies still enjoy an advantage.
   The report does point to new weapon developments, though. Among
them:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Soviets will soon deploy operational units of their new
Blackjack long-range bomber. Deployment of the new rail-mounted
SS-24 nuclear missile has now begun, and production should start
soon for a more accurate version of the huge SS-18 intercontinental
ballistic missile, the mainstay of the Soviet arsenal.
   _Production of self-propelled artillery pieces is at an
``all-time high;'' two new attack helicopters, the Havoc and Hokum,
``are expected to enter serial production soon,'' and the Soviets
have begun fielding ``a new tank derived from the T-72, exhibiting
improved protection, better mobility and enhanced firepower.''
   _Russia will complete a major upgrade of its anti-ballistic
missile defense system protecting Moscow ``in 1988 or 1989.'' A new
``Pill Box'' radar to help with tracking and targeting for that
system is ``nearing completion at Pushkino.''
   _``The Soviets are on the verge of deploying a variety of
sophisticated cruise missile systems,'' and continue to lead the
West in the pace of their activities in outer space.
   _In the area of Star Wars, the Soviet Union, like the United
States, is unlikely to develop small ``kinetic kill'' rockets that
could be placed in space to shoot down nuclear missiles at long
range. The Soviets could, however, ``deploy a short-range,
space-based system for space station defense or close-in attack by
a maneuvering satellite in the near future.''
   The report also spotlights for the first time Soviet efforts to
develop the equipment needed for ``radio-electronic combat'' _ the
use of electronic jamming and deception techniques to disrupt U.S.
and allied radio communication systems.
   On the strategic nuclear side, the report concludes the United
States can deter a Soviet attack and continue to press for
additional arms control agreements, so long as it continues
President Reagan's program of introducing weapons such as the B-1B
and Stealth bombers and the MX missile while pursuing Star Wars
research.
</TEXT>
