<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Wonka     04-29 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wonka,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Condemns Death of Imprisoned Czech Rights Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pavel Wonka, a human rights activist who
died suddenly in a Czechoslovak jail, had asked the Helsinki human
rights conference to make sure he was not silenced in prison, a
U.S. official said today.
   Warren Zimmermann, chief U.S. delegate to the Conference on
Security and Cooperation in Europe, condemned Wonka's imprisonment
and said the conference had a ``special obligation to Wonka and to
people like him.''
   The conference adopted the Helsinki accords on human rights in
1975.
   Prison authorities did not explain Wonka's death and official
media in Czechoslovakia have not reported it. Human rights groups
have said that the activist was beaten in detention.
   Frantiski Dolezel, the chief Czechoslovak delegate to the
conference, said Wonka died of emphysema.
   ``As we record and mourn his untimely death, we must also
condemn the wholly unjustifiable imprisonment and mistreatment he
suffered while serving his term,'' the U.S. diplomat said.
   Wonka, who was released Feb. 26 after serving a 21-month prison
sentence, was to be under ``protective surveillance'' for three
years after he was freed. He was rearrested on April 5 and
sentenced to another five-month jail term on unspecified charges
April 21.
   Zimmermann said that in his March 3 message, Wonka said people
in the Soviet bloc should be made more aware of how their laws
affect their rights and freedoms.
   ``My right to freedom of expression is guaranteed by the
constitution of Czechoslovakia. Experience, however, has taught me
not to depend too much on such declarations,'' Zimmermann quoted
Wonka as saying.
   ``Therefore, I have learned to be careful and I am taking the
liberty to ask the ... governments of all the signatory states to
see that my voice is not silenced _ under some pretext _ in
prison,'' the message said.
   Several international groups have asked the Prague government to
allow independent doctors to attend Wonka's port-mortem.
   Wonka, an auto mechanic by profession, had sought to run for
Parliament as an independent candidate for his hometown in northern
Bohemia. He was known to be suffering from some intestinal problems
but was not fatally ill, according to an emigre source.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
