<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sheriff-Hearing     04-29 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sheriff-Hearing,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columbus Sheriff Removed from Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Columbus County sheriff has been
removed from office by a judge who ruled that he had failed to
comply with court orders, falsified court documents and kissed two
women against their will.
   ``I definitely feel betrayed, and I definitely feel my
intentions were not to do anything wrong,'' said former sheriff
William Rhodes. ``I do feel like ... the things I have done in law
enforcement, I tried to do right.''
   Rhodes, 59, said after Thursday's ruling that testimony by
current and former employees had confirmed his suspicions that many
of them were working against him. He said several lied, or were
mistaken, in their testimony about events at the department.
   ``I think I had a fair hearing,'' he said. ``The one thing I
would say is, it helped me find out what I wanted to find out about
the people I was dealing with.
   Superior Court Judge Robert H. Hobgood said he found evidence
supporting all 14 allegations made in a petition filed by District
Attorney Michael Easley that sought Rhodes' removal for willful
misconduct or maladministration in office.
   Easley's petition followed Rhodes' guilty plea last month to
misdemeanor charges of obstructing justice and attempting to
obstruct justice.
   Rhodes admitted he informed an attorney associated with a local
country club that state Alcohol Law Enforcement agents were on
their way to the club for a raid on beer selling without a permit.
   Rhodes testified Thursday that his actions were not intended to
obstruct justice, but the judge found that he ``knew or should have
known'' that his telling about the raids would result in illegal
beer supplies being hidden before agents arrived.
   The judge also found that the sheriff directed one of his
deputies to falsify a jail record to show that a defendant had
served time in the county jail.
   The judge also ruled that Rhodes violated court orders by
allowing the temporary release of inmates to visit their families
or to perform cleanup duties for the county.
   Hobgood also found that Rhodes had kissed two women _ one 15 and
another 20 _ without their consent.
   County Coroner Henry Smith Rowan will serve as interim sheriff
until the county commissioners name a replacement to fill Rhodes'
term, which expires in 1990.
</TEXT>
