<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0483 04-29 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 17 grafs new with tentative agreement; picks up 15th
graf pvs, The administration has...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has reached a
tentative agreement with Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega under which he will resign as defense chief but remain on
in Panama for the time being, a U.S. official said today.
   The official, insisting on anonymity, said the settlement is
``less than ideal'' because the administration had initially
insisted that Noriega leave Panama upon his resignation as part of
a transition to democratic rule.
   ``We have to settle for three-fourths of a loaf,'' the official
said.
   The administration had been concerned that any solution that
allowed Noriega to remain on in Panama could enable him to retain
effective control even if he surrendered his post as commander of
the Defense Forces.
   But the official said that Noriega, once he steps down, would be
like a ``cop out of uniform'' and would cease to be the dominant
force in Panama's political life.
   The timing of Noriega's resignation and the question of whether
he eventually will go into exile remain up in the air and are
subject to future negotiations, the official said.
   The Washington Post said in today's editions that Noriega is
known to prefer the Dominican Republic if he is forced into exile.
   On Thursday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater hinted that
the admininistration was backing away from its demand that Noriega
leave Panama as part of a settlement.
   The administration goal, he said, was for Noriega to ``leave
power.''
   Fitzwater had indicated earlier the arrangement did not
represent a policy change, but President Reagan and others had said
in previous statements no acceptable settlement could be reached
until Noriega left Panama.
   Fitzwater said: ``Our policy is that Gen. Noriega must go, which
means leave power. We've talked about that a number of times. We
have said we prefer him to leave Panama, but the policy issue is to
leave power.''
   On March 22, Reagan was asked by reporters if he'd be satisfied
if the military strongman would step down, but not leave his
country.
   ``We feel Noriega should leave Panama,'' the president replied.
   On March 28, Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams said,
``The way to end this crisis is to get him (Noriega) out of the
country.''
   The Post quoted unnamed sources as saying that Noriega has
agreed to resign in ``a matter of weeks'' and would permit free
elections and the restoration of constitutional government.
   Noriega has said only that he would be willing to step down from
his post before national elections set for May 1989 if certain
conditions are met.
   The scaling back of the U.S. demand occurred as a top State
Department official, Michael Kozak, was in Panama for his second
round of talks with Noriega in less than two weeks. The official
said Kozak was back in Washington today.
   The administration has not acknowledged that Kozak has met with
Noriega on either visit in an apparent attempt to make it easier
for the general to arrange a face-saving way out. Officials believe
the more Noriega is seen to be under U.S. pressure to step down the
less cooperative he will be.
   The Post said the tentative deal was worked out during secret
negotiations this week between the two. Administration officials
have been anguished by Noriega's ability to hang on to power in the
face of a severe cash-flow crisis that has meant no paychecks for
thousands of Panamanian workers.
   Among other measures, the United States has frozen Panamanian
assets in the United States and cut off payments to Panama for
services relating to Panama Canal operations.
   The administration also has continued to recognize the
government of President Eric Arturo Delvalle even though he was
ousted by Noriega's supporters two months ago.
   Noriega was indicted on drug charges in February by two grand
juries in Florida. U.S. officials have informed Noriega he will not
be subject to extradition here if he agrees to seek political exile
in a third country. Spain has offered Noriega conditional exile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
