<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Handguns 1stLd-Writethru a0608 04-29 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Handguns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Invited to Consider Liability Issue Regarding Cheap Handguns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 2 grafs with further background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today invited the
District of Columbia's highest court to consider whether gun
manufacturers may be held liable in civil suits for deaths and
injuries caused by cheap handguns.
   The advisory opinion was issued by the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals here about the dismissal of a civil suit against the
manufacturer of the .22-caliber pistol presidential assailant John
W. Hinckley Jr. used to shoot President Reagan in 1981.
   It invited the District of Columbia Court of Appeals, which
interprets local law in the nation's capital, to determine whether
to adopt a 1985 finding by Maryland's highest state court that gun
manufacturers are liable for injuries and deaths caused by the
criminal use of so-called Saturday Night Specials.
   The panel of three federal circuit judges found that the
Maryland decision ``was based on public policy considerations''
expressed in that state's gun-control laws.
   ``The district's gun control statute... places limitations on
handgun ownership and purchases that are at least as strict as the
Maryland provisions concerning handgun possession'' that formed the
basis of the 1985 decision by Maryland's highest court, the panel
said.
   ``Such a reassessment is permissive, not mandatory'' by the
local appellate court, the federal panel said.
   Maryland's legislature recently voted to outlaw all cheap
handguns, but that change in policy should not be a factor in the
D.C. court's review of the issue, the federal panel said in an
opinion written by Circuit Judge Abner Mikva.
   The advisory opinion follows by a year a decision by the same
appellate court upholding the dismissal of Roehm of Germany as a
defendant in civil suits filed by others wounded during Hinckley's
attack on Reagan.
   Roehm, which makes the guns through its U.S. subsidiary R.G.
Industries of Miami, had been sued for $20 million by White House
press secretary James Brady and former D.C. police officer Thomas
Delahanty.
   Both were wounded along with Secret Service Agent Timothy
McCarthy when Hinckley shot Reagan on March 30, 1981.
   The shooting has left Brady confined to a wheelchair and
Delahanty's wounds forced him to retire from the police force.
   A suit against Hinckley by the three men is scheduled to go to
trial May 16 in U.S. Distict Court here.
   Two of the three judges in today's opinion, Kenneth Starr and
Harry Edwards, participated in last year's holding that gun
manufacturers could not be held negligent for failing ``to prevent
criminals from using their products.''
   That decision also found that ``the strict liability claim fails
because there is no allegation that the gun failed to operate
properly. The gun was not defective.''
   Because the 1987 opinion was not published by the court, it is
not legal precedent.
   In a concurring opinion to today's ruling, Starr expressed
regret that the court did not refer last year's issue for the same
study by the D.C. court.
   Starr said that if the D.C. Court of Appeals holds gun
manufacturers can be sued, the federal appellate court can
reconsider whether to reinstate the suits by Brady and Delahanty
against Roehm.
   The court said that a review of the liability standard was
appropriate because the District of Columbia was carved out of
Maryland and ``derived its common law from the state.''
   The Maryland decision, by a unanimous Court of Appeals, also
involved a lawsuit against Roehm.
   The state's highest court said the manufacturer or marketer of a
Saturday Night Special knows or ought to know ``that he is making
or selling a product principally to be used in criminal activity.''
These guns are ``largely unfit'' for legitimate uses, the court
found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
