<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TuskegeeProtest     04-29 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tuskegee Protest,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Wants Restraint Order Thrown Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSKEGEE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Tuskegee University have
asked a judge to drop his order that temporarily blocks the school
from prohibiting students who owe $300 or more in overdue fees from
attending classes.
   University President Benjamin Payton said Thursday the 10-day
temporary restraining order obtained by students weakens the
university's loan collection policy.
   Payton said the order issued Wednesday by Circuit Judge Howard
F. Bryan was unfair. He said neither school officials nor their
attorneys were contacted to state their position before Bryan
issued his order.
   The university's policy kept students with overdue fees from
attending classes and taking final exams, which begin next week.
   That sparked a week of protests, including demonstrations and a
sit-in, at the predominantly black private institution, followed by
the students' plea to the judge.
   Leaders of the Student Government Association, which directed
the protests, have said school officials should have warned
students earlier in the semester about the crackdown.
   University officials said the crackdown was prompted by abuse of
an installment payment plan. They estimate some 2,000 students owe
almost $1.5 million.
   Payton said the order ``saddens me deeply and it jeopardizes the
financial well-being of the university, including its undermining
of the process that had resulted in significant payments of
delinquent student fees.''
   He said it is ``revealing and unfortunate'' that students who
said they didn't have funds to pay their fees had gotten money to
take the issue to court.
</TEXT>
