<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Terrorist Suspect Pleads Innocent to Weapons Possession
Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man linked to a left-wing Japanese
terrorist group pleaded innocent today to weapons possession
charges, 17 days after police found three pipe bombs in his car
along the New Jersey Turnpike.
   FBI agents have been investigating a possible link between the
man, Yu Kikumura, 36, and a USO club bombing in Naples, Italy, that
killed five people, including a U.S. servicewoman. Italian
authorities have linked the bombing to the terrorist group.
   Italian authorities have confirmed that Kikumura was in their
country in February. FBI spokesman James J. Knights said he could
not comment on a continuing investigation.
   The Japanese Foreign Ministry has identified Kikumura as a
suspected member of the Red Army terrorist group.
   Kikumura, 36, was arrested April 12 at a New Jersey Turnpike
service area after police found three sophisticated homemade bombs
and falsified papers in his car.
   At Kikumura's arraignment, defense attorney William Kunstler
questioned how Kikumura's case was assigned to the court of U.S.
District Judge Alfred E. Lechner Jr., a judge Kunstler's partner
called the most conservative in the state.
   ``We were told it was rotation, but who knows?'' Kunstler said.
``We just want to see if it wasn't maneuvered.''
   U.S. Attorney Samuel Alito Jr. denied the charges.
   ``I resent his accusations to the press yesterday that we
calculated the judge to which it was assigned,'' Alito said.
``There certainly was no effort to link the return of indictments.''
   Kikumura pleaded innocent to all charges in the 12-count federal
indictment, nine of which relate to the bombs and three stemming
from alleged misuse of a visa and a passport.
   If convicted on all 12 counts, he could face 90 years in prison.
</TEXT>
