<DOCNO> AP880429-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CopyrightTreaty     04-29 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copyright Treaty,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Copyright Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters today predicted swift House action
on a bill allowing the United States to adhere to a century-old
international copyright treaty and strengthen its hand against
foreign piracy of records, tapes and computer technology.
   The measure was approved Thursday by a voice vote of the House
Judiciary Committee without the so-called ``moral rights''
provision sought by Hollywood film makers to help prevent
unauthorized coloring and other alterations in works sold to
television broadcasters.
   Rep. Robert W. Kastenmeier, D-Wis., chief sponsor of the House
bill, said the moral rights issue will be considered later in
separate hearings by his Judiciary subcommittee, which considers
copyright issues.
   A similar measure, also without a moral rights provision, was
approved April 14 by the Senate Judiciary Committee. Approval of
the legislation by the full House and Senate was expected within
the next few weeks, congressional staff aides said.
   If the treaty is then ratified by a two-thirds majority of the
Senate, the United States would join 76 other nations that
subscribe to the Bern Convention for the Protection of Literary and
Artistic Works, which sets the world standard for copyright
protection of creative works exported by any of the signatory
nations.
   Kastenmeier and other supporters of the bill said U.S. adherence
would help stem piracy of American-owned works in the computer and
entertainment fields. U.S. producers of records and tapes, for
example, lost an estimated $558 million in sales in 1986 because of
foreign counterfeiting and piracy, according to the U.S.
International Trade Commission.
   ``I want to bring this to the full House for a vote right
away,'' Kastenmeier said today through a spokeswoman. ``Every day
the U.S. waits to join Bern is another day that the gold medalist
of the world intellectual property Olympics stays on the bench for
lack of proper credentials.''
   Kastenmeier said the bill would allow the United States to
improve copyright relations with 24 of the 76 subscribing nations.
   ``Joining the Bern convention is a trade issue as well as an
artistic concern,'' he said. ``...We enhance our own political
credibility in our global efforts to raise copyright standards and
reduce piracy. The more we achieve in all those areas, the better
we protect American jobs and American creativity.''
   At a hearing before a Senate Judiciary subcommittee on March 3,
film makers Steven Spielberg and George Lucas appealed for a
statutory ``moral rights'' ban on changes in a motion picture by
its financial backers or buyers without the consent of directors
and screenwriters.
   ``American law does not protect our painters, sculptors,
recording artists, authors or film makers from having their life
work distorted and their reputation distorted,'' said Lucas, who
directed the hit movie ``Star Wars.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
