<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0443 04-29 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Urges Reagan Not To Veto Trade Bill; Bush Begins Campaign
Swing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis, Bush, Jackson comments in top 11 grafs,
picking up in 14th graf pvs, Ohio offers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis appealed to
President Reagan today to think about workers who lose their jobs
when plants close, but Republican George Bush dismissed his
comments, saying, ``He can talk about pink slips. I want to talk
about competitiveness.''
   Bush, at a breakfast with supporters in Fort Wayne, Ind.,
criticized Dukakis' backing of trade legislation that includes a
provision requiring that notice be given to workers before plant
closings. Reagan is expected to veto the measure, which won
congressional approval this week.
   The vice president said the fall election would give voters a
clear choice between strong Republican leadership and
``old-fashioned liberal Democrats talking compassion and delivering
misery.''
   Dukakis, campaigning in Columbus, Ohio, said, ``I hope the
president will take the time to think about the three million
American workers who lose their jobs in this country every year
through plant shutdowns. In at least half those cases, those plants
shut down with little or no notice to those most affected _ their
own employees.''
   ``These people are our neighbors,'' Dukakis said in prepared
remarks. ``They deserve better from their employers. They deserve
better from America.''
   Democrat Jesse Jackson, far behind Dukakis but doggedly
remaining in the race, criticized Dukakis today on the issue of
South Africa, telling students at a high school in Cleveland that
both Bush and Dukakis should label South Africa a terrorist state
because of its backing of extremist rebels in Mozambique.
   He accused the rebels of atrocities and said ``South Africa is
responsible for that behavior.''
   The candidates were spending the day in the two states that have
the next two big primaries next Tuesday.
   One day earlier, the Massachusetts governor, criticized by Bush
for lacking foreign policy experience, met with Spain's prime
minister, Felipe Gonzalez, and the two conversed in Spanish, aides
said.
   Jackson, on Wednesday, expressed determination during an Ohio
campaign swing to stay in the race despite a series of setbacks.
   ``We're winning every day on this long and tortuous journey to
the White House,'' Jackson told supporters in Canton on Thursday.
Later, in Akron, he vowed: ``Nothing and nobody is going to turn us
around.''
   Ohio offers 159 delegates, and a Gallup poll earlier this month
indicated Dukakis led Jackson in the state by a 2-1 margin.
   Dukakis widened his delegate lead over Jackson, as delegates
from the camps of now-inactive candidates began drifting his way.
New recruits included two former supporters of Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
of Tennessee and one backer of Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois.
   One delegate from New Hampshire, state Rep. Richard Daschbach,
originally a supporter of Rep. Richard Gephardt, said Gephardt had
told him to go ahead and get behind Dukakis. He quoted Gephardt as
telling him: ``It's time to go. ... We've got to get out and
support him (Dukakis).''
   However, Deborah Johns, Gephardt's press secretary, said the
Missouri congressman, who abandoned his presidential bid in March,
remains neutral.
   ``As far as I know, he is not planning to endorse anyone soon,''
she said.
   According to the latest Associated Press delegate count, Dukakis
has 1,276 to Jackson's 852, with 2,081 needed to nominate. Aides
are beginning to suggest that Dukakis could clinch the nomination
during the primary season, which ends June 7 with big contests in
New Jersey and California.
   On the Republican side, Bush, who achieved a mathematical lock
on the nomination in Tuesday's Pennsylvania primary, now has 1,146
delegates, according to the AP count. Former television evangelist
Pat Robertson, who technically remains a candidate, has 31.
   Robertson's campaign has been given two weeks to submit
financial records in a federal investigation of the tax-exempt
status of Robertson's religious broadcasting network. U.S.
Magistrate Rebecca Smith in Norfolk, Va. extended a show-cause
order on Thursday until May 12, for documents originally requested
by the Internal Revenue Service last December.
   Most of the information requested has been turned over, but
Assistant U.S. Attorney Raymond Jackson has asked for additional
material, including bank records for Robertson groups in Texas,
Michigan and Virginia.
</TEXT>
