<HEAD>Martin Returns to Vegas Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Dean Martin gave himself a
clean bill of health when he returned to the stage nearly six weeks
after he left a ``Rat Pack'' tour with Frank Sinatra and Sammy
Davis Jr. because of a kidney problem.
   ``Everything's perfect, I feel great,'' Martin told an audience
Thursday night at Bally's Hotel and Casino, where he began a
weeklong engagement.
   Before the show, spokesman Mort Viner downplayed rumors that
Martin left the tour March 21 because of a split with Sinatra.
   ``There's absolutely nothing to that,'' Viner said. ``It's
totally false.''
   Martin, 70, had been on the nationwide ``Rat Pack'' reunion tour
with Sinatra and Davis when he returned to Los Angeles and checked
into Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. Hospital spokesman Ron Wise
described the illness as a ``flareup of an old kidney problem.''
   Martin was released from the hospital March 25 but ordered by
his physician, Dr. Charles Kivowitz, to remain home for three to
four weeks and skip the remainder of the tour.
   In his show Thursday night, Martin alluded to his former road
companions.
   ``Frank sent me a kidney, but I don't know whose it was,''
Martin joked.
   He also lauded Davis and Jerry Lewis, Martin's former partner
before the two had a bitter split years ago. Martin praised Lewis'
work for the Muscular Dystrophy Association.
   Martin said he felt he was ``home'' at Bally's, where he has
appeared for years.
   ``It's so good to be off the road,'' he said.
   Martin, Sinatra and Davis became known as members of the ``Rat
Pack'' in the late 1950s and early 1960s when they made movies
together, partied together and became fixtures on the Las Vegas
stage.
</TEXT>
