<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--CatsKilled     04-29 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cats Killed,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Killing Cypriot Cats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British military authorities have begun
killing the ancient cat population of the Akrotiri peninsula in
south Cyprus.
   Scores of cats have been destroyed in gas chambers since the
campaign was launched six weeks ago, said sources at the British
air base on Akrotiri who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``This is not an extermination campaign,'' said British military
spokesman Maj. Johnnie Rogers. ``The number of feral cats in the
area has reached sufficient numnbers to warrant some kind of
control measures.''
   According to local lore, the cats were introduced to Akrotiri in
the 4th century to control the snake population.
   The president of the Cyprus animal protection society, Loulla
Josephides, said that ``getting rid of the cats of Akrotiri will
upset the balance of nature. The whole area will soon be infested
by snakes again.''
</TEXT>
