<2ND_LINE>AM-Priest-Guns,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Support Priest Who Wants to Destroy Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-nine inmates at the Denver and Adams county
jails have signed a letter of support to a priest who called on
parishioners to turn in their guns and sign pledges they won't own
firearms.
   ``In these times of so much violence, guns are the demon,'' said
letter, sent Thursday. ``The purpose of guns is killing and hurting
other human beings. Some of us know how very true this is.''
   The Rev. Marshall Gourley earlier this month asked that members
of Our Lady of Guadalupe Roman Catholic Church give up their guns,
and his appeal has spread to other churches and received national
publicity.
   So far, only 11 guns have been turned in, but more than 400
people signed the pledge cards.
   The Rev. Jim Sunderland, the jails' chaplain, said he wrote the
letter and passed it around for inmates to sign.
   ``Being a jail chaplain, I know what handguns do,'' he said. ``I
eyed a couple of people as it went around because some were in
there for shooting, and they signed.''
   The letter praised Gourley for a ``small but very important step
toward lessening violence. We hope other pastors and other churches
will follow your example.''
