<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RefugeeSuicide     04-29 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugee Suicide,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Hangs Himself In Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 45-year-old Vietnamese refugee hanged
himself in a camp near Bangkok after complaining that he had been
at the camp too long and was going nowhere, camp officials said
Friday.
   The body of Nguyen Thanh Sang was found April 23 at the Phanat
Nikhom camp, about 70 miles southeast of the Thai capital, the
officials said.
   A Western relief official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said Sang wanted to resettle in the United States but did not have
documents proving his claim that he had served in the U.S.-backed
South Vietnamese army during the Vietnam War.
   The case was put on hold after U.S. officials interviewed him in
June 1986.
   Sang also apparently had personal problems, the official said.
His family remained behind in Vietnam after he fled to Thailand by
boat in 1986, and he lived alone in a section of the camp that
houses about 9,000 Vietnamese.
   A camp administration official said Sang had tried to kill
himself April 21, but a neighbor notified authorities, who stopped
him.
   Relief officials say there have been a growing number of suicide
attempts among Vietnamese refugees who have spent long periods of
time in the camp because they do not qualify for resettlement.
</TEXT>
