<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--JetSale     04-29 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Jet Sale,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch May Sell Jets To Turkey, Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dutch government has agreed to
sell up to 60 aging jet fighters to Turkey, the Defense Ministry
said Friday.
   From 50 to 60 of the Northrop NF-5 jets will be sold to Turkey
after the Dutch air force retires them from service in the next
five years, said ministry spokesman Cent van Vliet.
   The price and quantity still are being discussed, Van Vliet
said. He said Dutch Deputy Defense Minister Jan van Houwelingen
agreed to the sale during a visit to Turkey last week.
   The single-engine jets, built in the 1960s, are being replaced
by U.S.-built F-16 fighters.
   Talks also were under way for the sale of 20 to 30 of the NF-5
jets to Greece, which frequently is at odds with Turkey over oil
drilling rights in the Aegean Sea.
</TEXT>
