<1ST_LINE>r a BC-APNebraskaAppointment     04-29 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Nebraska Appointment,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dan Day Named Nebraska AP Bureau Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Day, who has been correspondent in charge of
The Associated Press office in Omaha, Neb., was named chief of
bureau for Nebraska on Friday by AP President Louis D. Boccardi.
   Day, 31, becomes the first Nebraska bureau chief for the news
cooperative since 1939. Nebraska AP operations have been under the
administrative direction of the Des Moines, Iowa, bureau.
   The delegation of full responsibility for news and
administration makes Omaha the 41st domestic control bureau. The
Lincoln office will report to Omaha.
   Day, a native of Cleveland, graduated from Holy Cross College
and received a master's degree in journalism from Marquette
University in Milwaukee. He worked for the Daily Times in Ottawa,
Ill., before joining AP in Milwaukee in 1981. He was named
broadcast editor in 1982, then news editor in Omaha in 1983. In
1985, he was elevated to correspondent in charge of the Omaha
office.
</TEXT>
