<1ST_LINE>r a BC-APNewMexicoAppointment     04-29 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP New Mexico Appointment,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mark Mittelstadt Named AP New Mexico Chief of Bureau</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Mittelstadt, news editor in the Des Moines,
Iowa, bureau of The Associated Press has been named chief of bureau
in Albuquerque, N.M., succeeding Robert H. Johnson, who retires
July 1 after a 42-year career with the news agency.
   Mittelstadt, 34, a native of Fort Dodge, Iowa, graduated from
the University of Iowa and worked for the Cedar Falls Record, where
he was named editor, before joining the AP in Des Moines in 1981.
He was named news editor in that bureau in 1982.
   Johnson, a native of Colorado City, Texas, and a graduate of
Southern Methodist University, joined AP in 1946 in Dallas after
serving with the U.S. Marines during World War II. He was named
chief of bureau in Salt Lake City and Indianapolis before returning
to Dallas as bureau chief in 1962. He directed the AP coverage of
the assassination of President John F. Kennedy in 1963.
   In 1969, Johnson transferred to New York as sports editor of the
AP, and in 1972 directed coverage of the massacre of Israeli
athletes at the Munich Olympics. He became managing editor in 1973
and helped direct coverage of Watergate and the resignation of
President Nixon.
   He served as assistant to the president of the AP before
becoming chief of bureau in Albuquerque in 1984. Johnson, 64, and
his wife, Luise, will retire in Albuquerque, and Johnson will teach
journalism at New Mexico State University in Las Cruces.
</TEXT>
