<HEAD>One Dead, 13 Others Injured in Forest Van Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to CORRECT that vehicle was van, not bus.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ESTACADA, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A van plunged off a steep embankment on a
winding, rain-slickened road in Mount Hood National Forest, killing
one forest worker and injuring 13 others, authorities said.
   The van, carrying a tree-planting crew home from work Thursday
evening, went off the road, rolled sideways down the embankment for
about 150 feet, then fell through stumps and brush before stopping
against a tree, said Lt. Sherwood Stillman of the Clackamas County
sheriff's office.
   The driver said he lost control of the vehicle while trying to
make a turn, said Dr. Duane Beitz, a member of the Oregon Trauma
Advisory Board.
   The man who died apparently was pinned beneath the van, said Dr.
William Long, trauma chief at Emanuel Hospital and Health Center in
Portland. The man's identity was not immediately available.
