<HEAD>Ruth Gersh Named Iowa Chief of Bureau</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Gersh, news editor in The Associated Press'
Louisville, Ky., bureau, has been named chief of bureau in Des
Moines, Iowa, succeeding Dave Tomlin, who was named deputy director
of AP membership based in New York.
   The appointments were announced Friday by Louis D. Boccardi,
president of AP.
   Gersh, 34, a native of Tuckahoe, N.Y. graduated from the
University of Pennsylvania and received a master's degree in
journalism from the University of Michigan. She worked for The
Baltimore Sun and the Norfolk Virginian-Pilot before joining AP in
Richmond, Va., in 1978.
   She was named correspondent in Norfolk in 1980, then transferred
back to Richmond in 1982 to cover state government. In 1986 she
became news editor in Louisville.
   Tomlin, 41, is a native of Providence, R.I. He received
bachlor's and master's degrees in international studies from Johns
Hopkins University and worked for the Newport News (Va.) Daily
Press and the Washington Star before joing AP in Columbus, Ohio, in
1970.
   Tomlin left the AP in 1973 to work for the San Antonio
Express-News as a reporter. He became editor of the combined Sunday
editions of that paper, then rejoined AP in Raleigh, N.C. in 1976.
He was appointed news editor there, then named correspondent in
Pittsburgh in 1978 and chief of bureau in Columbia, S.C., in 1980.
   He moved to Des Moines as chief of bureau in 1984. In New York
he will report to James M. Mangan, vice president for newspaper
membership of the news cooperative.
