<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0444 04-29 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Staff Warned About Criticizing Meese</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Fitzwater comments; picks up 3rd graf
pvs, Baker reminded.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's senior aides apparently got
the message when Chief of Staff Howard H. Baker told them he will
not tolerate attempts to undermine Attorney General Edwin Meese
III, the president's spokesman said today.
   An administration source said earlier that Baker told
subordinates Thursday he had ``had it'' with a spate of news
stories about underground efforts to win Meese's ouster.
   Baker reminded aides that Reagan has repeatedly stated his
confidence in Meese, and told them ``those people who disagree with
that should come to Howard Baker and talk,'' said the source,
speaking on grounds he not be identified publicly. He said Baker
left no doubt that such a meeting would center on the continuing
job status of the complaining aide.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said he did not believe anybody had
been in to see Baker as a result of his comments.
   ``I don't think anybody missed the message,'' Fitzwater said.
``They'd be too dumb to work at the White house if they did.''
   Baker reminded aides that Reagan has repeatedly stated his
confidence in Meese, and told them ``those people who disagree with
that should come to Howard Baker and talk,'' said the source,
speaking on grounds he not be identified publicly. He said Baker
left no doubt that such a meeting would center on the continuing
job status of the complaining aide.
   The source said Baker made it clear that because Reagan still
has confidence in Meese, his staff should respect that. He said
Baker told aides that he, too, believes in Meese's innocence.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay has been examining Meese's
assistance to the scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a proposed $1
billion oil pipeline project. Also under investigation are Meese's
meetings with regional Bell telephone company executives at a time
when he owned $14,000 in Baby Bell stock. In addition, McKay is
looking into the $40,000-a-year job for the attorney general's
wife, Ursula Meese, that is being funded by the foundation of a
Washington family that has leased real estate to the Justice
Department.
   The administration source said Baker was not directly challenged
by anyone in the meeting.
   ``You should have seen all the heads at the table, nodding up
and down, and probably someone at that table had been leaking
stories,'' he said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked about Baker's
threat, said, ``Senator Baker told the senior staff that the
president supports Ed Meese and the White House supports Ed Meese
and if anybody questions that policy, then they shouldn't.''
   Asked whether Baker, a former senator from Tennessee, had
suggested that those in disagreement might leave the White House,
Fitzwater said Baker had said, ``Come see me if you have any
problems.''
   A spate of stories has appeared recently quoting unidentified
administration and White House officials as saying the time has
come for the resignation of Meese. These people were quoted in the
various accounts as saying that a group of Reagan's close friends
and advisers had taken part in an underground effort, supposedly
with Nancy Reagan's support, to work for Meese's departure.
   However, Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen, denied that
the first lady had played a role in any such move.
</TEXT>
