<HEAD>Reagan May Finally Endorse Bush on Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aides to Vice President George Bush said
Friday that President Reagan may finally endorse Bush at a victory
party next Tuesday although the president's spokesman said a
decision has yet to be made.
   Bush aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there is a
strong possiblity the president will weigh in with his formal
support at a party planned to celebrate Bush's clinching of the GOP
nomination.
   ``We're over the top, so we may as well take advantage of it,''
said one aide.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater would not confirm that Reagan
would appear at the celebration at a Washington, D.C., hotel but
added: ``I won't tell you it ain't going to happen.''
   The previously scheduled event will be held as the Ohio, Indiana
and District of Columbia primary returns come in Tuesday night,
which was when Bush advisers initially had believed the vice
president would go over the 1,139 delegates needed to lock up the
GOP nomination.
   However, Bush reached that level last Tuesday, after the
Pennsylvania primary.
   There has been no question of Reagan's endorsement of his vice
president, only the matter of when it would come. Reagan had vowed
to remain publicly neutral so long as the GOP nomination was in
contention.
   The only remaining GOP rival is former television evangelist Pat
Robertson, but he has ceased active campaigning and has conceded
victory to Bush.
   Asked when Reagan would begin to make campaign appearances for
Bush, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters on
Friday: ``It hasn't been decided.''
</TEXT>
