<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Liquor,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Want Liquor Banned At New Hotel Unless Parking Increased</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developers of a $41 million luxury hotel near
Beverly Hills have agreed to expand their parking after affluent
neighbors threatened to put a cork in the hotel's liquor permit
application.
   Homeowners who don't want party-goers' cars parked around their
neighborhood will have their chance Tuesday at a hearing by the
Board of Zoning Appeals on the hotel's liquor permit request.
   ``No parking! No booze!'' was the residents' rallying cry at a
recent meeting.
   ``The neighborhood is going to get nothing but more problems out
of this hotel,'' said Harald Hahn, president of a homeowners group
near the 11-story, 311-room Ma Maison Sofitel Hotel being built on
Beverly Boulevard across from the posh Beverly Center shopping mall.
   The scheduled summer opening of the hotel will mark the return
of restaurateur Patrick Terrail's trendy Ma Maison eatery, which
closed on Melrose Avenue in 1985.
   Although the hotel's 328-space garage provides the legal minimum
number of slots, it should be bigger because any overflow will
spill onto already crowded streets, said Diana Plotkin of the
Beverly-Wilshire Homes Association.
   The hotel's developers have agreed to lease several dozen spaces
at a nearby bank for nighttime and weekend use and to squeeze 382
cars into the garage by allowing valet parking only.
   ``We sympathize with what they want: to preserve their life
style and the neighborhood,'' said James Keegan, president of the
firm developing the hotel. ``But at the same time we didn't throw
$40 million into a hole in the ground to have a dry hotel.''
</TEXT>
