<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAfricaSanctions     04-29 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa Sanctions,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partisan Squabbling Derails Sanctions Bill in House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts by House Democrats to advance a
sweeping South African sanctions bill were derailed Friday when
partisan squabbling broke out in the Foreign Affairs Committee and
the measure became entangled with a separate bill on Ethiopia.
   The legislation would cut off virtually all economic relations
between the United States and South Africa within a year. It is
seen by supporters as building upon the limited sanctions imposed
two years ago to force Pretoria to moderate its apartheid policy,
which deprives majority blacks of political and civil rights.
   But the measure is opposed by business interests as too harsh to
have its intended effect, and many Republicans who supported
limited sanctions in 1986 have said they will fight the Democrats
this time.
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, had planned to begin work on the sanctions bill
Friday. He was forced to postpone his panel's meeting until next
week, however, after the measure became entangled in a dispute
about a separate, Republican-sponsored bill to condemn the Marxist
government of Ethiopia.
   ``I guess it reflects some of the rising political tensions'' of
this election year, said Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., a senior
committee member.
   Republicans were holding up the South Africa sanctions bill as
leverage to first force action on the Ethiopian measure. That bill
urges President Reagan to cut off imports of Ethiopian coffee and
deny trade preferences if the Soviet-aligned government continues
to impede relief efforts for starving people in its northern
provinces.
   Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam on April 6 ordered
foreign relief workers out of the provinces of Tigray and Eritrea,
where his forces are at war with secessionist rebels. Mengistu has
been accused of trying to starve his own people into submission,
and more than 2 million people are reported to be at risk of
starvation.
   The Ethiopia sanctions measure, sponsored by Rep. Toby Roth,
R-Wis., was to have been acted on Friday before the committee
turned to consideration of the South Africa sanctions bill. But
Rep. Don Bonker, D-Wash., objected, saying the measure was poorly
written and was being rushed through without proper referral to the
trade subcommittee, which he heads.
   As the committee's meeting hit impasse and broke up, Republicans
cried foul. ``It's a sad mark of politics and procedure,'' Roth
said. ``We've got millions of people starving to death.''
   He accused Bonker, who is running for the Senate in his
forestry-oriented state, of trying to use the situation to advance
a pet bill imposing restrictions on exports of unprocessed logs.
   Bonker had told reporters that bill might come before the full
Foreign Affairs Committee this week, but that did not happen.
Bonker denied any connection between the two bills.
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said he would continue to use House
rules to block consideration of the South Africa bill until the
Democratic-controlled committee acts on Ethiopian sanctions. ``The
Ethiopian bill is much more significant at this point that South
Africa,'' he said.
   But one Democrat said the Republicans were merely using every
tactic they could to delay further action on South Africa, which
Democrats see as a potent political issue in their favor.
   ``When you're looking to sidetrack an issue, your best bet is to
light forest fires all around the place,'' said Rep. Gary Ackerman,
D-N.Y. ``It's a testy time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
