<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GradeSale-Probe     04-29 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grade Sale-Probe,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Classes Canceled Amid Accusations of Grade Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teachers are being questioned and three
classes have been canceled at California State University's
Northridge campus after students reported being offered top grades
for selling raffle tickets, officials said.
   Students reported that the three independent studies courses in
African history and culture also required no classroom attendance
and assigned no course work, said campus spokeswoman Ann Salisbury.
   University Vice President of Academic Affairs Bob Suzuki
announced Thursday that the classes had been canceled and the
school's campus police had launched an investigation.
   ``Because we have been informed that there was no syllabus for
this class and that most students never met with their instructors,
it appears to me that grades were offered in exchange for
activities not directly related to an officially approved course of
study,'' Suzuki said.
   The university is also considering disciplinary action against
two teachers and may turn over the findings of its investigation to
the district attorney's office, Ms. Salisbury said.
   She said interviews with 30 students enrolled in the courses led
to the probe.
   The two teachers being investigated were Eleazu S. Obinna, a
17-year faculty member, and William J. Bellamy, a first-year
lecturer, campus officials said.
   The raffle tickets were allegedly being sold on behalf of United
Crusade Foundation Inc., a non-profit, charitable organization
founded by Obinna.
   ``I have done nothing wrong,'' the Nigerian-born Obinna, 54,
said Thursday. ``I believe this is something concocted by the
administration, not from complaints by students.''
   Obinna said he required 45 hours of course work and graded
students on their participation in minority community affairs.
   Bellamy declined comment.
   Student Laural Isles, 18, said Obinna told her to sell 20
tickets at $5 each for an A grade in his class.
   ``I personally didn't know who was even in charge of the
class,'' said Trey Whitaker, 18, another student in Obinna's class.
``My understanding was that the proceeds were going to charity and
the grade was contingent on how much we sold.''
   Suzuki's statement said the university also was looking into the
legal status of United Crusade Foundation Inc.
   Obinna said the organization has sponsored summer youth job
programs and holiday meals for the homeless. He said it recently
lost its non-profit status, but he renewed it with the state
Thursday.
</TEXT>
