<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Angola 1stLd-Writethru   04-29 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0663,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiations Set for Angola, South-West Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS three grafs background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S., Cuban, South African and Angolan officials
will meet here next week for a two-day conference on troop
withdrawal from Angola and independence for South-West Africa, the
Foreign Office said today.
   The U.S. delegation will be headed by Chester Crocker, U.S.
assistant secretary of state for African affairs and Washington's
chief diplomatic troubleshooter in southern Africa, the U.S.
Embassy said.
   The talks will be held at a secret location in London Tuesday
and Wednesday, British and U.S. officials said.
   The other delegates were not identified, but a South African
Foreign Ministry statement said the participants would not be of
Cabinet rank.
   ``Discussions between the United States, Angola, South Africa
and Cuba, on troop withdrawal from Angola and independence for
Namibia, will take place on May 3 and 4 in Britain,'' a British
Foreign Office spokesman said.
   ``We are pleased to have facilitated and welcome this further
step in the negotiating process.''
   Crocker was in London this week and had talks with his Soviet
counterpart, Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoly Adamishin.
   South-West Africa, or Namibia, is ruled by South Africa in
defiance of a 1966 U.N. demand to give it independence.
   South Africa has said it is willing to give Namibia
independence, but insists Cuba withdraw its estimated 40,000 troops
from neighboring Angola.
   The United States, which has been trying for nine years to
mediate an agreement, backs South Africa's demand that the first
move be a Cuban withdrawal.
   Angola demands that South Africa and the United States stop
backing pro-Western rebels fighting to overthrow its Marxist
government. It says South Africa has 9,000 troops with heavy
artillery in Angolan territory, while South Africa says it has not
had more than 3,000 men there at one time since May 1987.
   South Africa has been waging a 21-year war with Namibian
independence fighters based in Angola, while Angola has been
wracked by civil war since 1975.
   UNITA, the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola,
South Africa's ally in the Angolan civil war, got U.S. aid worth
$15 million last year, including Stinger anti-aircraft missiles.
   In the past few months, most of the heavy fighting has been
around the strategic southeastern city of Cuito Cuanavale.
Cuban-backed Angolan forces still hold the city, although it has
been under regular attack by South African and UNITA troops. The
fighting appears to have reached stalemate in the past two months.
   The town, 190 miles north of the border with South-West Africa,
has a strategic airstrip and is used as a staging post for Angolan
army operations against UNITA.
</TEXT>
