<2ND_LINE>AM-Fraternity Rape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auburn Pi Kappa Alpha Member Arrested in March Rape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to CORRECT that student arrested Friday
was Auburn student, not Florida State, edit to clarify, picking up
10th graf pvs, `University spokeswoman ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Auburn University student was
arrested Friday in connection with an incident last month in which
a woman was repeatedly raped and left unconscious at a Florida
State University fraternity house, authorities said.
   Jason J. McPharlin, 19, of the Albama school's Pi Kappa Alpha
chapter, was charged with one count of accessory to a felony and
one count of failure to report a sexual battery, said Florida State
University police spokesman Jack Handley.
   ``The warrants charged McPharlin with having helped carry an
unconscious sexual battery victim from the Pi Kappa Alpha
fraternity and leaving her in the hallway of the Theta Chi
fraternity house,'' said Handley.
   McPharlin was to be booked into the Leon County jail under a
$6,000 bond.
   Meanwhile, a three-member Florida State committee met for the
third day to discuss what punishment will be handed out to the
fraternity, two of whose members were charged earlier this week
with raping and brutalizing the 18-year-old woman.
   The fraternity was suspended April 22 pending the hearing.
   An interim grand jury report issued last week said the victim
was raped by more than one person and was found at the Theta Chi
fraternity early March 5 ``intoxicated to a life-threatening
degree.''
   She suffered multiple scratches and abrasions, had crude words
and a fraternity symbol written on her thighs and had a .35 percent
blood-alcohol level, more than three times the legal limit for
driving.
   Byron L. Stewart, 21, of Orlando and Daniel G. Oltarsh, 23, of
Fort Lauderdale, both Pi Kappa Alpha members at Florida State, were
freed on $10,000 bond Wednesday after being charged with sexual
battery in the case. Each could face up to life in prison if
convicted.
   University spokeswoman Annette Lee said the committee
considering permanent sanctions against the fraternity will pass on
its recommendation to Dean of Students James Hayes.
   On Wednesday, the Pi Kappa Alpha fraternity at Stetson
University in Deland was suspended for a year following rape
allegations. Stetson officials said there was not enough evidence
to determine if there was probable cause for legal charges.
   The school suspended five students, including two seniors, and
ordered 27 members to move out of their fraternity house because of
sexual misconduct and alcohol abuse at a party.
</TEXT>
