<HEAD>Actor James Garner Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor James Garner was discharged from
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center on Friday, eight days after undergoing
coronary bypass surgery, a hospital spokesman said.
   ``The surgery went very smoothly, his recovery has been
outstanding and he was released at 9:30 a.m.,'' said spokesman Ron
Wise.
   Garner, 60, the Emmy-winning star of the old television series
``The Rockford Files'' and ``Maverick,'' underwent five hours of
surgery April 21.
   Garner entered the hospital for tests April 18. Doctors had
planned to perform surgery for an aneurysm on his aorta, the main
artery carrying blood from the heart. But after reviewing test
results, doctors recommended the quintuple bypass operation first.
Surgery for the aneurysm will be scheduled later, hospital
officials said.
   Garner has blamed his heart problems on cigarettes.
   People magazine once called the ruggedly handsome Garner ``the
last real man'' in America, and he is a spokesman for the beef
industry's $30 million ``Beef, Real Food for Real People''
advertising campaign.
