<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ArmsTreaty 3rdLd-Writethru a0669 04-29 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0669,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democratic leader Robert C. Byrd said
today he had tentatively decided to open debate May 11 on a
U.S.-Soviet treaty to ban medium-range nuclear missiles, but only
if the two superpowers could clear up differences on verification
and other issues.
   The State Department, meanwhile, urged the Senate ``to move
forward expeditiously'' and said the treaty's anti-cheating
provisions were effective.
   Charles E. Redman, the department spokesman, said the Soviets
had taken a ``restrictive'' view of the right of U.S. monitors to
inspect containers for missile components as well as access to
Soviet facilities.
   He said the State Department had raised the issue with the
Soviets at a senior diplomatic level and was waiting for a reply.
``So we will see what we get,'' Redman said.
   The State Department official called the Soviet interpretation
of the verification procedures unacceptable.
   Byrd made clear that debate would not begin on May 11 _ less
than three weeks before President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev meet in Moscow _ if areas of concern were still
unresolved.
   Reagan administration officials are urging the legislators to
approve the pact before the May 29-June 2 summit to enhance
prospects for the two nations agreeing to other weapons restraints.
   The majority leader said he is especially concerned by published
reports quoting ranking Soviet military leaders as appearing to be
back away from mutual understandings on what would be permitted
under treaty provisions allowing on-site verification inspection. s
Byrd called on both Washington and Moscow to quickly deal with that
question as well as others, including a treaty ambiguity on what
constitutes a weapons delivery system and whether or not such
``Star Wars'' weapons as those using laser beams or particle ray
generatiors are covered by the pact.
   Earlier, a U.S. arms control official said the embassy in Moscow
has been in touch with Soviet officials to resolve the differences
they raised on how to verify compliance with the treaty.
   ``We anticipate that it'll be cleared up,'' the official of the
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency said Thursday, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``We don't think this will be a big
problem.''
   Meanwhile, the Senate Intelligence Committee, in a closed
session this week, voted sharp cuts in the budgets for intelligence
agencies because of irritation at the administration's failure to
seek improved surveillance systems for use in verifying the treaty,
the New York Times reported today.
   Committee chairman Sen. David L. Boren, D-Okla., said in an
interview that he is prepared to filibuster the treaty unless the
White House requests the money the intelligence panel believes is
needed for monitoring, the Times reported.
</TEXT>
