<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-Reax     04-29 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Reax,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Exiles Denounce U.S.-Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian exiles on Friday blasted a
U.S.-sponsored deal that would allow Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to
resign as defense chief, calling the change purely cosmetic and one
that could create an anti-American backlash.
   The U.S. attorney's office, meanwhile, said drug indictments
against the Panamanian strongman remain in force.
   In Washington, sources reported Friday that Noriega had agreed
to step down from his powerful post as head of Panama's military,
but would not leave his country immediately as U.S. officials had
initially demanded.
   The reports did not say whether dismissing Noriega's
cocaine-trafficking charges in Miami and Tampa was part of the
deal, but such offers have reportedly been made in the past.
   ``This sounds like a surrender with cosmetics,'' said Roberto
Eisenmann, exiled publisher of the closed independent newspaper La
Prensa. ``This is the same mistake all over again _ the United
States intervening in Panama, ignoring totally the political forces
of the country.''
   Gilberto Mallol, exile representative here of the Panamanian
opposition umbrella group, the Civic Crusade, agreed.
   ``This cosmetic solution will only take the country down the
road to disaster,'' said Mallol. ``The Reagan administration has no
right to decide Noriega can remain in Panama.''
   Mallol disputed U.S. contentions that Noriega will be out of
power as soon as he is out of uniform. ``Obviously, this deal shows
Noriega is making conditions. He will continue to interfere and
continue the militarization of Panama.''
   Mallol warned that the deal could backfire on the United States,
causing a wave of anti-American sentiment among Noriega opponents.
   Eisenmann said the opposition will not let up because of the
deal, noting the latest outbreak of anti-Noriega demonstrations
Thursday. Hundreds of people demonstrated in Panama City, burning
barricades and chanting against the military leader.
   Both Mallol and Eisenmann agreed that Noriega should remain in
Panama only if he agrees to submit to Panamanian justice.
   They also said the nation must move toward a true democracy and
break the Panamanian Defense Force's stranglehold on power.
   ``The problem isn't Noriega,'' said Mallol, ``It's the military.
If the militarization of Panama is not ended, what looks like a
short-term solution will lose Panama in the long term.''
   Meanwhile, the U.S. attorney's office in Miami said it had not
been notified of any change in the status of Noriega's indictment,
which accuses him of accepting $4.6 million in bribes from the
Medellin Cartel to protect its cocaine-smuggling operations in
Panama. He is also under indictment in Tampa on separate drug
charges.
   ``The only two people who can dismiss an indictment are the
Attorney General of the United States or the U.S. Attorney for the
district in which the indictment was brought,'' said Richard
Gregorie, chief assistant U.S. attorney and lead prosecutor in the
case. ``As far as we are concerned, no dismissal has been entered
here.''
</TEXT>
