<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Church     04-29 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Church,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Of Underground Preacher Belies Relaxed Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The apparent arrest of an underground Christian
preacher comes during a time of unusual tolerance by the Communist
government toward China's illegal ``house churches.''
   Another underground minister in Beijing said authorities
recently have not stopped him and other preachers from holding
weekly services in their homes for dozens and even hundreds of
people even though they violate China's ban on preaching outside
state-sanctioned churches.
   The minister, who spoke on condition of anonymity, painted a
picture of an underground movement toughened by past harsh
repression and confident it can survive any setbacks.
   ``I was in prison more than 20 years _ I'm experienced,'' the
74-year-old minister said grinning broadly. ``If I am arrested
again and die for the Lord it is glorious.''
   He and Xu Yongzhe, who disappeared April 16 and is believed to
have been arrested, are among thousands of Protestant ministers and
Catholic priests and nuns who refuse to join the official churches.
Instead, they preach at home.
   About 8 million people belong to the official Protestant and
Catholic churches in China, and nearly as many are believed to
belong to the house churches.
   The believers make up a tiny fraction of China's more than 1
billion people.
   Although some house church preachers and members remain in
prisons and labor camps _ the minister said there were 500 in
custody _ the government is more tolerant of their activities than
ever before in nearly four decades of Communist rule.
   The minister said authorities have not bothered him even though
he remains under probation after being freed from jail in 1979, and
holds two services each Sunday. Forty people crowd into his
one-room home _ something impossible to hide from neighbors in
Beijing's tightly packed residential areas.
   Xu's arrest, however, was no surprise. He had been a fugitive
since 1982, when he escaped from a jail in Henan in central China,
hopped on a bicycle and peddled into hiding. He ran an underground
seminary but was not especially prominent among house church
preachers, his fellow minister said.
   Xu, believed to be about 50, had been in jail only a few months
charged with illegal proselytizing. The other minister said he did
not know Xu's sentence.
   He said he'd been expecting Xu to visit the day he disappeared.
   Instead, Xu's sister came alone and reported that Xu disappeared
while visiting the Beijing Zoo with two friends, the second day
after he left his hiding place in northern China to hear visiting
American evangelist Billy Graham preach in Beijing.
   He said Xu's sister received no confirmation from authorities
that he had been arrested, but it appeared certain. The Ministry of
State Security refused to answer queries about Xu.
   Graham said Friday in Hong Kong at the end of his 16-day Chinese
tour that he asked high-level Chinese officials about the reported
arrest but received neither confirmation nor denial.
   The renowned Southern Baptist minister said he prayed for Xu and
told Chinese officials his reaction to the report, but could not
otherwise intervene.
   ``Our hope is from the Lord, not from Billy Graham,'' Xu's
colleague said.
   The minister said he studied theology under Western missionaries
in the 1930s, but Xu and younger house preachers learned through
self-study and informal training by house church preachers. Funds
and thousands of Bibles are smuggled in each year from religious
groups outside China.
   The minister said the house churches have no central
organization and do not oppose the government.
   ``We have no time to mess with the things of the world,'' he
said.
   ``I believe politics and religion should be separate. The
(official) churches have become a tool of the government. They
preach to ... serve the modernization policy.''
   Indeed, China's Catholic church does not recognize the Vatican.
   During the 1966-76 far leftist Cultural Revolution all churches
were closed and religious activity was banned.
   Although some churches have been reopened since Deng Xiaoping
came to power in 1978, ministers and priests are closely
circumscribed. They cannot give religious instruction to anyone
under 18, and must support government campaigns.
   Preaching on themes such as diligence, honesty and respect for
parents is considered to have social value. But the Christian
belief that Jesus Christ will come again at the end of the world is
discouraged as likely to undermine hard work.
   ``We are free _ but only inside the circle,'' the minister said,
running a finger around the rim of a rice bowl in illustration.
</TEXT>
