<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Gulf-MissingCopter     04-29 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Missing Copter,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps today declared two officers
missing from last week's fighting in the Persian Gulf ``killed in
action'' and disclosed that they reported a hostile radar had
locked on their helicopter gunship before it disappeared.
   The corps, in a statement, refused to say the AH-1T Cobra
gunship flown by Capt. Stephen C. Leslie and Capt. Kenneth W. Hill
had definitely been shot down by Iranian forces, as Iran has
claimed.
   But the statement said: ``After reviewing the circumstances, (a
Marine) fact-finding body determined the disappearance was a direct
result of hostile action, sustained in combat or relating thereto.
   ``In making its recommendation, the fact-finding body provided
the following explanation: `While being vectored to identify an
unknown surface contact, Captains Hill and Leslie reported a fire
control radar lock-on. The USS Wainwright lost communication and
radar contact with Captains Hill and Leslie.'''
</TEXT>
