<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Plant     04-29 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Plant,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Plant Closing Law Doesn't Apply in Possible Cullinet
Layoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JOHN DIAMOND</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts-based company reported to be
planning major layoffs has failed to notify the state at a time
when Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis has been
touting a state law on the subject.
   A state official says the law wouldn't apply in the case.
   Dukakis wants President Reagan to sign a federal trade bill that
requires companies to warn workers 60 days before a major layoff or
plant shutdown. He has emphasized that Massachusetts was one of the
first states to impose its own plant-closing law.
   The issue has been of particular importance to the Massachusetts
governor as he campaigns in industrial sections of Ohio and
Indiana, which have primaries Tuesday.
   Dukakis administration officials said it was only this week that
they saw press reports that Cullinet Software Inc. planned to lay
off 400 of its 2,400 workers Monday and that half the layoffs would
occur at the company's Westwood, Mass., plant.
   Cullinet spokeswoman Frances Wheeler termed reports of the
layoffs ``rumors.'' She said she was familiar with the state
plant-closing law, but ``we don't have any set, bound company
policy about notifying.''
   ``Of course we would always prefer advance warning,'' said Rick
Gureghian, spokesman for Dukakis' Executive Office of Economic and
Manpower Affairs.
   However, unlike the federal proposal, the Massachusetts law
requests but does not require companies to provide advance warning
of plant closings. Dukakis defends it as effective and says there
are sanctions to make companies comply. ``In many ways,'' he said
of the state's law, ``it goes beyond this (federal proposal) and in
other ways it doesn't.''
   Gureghian said the state defines a plant closing as laying off
90 percent of the work force at a plant. A ``partial closing,''
Gureghian said, is ``a permanent cessation of a major, discreet
portion'' of a company or division.
   The reported plans for Cullinet layoffs would not apply to
either definition, he said.
</TEXT>
