<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-McDonalds     04-29 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-McDonalds,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McGlasnost: Golden Arches Vault Iron Curtain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest burger maker in the free world wants
to find out if it can cut the mustard in Moscow, but only after it
goes Hungary.
   McDonald's announced Friday it will open the first of a string
of eateries in downtown Moscow next year.
   It may not mean golden arches in Red Square, but it will mean
Muscovites can munch fries, slurp shakes and gobble ``Big Maks''
just like their Western counterparts, courtesy of McGlasnost.
   ``I think the McDonald's in Moscow will be the highest volume
McDonald's in the world,'' predicted George A. Cohon, president of
McDonald's Restaurants of Canada Ltd., after signing a joint pact
with the Moscow city government.
   Meanwhile, the first McDonald's in a Soviet bloc country opens
its doors Saturday in Hungary. The Budapest burger emporium was
dedicated on Friday.
   Last month, McDonald's opened a restaurant in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, its first in a communist nation. Impatient customers
waiting in line on opening day became so unruly that police were
called.
   Although five more restaurants are planned for Belgrade, Moscow
could be the big enchilada for McDonald's, which had worldwide
sales of $14.3 billion last year.
   Cohon and Vladimir I. Malishkov, chief of food services for the
Soviet capital, signed an agreement for the creation of up to 20
fast-food eateries in Moscow and the building of a commissary to
process beef, potatoes and other foods McDonald's uses.
   ``A Big Mac, our world-famous sandwich, will taste the same in
Moscow as it does in Toronto, or Tokyo, or Rio, or New York,''
Cohon vowed at a news conference in Moscow's city hall.
   The agreement, which gives McDonald's of Canada a 49 percent
share in the Soviet-controled joint firm, is the latest business
venture concluded by the Soviets with a foreign company, and th
first with a Canadian firm.
   Last year, the Kremlin enacted a new law on joint ventures in a
bid to woo capital, technology and expertise from abroad. The
reform is part of changes enacted under Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev designed to improve the quality and quantity of consumer
goods.
   Pepsico Inc. last September signed a contract to open two Pizza
Hut restaurants in Moscow in a joint venture. A New Jersey company
called AstroPizza brought a van into the capital this month to
serve pizza to Soviets and foreigners, and plans to open a joint
venture restaurant in Moscow later this year.
   Malishkov and Moscow Deputy Mayor Valery A. Zharov said the
Soviets want to draw upon the expertise of the U.S.-based
McDonald's to improve service in their country's food industry.
   And the Moscow restaurants are only the beginning.
   ``We're not thinking of just opening 20 McDonald's in this
country,'' Cohon said. ``There will be many more.''
   Soviets will be able to buy a Big Mac, the chain's double-patty
hamburger sandwich, for about 2 rubles, or roughly $3.
   The first McDonald's in the Soviet capital is expected to open
on Gorky Street next year, Cohon said. But nobody will say where.
   ``We don't want to create any lines,'' Zharov said with a smile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i LaborUnrestSpreadstoSecondPlantinWeekofStrikes     04-29
0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Labor Unrest Spreads to Second Plant in Week of Strikes</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of employees struck for higher
pay at a heavy machinery plant Friday, capping a week of Poland's
worst labor trouble since the Communist authorities suppressed
Solidarity more than six years ago.
   Warsaw police detained Jacek Kuron, a senior adviser to the
outlawed union. A member of his household said three
plainclothesmen arrived as Kuron was being interviewed by telephone
by a Western radio station.
   Strikes began Monday with bus and streetcar drivers at Bydgoszcz
in the west. Workers at the huge Lenin steel works at Nowa Huta in
the southern industrial belt followed suit Tuesday, and on Friday
it was the machinery plant at Stalowa Wola, about 65 miles east of
Nowa Huta.
   Another job action was threatened for over the May Day holiday
weekend. Solidarity activists in Krakow's municipal transport
company said in a statement they were calling a strike for 6 a.m.
Saturday to support the Nowa Huta workers.
   Workers demand pay increases of 50 percent or more. Prices rose
42 percent in the first three months of 1988 because the government
reduced subsidies on many consumer items.
   The government has both threatened dismissals and promised to
improve wages. At Bydgoszcz, the 2,800 drivers won a 60 percent pay
increase with an 11-hour strike.
   Officials of Solidarity threatened more strikes if authorities
use force against strikers. They said workers in at least four
other cities had declared support for the Nowa Huta action and
issued strike alerts.
   In West Germany, the newspaper Bild quoted Solidarity founder
Lech Walesa as saying in an interview the strike ``has to spread
because the economic situation is bad. We really didn't want to
strike because strikes have never filled a bread basket, but the
government leaves us no choice but to fight for our rights.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said an attempt to start a
strike failed at the 18,000-worker Stalowa Wola heavy machinery
plant, but the official news agency PAP said later at least one
department was shut down.
   A Roman Catholic priest in Stalowa Wola, the Rev. Jan Niemiec,
said about 7,000 strikers were occupying three department and the
strike began when about 5,000 first-shift employees quit working.
He said management tried to lock out most of the second-shift
workers but some broke in.
   Niemiec said the number of strikers could be as high as 9,000,
but he could not confirm the figure. He said the information came
from a member of the strike committee.
   In Poland, strikers customarily go to their places of employment
but do not work. Often they hold meetings or pass out leaflets.
   About 12,000 workers were striking for a fourth day at the Lenin
plant in Nowa Huta, which means New Steel Mill and was built as a
model city in the 1950s just outside Krakow.
   Management representatives met with the plant's
government-sanctioned union but refused to deal with the unofficial
committee that claims to represent at least half the plant's 32,000
workers.
   The Nowa Huta strike is the biggfest in Poland since those that
swept the country after food price increases in 1980, bringing down
a government and giving birth to Solidarity. The independent union
federation was suppressed, then outlawed, after martial law was
declared in December 1981.
   Urban said there had been ``preventative detentions'' in Poland
this week, but did not say how many. Kuron, the Solidarity adviser,
said by telephone before his detention that 25 people had been
picked up around the country in the past two days.
   Bronislaw Geremek, an adviser to Walesa, said police stopped his
car Thursday in Stalowa Wola and detained him, Solidarity spokesman
Janusz Onyszkiewicz and Warsaw Solidarity leader Zbigniew Bujak. He
said Onyszkiewicz and Bujak remained in custody.
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity spokesman in Warsaw, said
many police were in Stalowa Wola and at least four Solidarity
activists were detained.
   Demands at Nowa Huta are representative: recognition of their
union rights, release of detained Solidarity activists and an
immediate 50 percent increase in monthly pay that averages the
equivalent of $105.
   The strike committee said it had sent a letter to Pope John Paul
II, who was Krakow's archbishop before becoming pope, that began:
``We address you with our words of devotion and respect. We are
sending those words from the place of our work and struggle for
decent payment.''
   Urban told a news conference in Warsaw: ``The situation in
Poland is not dramatic, with only one strike in Nowa Huta and an
attempt to organize a strike that failed in Stalowa Wola.''
   He said the Nowa Huta management had decided to fire striking
workers.
   Labor Minister Ireneneusz Sekula said the government would
announce tax law changes and other measures in a few days allowing
enterprises to grant higher pay. He said he could not be more
specific.
   Trybuna Ludu, the Communist Party newspaper, attacked ``Mr.
Walesa and company ... who are trying to use the uneasy situation
for their own political goals.''
   It said demands for higher wages were ``calls for anarchy, to
start unrestrained inflation, to create a situation in which we
would once again have empty store shelves and the creditors would
lose their growing confidence in us.''
</TEXT>
