<1ST_LINE>r i BC-CampaignAbroad     04-29 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Commentators Focus Now on Bush and Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In their comments on the U.S. presidential campaign,
editorialists and commentators abroad now are focusing on Vice
President George Bush, who has enough delegates to win the
Republican nomination, and Gov. Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
front-runner.
   Here is some of they had to say recently:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Daily Telegraph of London (conservative): ``Americans face
a choice in November between dull men, but not dangerous ones, in a
race that may be too close to call.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANADA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Maclean's (independent weekly news magazine): ``Both are
cautious pragmatists who have throughout their careers eschewed
sweeping ideological visions and popular stands. ... Both parties
are poised to select standard-bearers with a lack of flamboyance
after eight years with a crowd-pleasing actor in the White House.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CHILE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _El Mercurio of Santiago (conservative): ``The present
presidential campaign in the U.S. is increasingly looking like the
one in 1976. That year, the Democratic candidate (Jimmy Carter) ..
. was a state governor, virtually unknown until shortly before,
with no experience in federal politics, who based his political
appeal on his personal honesty and his difference from the previous
president (Gerald Ford). ... The man who will probably be the
candidate now is Michael Dukakis, Massachusetts governor, unknown
to world opinion until a few months ago, a technocrat without
charisma.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH AFRICA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The South African Broadcasting Corp. (governent-controlled) in
a commentary: ``So far, South Africa has not been a high-profile
issue in the election campaign, despite the efforts of Jesse
Jackson _ who will nevertheless undoubtedly have a hand in shaping
the Democratic Party's final election manifesto. Both Bush and
Dukakis believe in applying pressure on South Africa, but for Bush
(who opposes sanctions) it should take the form of greater
involvement, whereas Dukakis (who supports further sanctions)
appears to favor an isolationst approach. ... While Bush has
strongly endorsed the Reagan policy on opposing Soviet expansionism
by proxy _ in Angola, Central America and elsewhere _ Dukakis has
criticized all forms of American intervention in such conflict
situations.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PERU</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _El Diario of Lima (communist): ``Whichever candidate wins, the
imperialistic and warlike nature of the United States will not
change nor will its relations with Latin America, which, as we
know, are causing struggles for liberation and people's wars.''
</TEXT>
