<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultiplePersonality     04-29 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Personality,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Moves To Free Multiple Personality Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled Friday that a man found
innocent by reason of insanity on rape charges because he had
multiple personalities is now well, apparently clearing the way for
his release.
   William Milligan has been confined in various mental
institutions around the state for much of the time since the
original ruling in 1977.
   Judge C. Howard Johnson said psychiatric and psychological
reports show Milligan's multiple personalities have fused, and that
he is well.
   Milligan, who was charged with rape and abduction in three
attacks in the Columbus area, once had more than 20 personalities,
according to the book ``The Minds of Billy Milligan.''
   As a result of the judge's ruling, Milligan was transferred from
the maximum security section of the Timothy Moritz Forensics Center
here to the Central Ohio Psychiatric Hospital.
   Milligan had been confined at the Moritz center since he was
captured in December 1986 after escaping from the Central Ohio
Psychiatric Hospital on July 4, 1986.
   Officials say it will take about a month to place him in private
housing and help him try to find a job.
   During his court appearance Friday, Milligan pledged to obey the
law and said he wants to be a tax-paying citizen. He said he wants
to continue his work as an artist, or find a job involving
computers.
   Milligan still must undergo therapy twice a week for the next
year, according to the judge's ruling.
   Milligan also was charged in a November 1984 shooting at a barn
on property owned by a worker at a mental health facility where he
was a patient.
   No one was injured in the shooting, and the case was dismissed
after defense attorneys claimed that Milligan's constitutional
rights were violated when a jailer recorded his side of a phone
conversation with his attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
