<DOCNO> AP880429-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     04-29 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikhs Militants Attack Troops Outside Temple; 24 Dead Throughout
Punjab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants holed up in the Golden
Temple attacked para-military troops on Friday and at least 24
people were killed in other parts of Punjab in separatist violence,
police and news reports said.
   The slayings raised to 862 the number of people killed this year
in attacks blamed on the radical movement for a Sikh homeland.
   At least six people were killed and 80 injured when five bombs
exploded on Friday afternoon in the crowded main market of Batala
town, the United News of India said. It said police clamped an
indefinite curfew on the town, 25 miles northeast of Amritsar,
after the explosions.
   At least two of the victims were reported to be militants. Three
people who were believed to have placed the explosives were
arrested, UNI said.
   Merchants around Amritsar's Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest
shrine, closed their shops when militants fired at a patrol of the
Central Reserve Police on Friday, said police superintendent Baldev
Singh.
   The attack started when the troops attempted to arrest a wanted
militant as he was heading for the shrine, Baldev Singh said. The
troops returned the fire but the militant escaped in the confusion.
   One woman was injured in the 20-minute firefight, he said. The
attack prompted authorities to place the city's police force on a
``red alert'' although security forces did not attempt to enter the
temple.
   Security forces have entered the temple previously but usually
avoid doing so because of Sikh sentiment. Police estimate that at
least 100 militants, armed with automatic rifles, are hiding in the
shrine.
   In other militant attacks Thursday night, at least seven Hindus
were shot and killed in two villages near Amritsar. Five Sikhs were
killed in a raid on a farmer's home, also near Amritsar.
   At least six other people, including four Sikhs and two
unidentified victims, were shot and killed in other attacks through
the state.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million people but make up a
majority in Punjab. The militants have been agitating for an
independent homeland since 1983, claiming discrimination by the
Hindu majority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
