<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DayintheLife     04-29 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Day in the Life,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Photographers Make `Visual Time Capsule' Of California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hundred photographers fanned out across
California on Friday, using thousands of rolls of film for an
everyday portrait of the state.
   It was just another day in Chinatown, where inside a Catholic
school, children began with the pledge of allegiance, a prayer and
a song. Seny Norasingh, one of the photographers for the planned
book ``A Day in the Life of California,'' also was there.
   Norasingh watched the first-graders as they chanted a phonics
lesson, then began to use his camera, crouching near the small
desks. Several other photographers took photos of Norasingh or of
their colleagues taking pictures of him.
   Meanwhile, 99 other men and women with cameras were on
assignment in Chico, Stockton, the Silicon Valley, Fresno, Yosemite
and other places between Crescent City and El Centro for the book.
   The volume, set for fall publication, is part of a series of
books containing photographs taken in a certain place in a single
day.
   ``The concept is extremely easy to grasp and elegantly simple.
That is, you're creating a visual time capsule, a family album,''
said David Cohen, who with Rick Smolan, began the series seven
years ago.
   The books have focused on Australia, Hawaii, Canada, Spain,
America and the Soviet Union.
   Cohen, formerly managing editor of Contact Press Images in New
York, and Smolan, a former Contact photographer, have published
most of the books themselves, but they didn't achieve great
commercial success until the book on America came out in 1986.
   Cohen said he believes a market for another book on California
exists, despite a glut of coffee-table books filled with photos of
the state, because most are filled with cliches of beauty spots
``or they go completely in the other direction and you see a freak
show.''
</TEXT>
