<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Tiffany     04-29 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Tiffany,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Removed From Trust Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of teen rocker Tiffany has been
replaced as trustee of the singer's $100,000 trust fund in the
latest development of legal wrangling between the two.
   Janie C. Williams of suburban Norwalk said in an interview
published Friday by the Los Angeles Times that she was removed as
her 16-year-old daughter's trustee Wednesday by Superior Court
Judge Kenneth Black.
   All court documents filed in the dispute have been sealed, and
all hearings have been closed.
   Black named the Bank of California and the accounting firm of
Prager & Fenton as new trustees; boosted the percentage of
Tiffany's record earnings that must go into the trust fund from 30
percent to 50 percent; and authorized the new trustees to make
income tax payments out of the account.
   Tiffany hired attorney John Frankenheimer three weeks ago to act
on her behalf in freeing her finances from both her mother and
manager George Tobin.
   Tiffany has three Top 10 singles, including ``I Think We're
Alone Now,'' and sold more than 4 million copies of her first
album, meaning her royalties should amount to more than $2 million,
according to Tobin's contract with MCA Records, the Times reported.
   Ms. Williams told the Times and alleged in court documents that
Tiffany and Tobin were working toward a break between the singer
and her immediate family, beginning on March 9 when Tiffany's
mother reported her missing because she failed to return home from
Tobin's North Hollywood recording studio.
   The rock star, who does not use her last name, told the Norwalk
Sheriff's Station she was not a runaway, and later filed in court
for status as an emancipated minor, meaning she would have adult
rights in contractual matters.
   ``I felt that George wanted all the control and Tiffany went
along with it because she had her dream of being a star and he
(Tobin) could give it to her,'' Ms. Williams told the newspaper.
``I was never introduced as Tiffany's mother. I was never
introduced to anybody of any great importance. George didn't want
anybody to know I was Tiffany's mother.''
   In late March, Tiffany's aunt, Julie Abbas, was appointed
temporary guardian pending the outcome of the emancipation
proceedings. No hearings have been scheduled on the matter, which
is being handled by a court-appointed mediator.
   Tobin's production contract with Tiffany gives him 50 percent of
her royalties, and a management agreement grants him 20 percent of
her concert earnings.
   Along with those earnings, Tiffany has a $350,000 merchandising
deal with Winterland Productions for Tiffany clothing and
souvenirs, said Ms. Williams' attorney, Neal Goldstein.
   He claimed Tobin ``is attempting to kidnap her through the
court. It's a judicial kidnapping.''
   ``That statement is not worthy of a response,'' Frankenheimer
said. ``We believe the proper forum for deciding this matter is the
court and not the press.''
   Ms. Williams told the newspaper she believes Tobin now could
gain control of the trust, even though Black handed its control
over to neutral third parties.
   Goldstein said Ms. Williams would seek a reconsideration of the
decision, or appeal it.
</TEXT>
