<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TruckersProtest Bjt   04-29 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truckers Protest, Bjt,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truck Drivers Protest 55 mph Speed Limit With Convoys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY ROSE DONAHUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disgruntled truckers are queuing up into
50-rig convoys and creeping along Indiana interstates to protest a
new state law that has boosted the gasoline tax and lowered the
speed limit for large vehicles.
   The convoys are a new wrinkle in a month-old protest by truckers
boycotting Indiana truckstops, gas stations and restaurants to call
attention to regulations that hurt their business.
   State police have tracked 12 convoys since Tuesday night, when
the first was reported, Lt. Ken Hollingsworth said Friday.
   The lined-up trucks were moving about 40-55 mph, staying in one
lane for the most part, and not interfering with regular vehicular
traffic, said Hollingsworth.
   The convoys averaged about 50 semi tractor-trailers, and most
were reported on Interstate 70, which passes from Ohio to Illinois
through Indianapolis.
   The truckers are unhappy with a state law that went into effect
April 1 lowering the speed limit for heavy trucks from 65 mph to 55
mph on rural sections of interstates. For light trucks and cars,
the speed limit remains 65 mph.
   Indiana also boosted its gasoline tax by 1 cent per gallon
earlier this month.
   Ron Vernon, a trucker from Cedar Rapids, Iowa, said the lowered
speed limit would take money out of his pocket.
   ``If I slow down, I lose $2 or $3 per hour,'' said Vernon, who
had stopped Friday to eat at the Indy 500 Truck Plaza in
Whitestown, just south of Indianapolis. ``We're the only occupation
in the country that gets penalized for working overtime.''
   Truckers weren't the only ones complaining.
   Dave Martin, owner of the Stop 1 Truck Plaza in Cambridge City,
said the boycott had cut his food and fuel sales by 30 percent.
   Martin said although he thought the truckers have a legitimate
complaint, he does not approve of their methods.
   ``I agree the state is doing the wrong thing, but why don't they
go to the Legislature and circle the wagons?'' Martin asked.
   The boycott was the brainchild of Cincinnati disc jockey Dale
Sommers, whose ``Interstate 700'' show is broadcast nightly on
WLW-AM.
   Sommers, who goes by the name ``Truckin' Bozo'' on the air, is
one of the founders of the four-month-old North American
Professional Truckers Association, which represents about 2,000
truckers. He said he drove an 18-wheeler for one week in 1968.
   ``Their votes are in another state and don't count in Indiana,''
Sommers said of his trucker listeners and why he urged the boycott
of truckstops, gas stations and restaurants in the state. ``You
have to make the voters in Indiana pay attention.''
   Indianapolis independent contractor James Walden said the
Indiana protest may be the start of a nationwide movement.
   ``This thing's going to grow. It's starting here, but it's going
coast to coast,'' said Walden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChemicalWeapons     04-29 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Weapons,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Breakthrough In Sight For Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 40-nation Geneva Conference on Disarmament
wound up its spring session Friday with no breakthrough in sight on
a global ban on chemical weapons even though many delegates agree
the ban is more urgent than ever.
   Negotiations on a convention prohibiting the development,
production, and stockpiling of chemical weapons and providing for
their destruction dominated the three-month meeting.
   However, early pronouncements that a text could be finalized
this year clashed with the reality of the complexities involved,
delegates said.
   Hungary's David Meiszter, president of the conference for April,
told a press conference that he was optimistic that agreement will
come ``in the near future.''
   But other conference sources, while acknowledging further
progress, simply said many unresolved problems make any predictions
impossible.
   At the same time, addresses to the conference have stressed that
the continued use of chemical weapons in the war between Iraq and
Iran have added urgency to the 20-year-old negotiations.
   The latest addition to the potential stumbling blocks is
France's insistence on provisions allowing ``security stocks'' of
chemical weapons for eight years after the convention enters into
force.
   France argues that such a possibility is needed in view of the
``very large disproportion'' between existing chemical stocks. This
is an evident reference to the Soviet arsenal.
   The Soviets say they have 50,000 tons of chemical weapons, but
Western intelligence sources say that is a gross understatement.
   Obsolete U.S. chemical weapons stockpiled in West Germany are to
be removed in 1992 under an informal understanding between
Washington and Bonn. This would leave the Soviets with the only
chemical weapons left on European territory.
   Diplomatic sources who insisted on anonymity said no other
delegation supports the French proposal because in effect it would
give countries that do not have chemical weapons the go-ahead to
start production of the arms the moment the convention is ratified.
   ``It is the top issue now,'' said one Western source. ``I can't
see any treaty if France sticks to its position.''
   The chief U.S. representative, ambassador Max Friedersdorf, was
quoted in an interview as saying that the negotiations are getting
to the point ``where we are going to have one (a ban) or not going
to have one.''
   Friedersdorf said the problems with the treaty range from
details of anti-cheating provisions to monitoring the civilian
industry to make surce that chemicals are not diverted to hostile
uses.
   The interview was printed in the U.S. Mission's Daily Bulletin.
It did not include any mention of the French proposal.
   Up to now, the Soviet Union and the United States are the only
member countries that have admitted possession of chemical weapons.
The United States has not officially disclosed its reserves but
they are generally reported to total less than 30,000 tons.
   Western sources estimate at least 15 other countries may have
chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SiameseTwins     04-29 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Siamese Twins,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Operation Planned To Separate Twins Joined At Head</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical team plans a
marathon, high-risk operation to separate 16-month-old Siamese
twins joined at the head, doctors said Friday.
   Doctors at Baragwanath Hospital, the main hospital in the black
township outside Johannesburg, performed two preliminary operations
in October in preparation for Tuesday's surgery. The procedure is
expected to take at least nine hours.
   The twin girls, Mpho and Mphonyana, were born Dec. 7, 1986, to
Sophie Mathibela, an unmarried, 33-year-old black domestic worker
who earns about $60 a month.
   The girls share a major blood vessel in their heads. Doctors
partially clamped the vein in the earlier operations in hopes that
lesser blood vessels would take over its functions.
   Dr. Robert Lipschitz, head of the medical team, said the chances
for success were not high, but that doctors would not sacrifice one
of the girls to save the other.
   ``This is going to be a long, lengthy, intricate operation which
carries many dangers with it,'' Lipschitz told a news conference
Friday. ``The prognosis is still very grave.''
   ``Though the chances are still not in both the children's favor,
at this moment they appear to stand the best chance that we can
give them under the present state of the art,'' he said.
   The girls have a combined weight of 33 pounds. Mpho appears to
be developing normally and recently began to speak, while Mphonyana
is slightly smaller and does not appear to be as advanced, the
hospital said.
   The Baragwanath doctors have received advice from Johns Hopkins
Hospital in Baltimore, where in September doctors separated West
German twins joined at the head. Both boys survived and were sent
home in March, but they reportedly are suffering physical and
mental problems.
   Ms. Mathibela was asked to make a $5 contribution to the costs
of the operation, which otherwise are being covered by the hospital
and the University of the Witwatersrand medical school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
