<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Gulf-MissingCopter     04-29 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Missing Copter,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Declare Missing Pilots Killed in Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Marine helicopter pilots missing since
U.S.-Iranian fighting in the Persian Gulf on April 18 were declared
``killed in action'' Friday after the corps disclosed that a
hostile radar had targeted their copter before it disappeared.
   A Marine fact-finding board, ``after reviewing all the evidence
in this case, determined that there was sufficient evidence to
conclude that these Marines had been killed as a result of hostile
action, sustained in combat or relating thereto,'' the corps said
in a statement.
   The corps refused to say the AH-1T Cobra gunship flown by Capt.
Stephen C. Leslie and Capt. Kenneth W. Hill had definitely been
shot down by Iranian forces, as Iran has claimed.
   But the statement conceded: ``In making its recommendation, the
fact-finding body provided the following explanation: `While being
vectored (directed) to identify an unknown surface contact, Capts.
Hill and Leslie reported a fire control radar lock-on. The USS
Wainwright lost communication and radar contact with Capts. Hill
and Leslie.'''
   The term ``surface contact'' is normally used to refer to a
radar signal indicating the presence of a boat. A fire control
radar is used to track targets for a gun or missile.
   The Wainwright, a cruiser from which the two Marines were
flying, was attacked at one point during last week's fighting by an
Iranian patrol boat, suggesting other Iranian boats could have been
in the area.
   Leslie, 30, of New Bern, N.C., and Hill, 33, of Thomasville,
N.C., were assigned to Marine Light Attack Helicopter Squadron 167
at the New River, N.C., Marine Corps Air Station.
   During the day of fighting between U.S. Navy ships and Iranian
vessels, the two were sent up on what the Pentagon has described as
a routine patrol after the Wainwright helped destroy an Iranian
offshore platform.
   During the fighting, the Navy sank or crippled six Iranian
vessels without any of its ships being hit. With the exception of
the two missing Marines, no Americans were injured or killed in
those battles. Forty-four Iranians were reported killed.
   On April 20, when the two Marines were formally declared
missing, the Pentagon disclosed it was investigating a radio
challenge to the Cobra heard before it disappeared.
   Friday's statement, disclosing Leslie and Hill had themselves
reported a hostile radar contact, provided the first indication the
helicopter had become a target.
   Pentagon officials until Friday had played down Iran's claims to
have destroyed the Cobra, noting the Iranians did not begin making
the claim until after the Defense Department itself announced the
helicopter was overdue.
   But in its new statement, the Marine Corps said its fact-finding
board had concluded there was ``sufficient evidence to conclude
that these Marines had been killed as a result of hostile action
... (even though) neither the helicopter nor the remains of the
pilots have yet been recovered.''
   ``... It is not necessary to have recovered the remains to make
a determination of `killed in action,''' the service added.
</TEXT>
