<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Painting     04-29 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Painting,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louvre Has Successful Fund-Raiser to Buy Masterpiece</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund drive has raised most of the $5.6 million
needed to buy a 17th century masterpiece by Georges de la Tour, and
the government said Friday it will provide the rest so the painting
will remain in France.
   The austere portrait ``St. Thomas'' is the last work of de la
Tour (1593-1652) still in private hands.
   With the campaign closing Saturday, about $4.2 million of the
necessary 32 million has been raised from bequests, corporations
and visitors to the Louvre Museum.
   The final contribution from Finance Ministry will allow the
Louvre to buy the painting from the Knights of Malta, an
international charity group founded in the 11th century.
   It has been on show at the Jeu de Paume, a Louvre annex, since
the campaign began March 22 and has attracted thousands of
visitors, many of whom put dropped modest donations into the tall
black urn at the entrance, said Louvre spokeswoman Sylvie Poujade.
   When the fund drive began, Finance Minister Eduoard Balladur
said the government would pay a substantial share to keep the
painting in France. Ministry officials confirmed Friday that state
funds would put the campaign over the top.
   The Knights of Malta acquired the painting in 1985 in the will
of Anne de Ruille, an unmarried countess who lived alone in her
castle in central France. The masterpiece, which she was said to
keep under her bed, was a family heirloom, Ms. Poujade said.
   Rules of the order, a non-profit group specializing in hospital
work, require it to sell such valuable possessions and use the
money for its charities.
   Officials of the organization said several foreigners offered to
buy the painting but it preferred to give France an opportunity to
add it to de la Tour paintings already in the Louvre, including the
famous ``Tricheur'' (Cheater).
   Proceeds from the sale will help build a hospital in France for
the mentally and physically handicapped, the order said.
</TEXT>
