<HEAD>Publicist Says Reynolds, Anderson Tie The Knot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUPITER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Burt Reynolds and longtime companion
Loni Anderson were married Friday at a private ceremony in a
specially built white chapel at his 160-acre horse ranch, spokesmen
said.
   Reynolds, the 52-year-old star of ``Deliverance,'' ``Smokey and
the Bandit'' and ``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas,'' announced
his marriage intentions two months ago in a magazine article, but
he refused to say when or where he would marry his girlfriend of
five years.
   Peggy Gossett, spokeswoman for the Burt Reynolds Dinner Theater,
said the ceremony was completed at midafternoon Friday and the
reception was under way. Mickey Freeman, publicist for Ms.
Anderson; and David Gershenson, Reynolds' personal manager, also
confirmed Friday that the ceremony was set for the afternoon in the
chapel at Reynolds' ranch here.
   The marriage is the third for the 41-year-old bride, best known
for her role as the not-so-dumb blonde secretary in the TV series
``WKRP in Cincinnati.'' It's Reynolds' second marriage.
   Officiating was the Rev. Jess Moody of California, and guests
included singer-actress Ann-Margaret and her husband, Roger Smith;
Ms. Anderson's daughter from a prior marriage, Diedra Hoffman; Ms.
Anderson's sister; Reynolds' parents and sister; actor-singer Jim
Nabors; and Perry Como; as well as numerous other celebrities,
Gossett said.
   Nabors was to sing at the ceremony, Freeman had said in a
telephone interview from his Los Angeles office.
   Ms. Anderson wore a knee-length, strapless white jersey dress
fitted with a beaded lace jacket, he said.
   Freeman said he understood the newlyweds planned to leave by
helicopter for a Bahamas honeymoon after a reception at Reynolds'
second Palm Beach County home, on the Intracoastal Waterway in
Jupiter.
   Before the wedding, local companies scurried to deliver
champagne, ice, flowers and party supplies to Reynolds' ranch,
which is behind a barrier of 10-foot-high metal gates.
   Reynolds, the son of the former police chief of West Palm Beach,
played halfback for Florida State University on the 1953-54
Seminole team.
   Although he never graduated, Reynolds treated the school well
after he achieved fame, setting up an intern program for students
at his Burt Reynolds Dinner Theater and giving FSU $600,000 to
endow a theater professorship. In 1981, FSU gave an honorary degree
to Reynolds.
   His first marriage was to onetime ``Laugh-In'' star Judy Carne.
</TEXT>
