<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SuperCollider     04-29 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Collider,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Defeats Bid To Make States Ante Up for Super Collider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee Friday refused to require
states seeking the super collider atom smasher to put up at least
$500 million in cash or services to land the eagerly pursued
research installation.
   On a 20-11 vote, the Space, Science and Technology Committee
rejected the minimum-funds amendment offered by Rep. Ron Packard,
R-Calif., for the $4.4 billion superconducting super collider.
   Just before that, members voted 16-14 against an alternative
that would have required the secretary of energy to report to the
committee in six months his recommendations for what the winning
state should pay.
   The amendments were offered to the $3.1 billion Energy
Department research authorization bill.
   As it stands, the bill would authorize $1.6 billion over the
next three years for the collider, of which $148 million would be
for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 _ but with no construction
funds until Oct. 1, 1989.
   The bill would set a limit of 25 percent on any foreign
contributions and require that no more than 33 percent of the
equipment be of foreign manufacture. The administration has said it
believes it can get foreign countries to contribute at least 25
percent of the cost. But so far there have been no foreign
commitments, and only Italy has agreed to explore collaboration.
   Several amendments to the bill remain to be considered,
including measures that would sharply reduce the super collider
authorization or eliminate it altogether, and to make a 25 percent
foreign contribution a requirement for proceeding with the giant
atom smasher.
   The department sought $363 million for the new fiscal year, a
large part of it to begin construction after site selection. That
selection is to be made in November and confirmed in January.
   Since the department actually needs no authorization and could
proceed under its general authority to conduct scientific research,
the bill would be important for the collider only as a statement of
congressional intent and limit on later appropriations, which the
department does have to have.
   Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., chairman of the House Appropriations
energy subcommittee, has told the Illinois delegation his panel
will approve no more than $60 million.
   Illinois, Michigan, North Carolina, Tennessee, Colorado, Arizona
and Texas are finalists to host the super collider, which comprises
a 53 miles-around tunnel and associated experimental facilities for
smashing beams of protons into each other at energies 20 times the
maximum possible today.
   Current law forbids the states from offering cash contributions
during the selection process. The Energy Department is insisting on
donation of the land, and the states may undertake site
improvements _ which may be substantial.
   Illinois officials figure the state's land purchase, tunneling,
road and other work is worth $590 million, and several states have
submitted sealed bids that are to be opened only if that state is
chosen.
   Before the vote on Packard's amendment, Rep. Manuel Lujan Jr.,
R-N.M., said Tennessee officials had claimed they would have to
drop out of the competition if a minimum-funds requirement were
imposed.
   Others were skeptical that a $500 million requirement would
deter anyone. ``Whoever wins ... is winning a $50 billion economic
development program,'' said the chairman, Rep. Robert A. Roe, D-N.J.
</TEXT>
