<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0717 04-29 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Rejects Attempts To Order Reduction Of US Troops In Europe,
Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 6 grafs after 6th graf bgng: Both Bryant ... to
UPDATE with Pentagon report on allied contributions. Picks up 7th
graf pvs bgng: Legislators in ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House overwhelmingly turned down attempts
Friday to order U.S. troops brought home from Western Europe and
Japan unless America's allies spend more for defense.
   The decisions came as the chamber worked its way through a bill
authorizing the Pentagon budget for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   First, the chamber rejected, 240-120, a proposal by Rep. John
Bryant, D-Texas, to bring 30,000 troops a year back from Europe,
and 7,000 troops annually from Japan, starting in 1991.
   Then, a 332-21 vote shot down an amendment by Rep. Tommy
Robinson, D-Ark., to withdraw 70,000 troops a year from Europe.
   Moments later, the House voted 359-0 approval of a proposal
saying the Reagan administration should begin talks with U.S.
allies about defense burden-sharing. A similar call was approved by
Congress last year, but the proposal is not binding and only
suggests that the negotiations should start.
   Both Bryant and Robinson tied their reduction requirements to
demands that Japan and the other 15 North Atlantic Treaty
Organization nations should spend a bigger portion of their budgets
for alliance defense.
   The House votes came as the Pentagon released its annual
assessment, mandated by Congress, on ``Allied Contributions to the
Common Defense.''
   The report was accompanied by a personal pledge from Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci ``to press at every opportunity for
progress in improving allied defense capabilities and in sharing
equitably the roles, risks and burdens of the alliance.''
   Carlucci said U.S. allies ``make a substantial contribution to
the common defense _ considerably more than they are often given
credit for.'' But, he said the United States ``in some areas is
doing more than most of its partners.''
   ``What is very clear is that there are substantial variations in
performance among individual allies,'' Carlucci said.
   The report says that in 1986, the latest year for which complete
figures are available, the United States allocated 6.8 percent of
its gross national product to defense.
   Greece, which ranked second among the allies, allocated 6.1
percent. England was third with 5.1 percent, followed by Turkey at
4.8 percent and France at 3.9 percent. The remaining nations had
shares of 3.2 percent or less.
   Legislators in both the House and Senate have repeatedly
criticized NATO nations for not doing more. But they have rejected
several attempts in the past three years to order U.S. force
reductions in Europe, where 326,000 U.S. troops are stationed, and
in Japan, where there are about 63,000 American service personnel.
   ``Let's get smart and begin to tell our allies that we expect
them to pay their fair share,'' said Bryant. ``We are subsidizing
their defense.''
   Robinson was even more blunt. ``The real purpose of this
amendment is to demonstrate to our allies that we've had it. These
people are stealing our jobs because we have been suckered into
paying for their defense.''
   But Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., called Robinson's plan ``a
dangerous and irresponsible effort to bring troops home to deal
with the (U.S.) trade problem.''
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., opposed both plans, saying, ``this
would be entirely counter-productive ... it is simply not possible
to maintain the viability of a voluntary alliance of free countries
if one of those countries tries to impose standards on the others.''
   Rep. Douglas Bereuter, R-Neb., said, ``this would send the wrong
message'' at a time when the United States is trying to urge NATO
countries to spend more for non-nuclear weapons in the wake of the
U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear weapons.
   But Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said, ``it's time Uncle Sam quit
being taken for uncle sucker.''
   The bill authorizes Pentagon spending of $299.5 billion in the
fiscal year starting Oct. 1, which is the same amount proposed by
the separate bill that will be considered next month by the Senate.
   Differences between the bills that pass each chamber will
eventually be reconciled by a House-Senate conference committee.
</TEXT>
