<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TreePlanting     04-29 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tree Planting,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ag Department Says Trees Being Planting at Healthy Pace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tree-planting in the United States hasn't gone
to the dogs, by any means, an Agriculture Department report showed
Friday.
   Last year more than 3 million acres were reforested with 2.3
billion tree seedlings, an area about the size of Connecticut,
Forest Service Chief F. Dale Robertson said.
   About 87 percent of the 1987 tree plantings was on private
lands, mostly in the South, he said.
   More than 1 million acres of the seeding involved land enrolled
in the department's Conservation Reserve Program authorized in the
1985 farm law, he said. Under the program, farmers get federal aid
to plant trees or grass to protect highly erodible land, plus
annual rental payments for 10 years to keep the land out of crop
production.
   Robertson said tree planting has set annual records since 1981
when more than 2.37 million acres were reforested.
   By comparison, he said, the Civilian Conservation Corps planted
about 2.33 million acres in trees over a 10-year period in the
1930s and early 1940s. More than 2 million acres were planted under
the Soil Bank program in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
</TEXT>
