<HEAD>Ax-Wielding Rapist Reportedly Visited Tampa-Area Relative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence Singleton, the convicted
rapist-mutilator who was the target of protests from towns
mentioned as possible homes after his parole last year, visited
Tampa area relatives earlier this week, authorities said Friday.
   Sheriff's Maj. John Cacciatore said a relative of the
60-year-old Tampa native told him Thursday by telephone that
Singleton paid a short visit earlier this week and left.
   ``I don't know where's he's gone,'' Cacciatore said. ``It's not
that we're not concerned. We just don't know.''
   He was convicted in California of raping a 15-year-old
hitchhiker in 1978, then chopping off her forearms with an ax and
leaving her to die. He served eight years of a 14-year sentence,
getting out early for participating in a prison work-credit program.
   His presence in Tampa was unpublicized and provoked no outcry.
Officials have said that obscurity is probably the best approach he
can take to try to offset public resentment.
   Officials said they were unsure if Singleton was still in the
state. One of eight siblings raised in the Tampa area, Singleton
has other relatives in Florida.
   Singleton's parole officially ended Monday, so he no longer is
required to tell officials where he goes or settles, according to
Bob Gore of the California Department of Corrections.
   Controversy has dogged the former merchant seaman since his
release last year. Outraged Californians mounted campaigns when
their communites were mentioned as possible homes during his
year-long parole.
   He spent weeks being shuttled among apartments and motels along
the California coast and wound up in a mobile home on the grounds
of San Quentin Prison until the parole expired.
</TEXT>
