<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sea-TacCrash     04-29 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sea-Tac Crash,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tower Tape Reveals Cool Heads Prevailed During April 15 Crash At
Sea-Tac</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a Horizon Air commuter plane and
controllers at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport remained cool
even as the aircraft caught fire and made a crash-landing, a tape
released Friday showed.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials praised the calm
response of pilot Carl Carlson and co-pilot Mark Hilstead to the
April 15 emergency. They also singled out the work of Steve
Boniberger, a controller for seven years who was working his second
day at Sea-Tac since transferring from New York's La Guardia
Airport.
   ``Our people performed outstanding ... above and beyond the call
of duty,'' said Wes Hamilton, an FAA official and manager of the
Sea-Tac tower.
   The plane touched down safely but then went out of control,
ramming three passenger boarding ramps before coming to rest just
feet in front of a passenger concourse. All 40 people aboard
survived. Nineteen were injured and two remain hospitalized in
stable condition.
   The tape of conversation between the de Havilland Dash 8 and
Sea-Tac controllers was played for reporters at the control tower
Friday.
   ``We're going to have to return to the airport,'' said a calm,
measured voice from the cockpit of Flight 2658 about a minute after
its takeoff on a scheduled trip to Spokane. The plane was less than
three miles from the airport.
   ``Do you have a problem?'' the tower asked.
   ``Yes,'' the Horizon crew responded. ``... Reduced power in the
right engine.''
   The tower noted that the Horizon commuter had not officially
declared an emergency and asked, ``Do you want (emergency safety)
equipment?''
   ``Yes,'' the crew replied, adding that the plane was carrying 40
people and 2,800 pounds of fuel.
   FAA officials did not identify which crew member made each
comment.
   Controllers then warned other aircraft on the ground to stay
clear of the runway.
   As the Horizon plane made its approach, Boniberger reported
seeing a puff of white smoke come from the right engine.
   Then a voice from another airplane broke into the tape: ``You've
got a fire going on that airplane.'' The voice said the fire was in
the right engine.
   ``From then on we knew it was something serious,'' Hamilton said
Friday.
   After touchdown, the plane veered toward the airport terminal
and the cockpit crew said the craft was ``out of control ...
leaving the runway.''
   The controller then shouted urgently, ``He's out of control .. .
he's out of control.'' It was the most excited response of the
five-minute incident and came seconds before the plane crashed into
the passenger ramps.
   The FAA and National Transportation Safety Board expect their
investigation into the crash to take at least a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
