<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-29 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Across Texas, Heavy Rain In New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms battered parts of Texas on Friday, with at
least one tornado, and parts of New England had rain heavy enough
to flood highways. Sections of the drty Northwest also got rain,
with snow at higher elevations.
   Showers and thunderstorms were widespread across central and
southeastern Texas during the morning, some accompanied by brief
heavy rain and hail. Thunderstorms also extended north into parts
of Oklahoma and Kansas.
   A tornado destroyed a building and damaged trees during the
afternoon near Columbus, Texas, in Colorado County, but no injuries
were reported, the National Weather Service reported.
   Thunderstorms produced hail three-quarters of an inch in
diameter in Texas' Colorado County and Bexar County, and knocked
power out at Rock Island, Texas.
   A thunderstorm dropped a quarter of an inch of rain in just five
minutes at Fort Worth, Texas.
   Galveston, Texas, got 1.62 inches of rain in the six hours up to
2 p.m. EDT, and 1.13 inches fell in the same period at Bergstrom
Air Force Base near Austin.
   Showers and isolated thunderstorms were numerous across the
Northeast, with rain extending from western Pennsylvania and New
York state through Maine.
   In the 24 hours up to 8 a.m. EDT, rainfall amounts included 4.40
inches at North Conway, N.H.; 4.15 inches at Pinkham Notch, N.H.;
3.43 inches at Rochester, Vt.; 3.41 inches at Berlin, N.H.; and
3.40 inches at Lincoln and Ludlow, Vt.
   Some northern New Hampshire highways were blocked by high water,
police reported.
   Rain was scattered across the Pacific Northwest with showers
extending from western Washington and Oregon into northern
California. Showers and a few thunderstorms spread across much of
northern Idaho.
   Up to 6 inches of snow was expected by morning in the passes of
the Oregon Cascades.
   Temperatures pushed into the 60s and 70s across the upper
Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes, but chilly air moved
along the central and southern Appalachians and a frost warning was
issued overnight. A frost warning also was issued for much of South
Carolina.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Du Bois, Pa., to 89 at Harlingen and Kingsville, Texas.
The low for the day was 24 degrees at Hibbing, Minn., and
Marshfield, Wis.
   For Saturday, numerous showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the lower Mississippi Valley through the Gulf Coast region,
with showers widespread from the eastern Great Lakes through New
England. Widespread showers also were forecast across the northern
Pacific Coast and the northern Rockies.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted from the Pacific Northwest into
northern sections of the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah,
and from the upper Ohio Valley into New England; in the 80s across
New Mexico into western and southwest Texas, plus the southern half
of Florida; in the mid 90s over the Arizona deserts; and in the 60s
or 70s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
