<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0793 04-29 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0793,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Waffled on Strike Against Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis aide's comment in last graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Friday
that Democrat Michael Dukakis is more concerned about ``pink slips
and plant closings'' than creating new jobs.
   He also said Dukakis waffled on whether to support President
Reagan's retaliatory strike against Iran in the Persian Gulf, and
he accused both Dukakis and Jesse Jackson of being soft on
penalties for drug-pushers.
   He defended Reagan administration efforts to cut off the supply
of drugs, but told reporters, ``I'm taking a look now at changing
the whole structure of how the government is set up'' to wage the
drug fight.
   Bush defended Reagan's opposition to the trade bill that would
force factories to give workers advance notice of closings.
Referring to Reagan's threat of a veto, he said, ``It will get
one.''
   The vice president, after touring a Magnavox plant that makes
radios and other gear for the military, said notices of plant
closings should be left to management and labor unions to work out,
not Congress.
   Advance notice does not protect jobs, he said. ``All that does
is guarantee misery. ... I'm for plant openings.''
   Dukakis had challenged Bush to spell out whether he opposes the
trade bill, the product of two years of bipartisan work in Congress.
   At a breakfast for 325 GOP supporters here, Bush said that while
the Massachusetts governor ``is talking about pink slips and plant
closings, I want to talk about the fact that ... there are more
Americans at work than any time in the history of the country.''
   ``There's some big drug problems in this country. I hear a lot
of campaign rhetoric. I hear both Jackson and Dukakis assailing the
administration on this and thus denigrating those men and women in
the DEA (Drug Enforcement Administration) ... trying to staunch the
flow of drugs coming in and catch the criminals,' he said.
   ``But I haven't heard them talk about how tough they want to be
in changing the laws ... (to) put some muscle in,'' he said. ``I
strongly favor the death penalty for the narco-traffickers, those
kingpins that are pushing the poison on our kids.''
   The certain Republican nominee said front-runner Dukakis was
``waffling all over the field'' on whether to support Reagan's
strike against Iranian oil platforms and boats after a mine nearly
sank a U.S. Navy frigate. It took the Massachusetts governor most
of a day to formulate a response to the strike earlier this month.
   ``The president's different than anything else. You can't wait
around, hold your finger in the wind and see what the polls show,''
he said.
   Bush told the Magnavox workers, ``We can compete. Let's remember
who we are. We're the United States of America. We rolled back the
frontiers and battled the deserts and the shows.''
   Bush, in interviews with local reporters, said he is girding for
a close race in the fall. `I think I have to get my message out, my
passions, what my heartbeat is,'' he said.
   Asked whether Attorney General Edwin Meese III should resign
because of on-going investigations into his activities, Bush said,
``Let the system work it out. ... Let the system make that
deterrmination.''
   Asked if he would hire Meese in his administration, Bush said,
``If he proves innocent, I certainly would hire him.''
   But he said that was a theoretical question. ``We're going to
have change, new people'' in the entire Cabinet, he said.
   In Indianapolis, Bush told reporters ``we will have some fun,
too,'' if the Democrats try to taint him with the so-called sleaze
factor, a reference to alleged wrongdoing by high-ranking Reagan
administration officials.
   Bush, asked if he was hurt by Meese's problems, said, ``I think
Democrats are fair. I know the Democrats. I hear them talking about
it. But there is plenty of evidence to kind of go into a
guilt-by-association mode where we can find in Massachusetts
politics or campaign staff or things of that nature. I hope we
don't have to do it.''
   He added, ``We will have some fun, too, trying to look into what
is going on in Illinois or Massachusetts depending upon which one
wins the Democratic nomination. You know we've got some cannon
fodder, if you want to get into that.''
   Leslie Dach, a spokesman for Dukakis, responded, ``I guess his
support for Ed Meese is making the vice president nervous. The vice
president knows that the vast majority of Americans have serious
questions about his commitment to ethics in government.''
</TEXT>
