<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Workplace     04-29 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Workplace,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Requires Drug-Free Workplaces for Energy Department
Contractors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee voted Friday to permit the
Energy Department to withhold payments to some of its contractors
until they demonstrate they are trying to maintain drug-free
workplaces.
   The measure was attached as an amendment to the $3.1 billion
Energy Department research authorization bill being considered by
the House Space, Science and Technology Committee.
   Approval came on a 20-7 show of hands.
   Opponents said the amendment likely would prove to be
counterproductive and inappropriate. Rep. Jimmy Hayes, D-La., a
former prosecutor, said if he were a contractor, he would defend
arrested employees in court to avoid interruption of his income
from the department.
   Supporters said it was time for Congress to get serious about
the nation's drug problem.
   ``Have any hearings been held?'' said Rep. James Scheuer, D-N.Y.
   ``We have had hearings,'' said Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas.
``Hearings are going on right now in the juvenile courts, in the
jails and in the cemeteries.''
   Walker's provision would require all contracts authorized under
the bill to contain a provision permitting the contracting agency _
most often the Energy Department _ to withhold payments ``upon
proof of use, possession or possession with the intent to
distribute of any controlled substance in violation of any federal,
state or local law, by an employee in the workplace, as evidenced
by the conviction of such employee in a court of competent
jurisdiction'' until the contractor ``demonstrates to the agency
that it has taken sufficient action to restore a drug-free
workplace.''
   Convictions arising out of an employer's good-faith efforts to
enforce a drug-free workplace ``shall be considered substantial
evidence that the employer is taking sufficient action,'' Walker's
amendment said.
   Jeff Sherwood, spokesman for the Energy Department, said he was
unable to reach any officials in a position to comment.
   The Energy Department provides funds to universities and others
that operate laboratories which undertake a wide variety of
research, ranging from the most secret nuclear weapons to
environmental projects.
   Prospects for the drug provisions were not immediately clear,
since the science authorization bill for the department has failed
to get through Congress for the past severl years.
   The department has permanent, general authority to conduct
scientific research, and does so with money provided by
appropriations committees.
</TEXT>
