<HEAD>Nicaraguan Airliner Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan airliner with 23 people
aboard made an emergency landing Friday in San Jose after a window
blew out at 20,000 feet, an airport controller said.
   No injuries were reported among the 16 passengers and seven crew
members.
   The Aeronica Boeing 720 left San Jose for Panama at 8:15 a.m.
(10:15 a.m. EDT) and was over Costa Rica's Caribbean port of Limon
when a window blew out in the left forward part of the aircraft,
said the controller, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``The pilot advised us that the plane was losing pressure and
would return to Santamaria airport,'' he said. ``About 15 minutes .
.. (after takeoff) the plane landed without problems.''
   It had left Managua, the Nicaraguan capital, at 7 a.m. (9 a.m.
EDT).
   The flight was canceled and an investigation begun, the
controller said.
   Costa Rica's 39 regular air traffic controllers have been on
strike for eight days demanding higher pay and and equipment
improvements. The source was one of 11 substitutes.
</TEXT>
