<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarine Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0825,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crippled Submarine Returns To Home Port</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES 6th graf, `The crews...', which is redundant
material.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CHT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crippled submarine USS Bonefish was
towed into its home port Friday, five days after a fire and
explosion rocked the vessel off the Florida coast and killed three
crewmen.
   The Bonefish, assisted by four tugboats, tied up next to the USS
Frank Cable, a submarine auxiliary ship, at the Charleston Naval
Base at midafternoon.
   Three crewmen were killed and 22 others from the 92-man Bonefish
crew were injured in Sunday's fire. Lt. Cmdr. John Tull, a
spokesman for the Charleston Naval Base, said an investigation of
the accident is continuing.
   Several sailors from the Bonefish in white Navy uniforms stood
on top of the sub as it was towed up the Cooper River toward the
base. The crews of the Cable and the nearby guided missile
destroyer USS MacDonough stood at attention as the Bonefish, an
American flag flying from its conning tower, tied up.
   The sailors went out to meet the submarine at the harbor
entrance when the tugs took the Bonefish from the salvage ship USS
Hoist, which had towed the sub for two days from the site of the
accident.
   Tull said the investigation will be headed by Capt. Robin White,
the commander of the Charleston-based Submarine Squadron 18. No
deadline exists for completing the probe, he said, adding, ``You
take as long as you need to thoroughly investigate it.''
   Ronald Larsen, the chief electrician's mate on the Bonefish, had
told The Associated Press that most of the crew members believe the
ship won't be returned to service.
   But Tull said there's been no decision on what will be done with
the 30-year-old submarine, which is one of the Navy's last
remaining diesel-electric submarines.
   ``That will have to be evaluated,'' said Tull.
   Meanwhile, Tull said, three doctors from the Portsmouth Naval
Hospital in Virginia are in Charleston to counsel Bonefish crewmen.
   The accident killed Lt. Ray Everts, 30, of Naoma, W.Va.; Petty
Officer 1st Class Robert W. Bordelon Jr., 39, of Willis, Texas; and
Petty Officer 3rd Class Marshall T. Lindgren, 21, of Pisgah Forest,
N.C. The three bodies were recovered from the sub Wednesday and
Thursday.
   The funeral for Bordelon will be held Saturday, and the funerals
for the other two victims will be held Sunday. A memorial service
for all three is scheduled Saturday at a church in downtown
Charleston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
