<HEAD>TV Broadcasts in Armenian Begun to Disputed Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television began broadcasting in the
Armenian language Friday to Nagorno-Karabakh, the territory that
has caused conflict in the neighboring Caucasus republics of
Azerbaijan and Armenia, Tass reported.
   The broadcasts are part of the government's eight-year plan to
improve the cultural and economic life of Nagorno-Karabakh, which
has a predominantly Armenian population but was assigned to
Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Last month, the government refused demands by Armenia and
demonstrators in Nagorno-Karabakh that the area be annexed to
Armenia.
   Demonstrations began in mid-February in Armenia and Azerbaijan,
and riots began Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijan city of Sumgait.
   At least 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis were killed in three
days of violence and about 200 people were hurt, officials reported.
   Nagorno-Karabakh now receives the Armenian-lanaguage programming
on one channel in addition to two national channels broadcasting in
Russian and one in Azerbaijani, the official news agency said.
