<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     04-29 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Officials Scoff at Reports of Deal with US</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Friday denied reports of
an agreement with the Reagan administration that would have Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega quit as commander of the military but not
leave Panama.
   An estimated 10,000 people marched Friday in a demonstration of
support of Noriega, the head of Panamaa's 15,000-member Defense
Forces and the dominant force in the civilian government.
   ``That agreement does not exist,'' Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter
told a news conference. ``You can hardly reach an agreement when
relations with the United States are at the point they are.''
   Ritter confirmed that Michael Kozak, an aide to Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams, met with Noriega this week.
   ``Mr. Kozak was in Panama talking with different groups, with
leaders of the opposition,'' Ritter said. ``He also talked with the
general but did not reach any agreement, because they simply were
not negotiating.''
   Noriega was indicted in Florida in February on drug trafficking
charges. The United States subsequently demanded he resign from the
military and imposed economic sanctions on Panama. Noriega has
denied the narcoatics allegations.
   Government officials said privately the proposal on Noriega
quitting was a ``face-saving move by the United States.'' They said
Noriega has already offered to resign subject to the establishment
of a ``national dialogue'' with opposition forces.
   Opposition leaders were not immediately available for comment.
   Panamanian Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, a leader of the anti-Noriega
forces in Washington, accused the United States of going beyond its
authority in trying to negotiate Panama's political future.
   In Miami, anti-Noriega exiles called the U.S. proposal a
surrender with cosmetics.
   ``This cosmetic solution will only take the country down the
road to disaster,'' said Gilberto Mallol, exiled representative of
the Panamanian opposition umbrella group, the Civic Crusade.
   A U.S. official said in Washington Friday that the Reagan
administration reached a tentative agreement with Noriega under
which he will step down as chief of the Defense Forces and de facto
leader of the government but remain in Panama.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Kozak met
with Noriega this week. But he said the agreement was ``less than
ideal'' because it did not include the general's departure from the
country.
   The march Friday was called by the Popular Unity Front, which
includes some labor groups that support the government and some
parties in the governing coalition.
   One of the speakers at the rally, Alvaro Munoz of the National
Council of Workers, said: ``The problem of Noriega must be solved
through an agreement among Panamanians and within the laws of the
Defense Forces.''
   Noriega in mid-March offered to resign as commander of the
Defense Forces before the May 1989 elections.
   Panama is suffering a cash shortage because of the U.S. santions.
   The Reagan administration has refused to make scheduled payments
to Panama for Panama Canal operations. It also has set up accounts
in the United States under the name of ousted President Eric Arturo
Delvalle for tax and other payments by Americans and American
companies to this country.
   Washington continues to recognize Delvalle, who was deposed by
pro-Noriega legislators on Feb. 26, a day after he tried to fire
the general. But opposition leaders have said they will not
recognize Delvalle if Noriega leaves.
   Noriega has said the U.S. actions are the result of his refusal
to help the Reagan administration overthrow Nicaragua's leftist
government and of efforts by rightists in the the United States to
prevent the scheduled turnover of the Panama Canal to Panama at the
end of 1999.
</TEXT>
