<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Gulf-Roberts     04-29 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Roberts,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frigate To Be Repaired At Maine Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The guided-missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts,
badly ripped by a mine in the Persian Gulf two weeks ago, will be
repaired at the shipyards of the Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine,
the Navy announced Friday.
   The service said a damage assessment of the ship was still under
way in the United Arab Emirates port of Dubai, where the Roberts
was towed after the April 14 mining. No estimate could be made as
to when the frigate could sail for the United States.
   But the service said the Bath Iron Works had been selected to
make repairs ``because of its proximity to Newport, R.I., the home
port of the ship, and because the shipyard has both the capability
and capacity for doing the restoration.''
   ``The Samuel B. Roberts was built at Bath and was commissioned
there in April 1986,'' the Navy said in a statement. ``The cost of
the repairs has not yet been determined, and will not be known
until a full assessment can be made of the damage.''
   The Navy said no decision had been made on whether temporary
repairs could be performed in Dubai that would allow the ship to
steam home on its own power. A Navy source said, however, the
damage to the vessel was so severe that it ``almost certainly''
would have to be towed.
   Navy officials have said the Roberts almost certainly would have
sunk had it not been for the performance of its crew.
</TEXT>
