<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BunnyReunion     04-29 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bunny Reunion,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Bunnies Reunite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bunny suits are retired now _ some replaced
by pinstripes. But the women who found success in ears and
cottontails still love to lead a cheer for the bygone lifestyle.
   ``I think probably it is a lost era,'' said Sandi Meehan, 49, of
Manhattan, who joined other former bunnies planning a Saturday
night reunion. ``When someone says Playboy bunny, it brings images
of maybe Ziegfeld Follies `girls' or the Rockettes.''
   Mrs. Meehan, who worked at Playboy clubs from 1961 to 1974 and
recruited other women during ``bunny hunts,'' now invests in real
estate and owns a Manhattan bakery with another former bunny.
   Bunnydom, she said, gave her valuable training in business and
public relations.
   ``We (former bunnies) are very successful businesswomen and we
are not feminists,'' said Mrs. Meehan. ``Feminists are the ones who
attacked us. I don't think it's fair. I know so many successful
`girls' who came from Playboy.''
   One successful girl _ uh, woman _ invited to the reunion was Ms.
magazine founder Gloria Steinem, who once took a job as a bunny to
write an expose.
   Steinem won't attend the reunion, which will raise funds for
Cancer Care Inc. ``When we have a dinner where former bunnies feel
able to tell the truth, it will make a lot more money. And then
I'll come,'' she said.
   But perhaps the feminist leader could strike a common chord with
ex-bunny Anna Lederer, 37, who left her native Trinidad at 17
because ``they thought I was pretty and too young to be involved in
politics.''
   ``It was a man's world _ it still is,'' said Mrs. Lederer, who
went on to earn a degree in international relations at the
University of Geneva and open an import business.
   Before that, she worked from 1968 to 1971 in the old Manhattan
Playboy club, which closed in 1982.
   ``I was brought up in a convent,'' she explained. ``I wanted to
get a job where I wouldn't be so shy anymore.'' She said a club
manager's advice to stand tall and be proud of herself ``did more
for me than a psychiatrist could have done.''
   Lorraine Muscara, 28, rode the cottontail of the era. Her
employer, the Empire Club in Manhattan, opened in November 1985 and
closed in June 1986.
   Miss Muscara, director of sales for a Manhattan computer
maintenance company, hurried from her office three nights a week,
trading her business clothes for a bunny costume.
   ``It was a release. I couldn't wait to walk into the bunny
room,'' she said. ``It got me through the day sometimes.''
   Mrs. Lederer said she organized the reunion of ex-bunnies who
live in the metropolitan area at the suggestion of her 13-year-old
son.
   ``Years ago, we were teen-agers _ young and foolish,'' she said.
``Now, we've lived life, matured.''
   ``Some are bringing up babies on their own. Most of my
(ex-bunny) friends are in business; one is a doctor; one runs a
shelter; they have gone on to do incredible things with their
lives, for society,'' she added.
</TEXT>
