<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Finances     04-29 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Finances,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Files State Financial Disclosure Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis filed state financial disclosure
forms Friday that show, in addition to his $85,000 gubernatorial
salary, three family trusts, stocks and a Brookline home.
   The Democratic presidential front-runner and his wife, Kitty,
own at least $1,000 in stock in Automatix Inc., a Billerica, Mass.,
company that makes industrial robots. The couple also owns at least
$1,000 in U.S. Treasury notes.
   The governor's home in Brookline has a value of at least
$100,000.
   Other than the interest earned from the trusts, the only family
income reported on the financial disclosure forms required by state
law stems from Dukakis' official salary.
   Kitty Dukakis is a trustee, director or board member of several
philanthropic and cultural groups, but she reported no income from
them. The groups include the Wang Center for the Performing Arts,
the Boston Ballet, Lesley College, a prison rehabilitation project
and the Public Space Partnerships Project.
   The governor's disclosure form lists three trusts: one set up in
1974 by his father in the name of his wife and children; another
created in 1949 under the will of Kitty Dukakis' grandmother, Mabel
Williams, to be distributed to Mrs. Dukakis' father, Harry Ellis
Dickson; and one created in 1972 by Dickson.
   It was the trust set up in by Dukakis' father, Panos Dukakis,
that drew attention last year when a report filed by Dukakis with
the Federal Election Commission revealed that until 1986, the trust
included stocks in companies doing business in South Africa. The
trust was valued last year at $1 million.
   The Mabel Williams trust was valued at $50,000 as of last year,
and the Dickson trust $60,000.
   Up-to-date and detailed information on the trusts is expected to
be available later this month when Dukakis is scheduled to file
disclosure forms with the federal commission and to make public his
1987 income tax returns.
   The state disclosure forms do not require reporting precise
incomes or values of assets.
   Dukakis reported no real estate transactions, mortgage holdings
or loans on his state disclosure form.
</TEXT>
