<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Veto Of Trade Bill Would Be Tragedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 12 grafs new with later appearances; Picks up 7th graf
pvs, bgng: ``Dukakis, the ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Predede DAYTON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis turned aside
sharpened criticism from rival Jesse Jackson on Friday and said it
would be a ``tragedy'' if President Reagan vetoes legislation
requiring companies to give notice before closing factories.
   He said workers ``deserve better from America.''
   Dukakis criticized the Reagan administration on issues ranging
from homelessness to problems with the nation's airlines under
deregulation as he began campaigning toward Ohio's Democratic
presidential primary next Tuesday.
   Campaigning on the one-year anniversary of his formal entry into
the presidential race, Dukakis urged supporters to ignore polls
showing him far ahead.
   Dukakis did not mention his remaining Democratic rival, Jackson,
nor did he respond with criticism when asked about Jackson's sharp
comments in Ohio that Dukakis would merely ``manage'' Reagan's
economic program rather than change it.
   ``I just don't talk about these things _ I have a record,''
Dukakis said. ``... Not only that, I balance budgets, and that's
something that hasn't been a feature of Reaganomics.''
   Dukakis mentioned disagreements he has with Jackson on the
Middle East and other issues and said, ``I think you'll continue to
see us conduct this campaign with a lot of mutual respect and
genuine friendship, and the fact that we disagree on some issues I
don't think will change that.''
   Appearing before labor leaders at a local union hall in
Columbus, and later before a lunchtime crowd in downtown Dayton,
the Massachusetts governor pointed to his own state's law requiring
companies to make public their plans to close plants. He said it
had saved jobs by giving workers and local governments the chance
to prepare or find alternatives.
   ``I hope the president will take the time to think about the
three million American workers who lose their jobs in this country
every year through plant shutdowns,'' Dukakis said. ``In at least
half those cases, those plants shut down with little or no notice
to those most affected _ their own employees.
   ``These people are our neighbors,'' he said. ``They deserve
better from their employers. They deserve better from America.''
   Reagan has said he would veto trade legislation passed
overwhelmingly by the Senate this week because of a provision
requiring 60-days' notice on plant closings.
   ``I hope he will reconsider,'' Dukakis said.
   Speaking to reporters later in Youngstown, Dukakis said: ``I
think it would be a tragedy if it was vetoed. ... I think he might
reconsider.''
   Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee after big wins in New
York and Pennsylvania, is battling Jesse Jackson for Ohio's 159
Democratic delegates at stake Tuesday. After flying around Ohio
Friday and Saturday, he also planned to visit Indiana, where 79
delegates are also at stake in that state's primary Tuesday.
   Before leaving for Ohio, Dukakis released copies of letters sent
to Reagan and congressional leaders urging enactment of the trade
bill and said he would make the bill a major part of his attack on
Vice President George Bush, the certain GOP nominee, if the measure
is vetoed by Reagan.
   Dukakis appeared in Columbus with Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste, who
last year had flirted with the idea of running for the presidency.
Celeste spoke warmly of Dukakis but later said he was taking no
stand in the race.
   ``It's a desire to ensure an open, enthusiastic primary in the
state in which Reverend Jackson knows he's as welcome as Governor
Dukakis at every place, including the governor's office, and his
supporters know we expect them to be part of a unified effort in
the fall,'' Celeste said.
   Dukakis did not cite Bush by name but referred to him in saying
the Republican Party ``is going to be asking Americans to keep
things as they are. But I say we have to change.''
   Repeating his call for reinvestment in American jobs, Dukakis
said: ``I'm not running for president to overthrow governments in
Central America. I want to create jobs in middle America.''
</TEXT>
