<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Durenberger 1stLd-Writethru a0738 04-29 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Durenberger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Chastises Durenberger for Discussing Espionage
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS penultimate graf bgng, `Director Casey,' to FIX typo</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee criticized Sen.
David Durenberger on Friday for discussing an espionage case in
public last year, but stopped short of recommending disiplinary
action against the Minnnesota Republican.
   The committee said the remarks by Durenberger, the immediate
past chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, had
``jeopardized the mutual confidence which must exist between the
Congress and the intelligence community.''
   ``The ethics committee has determined that your statements gave
the appearance that you were disclosing sensitive national security
information,'' Durenberger was told.
   The Ethics Committee investigation centered on comments
Durenberger made at an event sponsored by the American Israel
Public Affairs Committee in Palm Beach, Fla., on March 15, 1987.
   Some members of the Senate were said to have been angered by
Durenberger's reported disclosure to the group that then-CIA
Director William J. Casey in 1982 had ``changed the rules'' under
which allies did not spy on each other by recruiting an Israeli
military officer to spy on Israel for the United States.
   Durenberger later denied he had revealed any classified
information.
   In its letter to Durenberger, the Ethics Committee said:
``Because the committee has concluded that your actions were not
intentional, deliberate, nor attended with gross negligence, and
because of the particular facts of this case, we will not recommend
that the Senate take institutional action against you. However, the
committee wants to make it clear that it does not condone your
actions.''
   The letter was signed by Sens. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., David
Pryor, D-Ark, Terry Sanford, D-N.C., Warren Rudman, R-N.H., Jesse
Helms, R-N.C. and Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   Durenberger said Friday he was ``gratified by their findings
that no action is warranted.''
   But he added: ``I respectfully disagree with the ethic
committee's conclusion that my statements gave an appearance that
may have put at risk the mutual confidence that must exist between
Congress and the intelligence community.''
   Sources present at the Palm Beach meeting who said they took
careful notes reported that Durenberger said the CIA recruited its
Israeli spy after Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon. The spy passed
along sensitive information about the invasion, Durenberger
reportedly told the group.
   Durenberger's comments were said to be aimed at giving context
to the case of Jonathan Jay Pollard, an American convicted of
spying on the United States for Israel.
   In a statement issued later, Durenberger said he had not been
seeking to justify Israel's recruitment of Pollard, but ``rather to
shed light on how it may have occurred'' and give it
``perspective.''
   In his statement Friday, Durenberger repeated his previous
assertions that he had not disclosed anything classified, but was
only referring to newspaper accounts at the time whose content led
to speculation that there may have been U.S. intelligence sources
in the Israeli government.
   ``I believe that I exercised due care in preparation for this
speech,'' Durenberger said. ``I respectfully disagree with the
ethic committee's conclusion that my statements gave the appearance
that I was disclosing sensitive information.''
   ``To the contrary, I expressly indicated that the source of my
remarks was newspaper articles, and I said nothing to leave the
impression that I was relaying confidential information,'' he said.
   ``Director Casey was a strong leader, loyal to his own view of
the public interest, but his belief that Congress should play
little or no role in intelligence oversight led to a lack of mutual
confidence long before March 1987,'' Durenberger said.
   In a separate statement Friday, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., said Durenberger ``was an excellent chairman during one of
the most demanding and crucial periods for intelligence oversight.
I had just as much confidence in Dave before the Ethics Committee
examination as I do right now.''
</TEXT>
