<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Ecology     04-29 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Ecology,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Plant Partially Closed As Public Health Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Friday shut down some production
facilities at a chemical plant in Armenia after environmentalists
contended the equipment increased cases of cancer and other
diseases.
   Soviet television said two units producing chloroprene rubber
were taken out of production Friday morning at the Nairit
Scientific Production Association in Yerevan because they caused
``irreparable harm to the city's ecology and people's health.''
   The decision was made due to ``multiple demands of residents of
Yerevan about a complicated ecological situation,'' an announcer
said.
   A correspondent for the television news program Vremya reported
from Yerevan that the two units sent 3,500 tons of pollutants into
the air annually.
   The report showed workers turning off valves on the units, built
in the late 1930s. The plant will continue to produce other items,
including anti-corrosive paint, according to the report.
   The shutdown was an example of how Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or openness, has made
authorities more responsive to citizens' complaints.
   The Soviet news media has carried a number of reports about
industrial pollution as a threat to public health. Many cities are
reported to be in violation of national air pollution standards. In
January, the government formed a State Committee for Environmental
Protection.
   At least 3,000 Armenians marched in Yerevan Oct. 17 to demand
the shutdown of Nairit and a nuclear power station.
   Soviet television said the national Cabinet, known as the
Council of Ministers, in December ordered an end to production of
chloroprene at Nairit using old technology.
   In March 1986, activists in Armenia sent Gorbachev a petition
demanding that the plant be relocated. They said it was
contributing to a massive increase in stomach cancer, cardiac and
respiratory disease and congenital defects. They claimed that over
the past 15 years the number of leukemia cases in and around
Yerevan quadrupled.
</TEXT>
