<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanArtFiasco     04-29 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Art Fiasco,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Art Official Refusing To Quit Over Auction Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A museum official, under fire from Cuban exiles for
including in an auction works by artists they consider sympathetic
to the Cuban government, accused his detractors of using the type
of totalitarian tactics they oppose.
   ``I have been subject to extreme pressure,'' said Ramon Cernuda,
vice president of the Cuban Museum of Arts and Culture.
   Cernuda has ignored requests to resign, though he says he has
received so many threatening telephone calls that he had to have
his phone number changed.
   The flap began over an April 22 auction that earned the museum
$50,000 in commissions from the auction of 173 paintings by various
Cuban artists, some of whom live or lived in Cuba and some of whom
live elsewhere.
   Some of the works were by artists considered by the strongly
anti-Communist Cuban exile community to be sympathetic to Fidel
Castro.
   The privately funded museum's governing board of directors,
which had narrowly approved the auction, met in emergency session
Friday to discuss the dispute, but there was no immediate word on
whether the board would announce any decision. Cernuda said he
would resign only if the 54-member board asked him to do so.
   Mignon Medrano, a museum founder and its former president, is
among those accusing Cernuda of tinkering with the museum's
ideological slant in what Medrano considers a misguided pursuit of
artistic freedom.
   ``We are a museum created and sustained by Cuban exiles,''
Medrano said. ``As long as we have a voice, we will never be a
propaganda vehicle for those artists who collaborate with the
communists.''
   Museum president Nunzio Mainieri, who says he has asked Cernuda
to quit because of the flap, has also canceled a planned showing
next month of work by Cuban artist Amelia Pelaez. One of Cuba's
foremost painters, she died on the island in 1986.
   She recently has been accused by some anti-Castro activists as a
collaborator of that government.
   That accusation is absurd, said art expert Jose Gomez-Sicre,
founder of the modern art museum at the Organization of American
States in Washington, D.C.
   ``They're imbeciles when they say that. She was the best painter
we ever produced,'' he said. ``She never got involved in politics.
All she had to do was paint.''
   The artist's 85-year-old sister, Elena Pelaez of Miami, also
denied the collaboration charge.
   ``She hasn't been a collaborator of any government, much less
this one,'' Ms. Pelaez said of Cuba. ``She just painted and painted
and painted.''
</TEXT>
