<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PeltIndictments     04-29 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pelt Indictments,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Accused of Smuggling Pelts Of Endangered Animals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former candidate for U.S. Senate and the husband
of a former state revenue commissioner have been indicted by a
federal grand jury in Nevada for allegedly smuggling the pelts of
endangered animals into the United States.
   The grand jury issued a 14-count indictment Thursday against two
wealthy physicians, Dr. Constantine Hampers, who has homes in
Weston, Mass., and Dublin, N.H.; and Dr. Edward B. Hager of
Lyndeborough, N.H.
   Hampers is the husband of former Massachusetts Revenue
Commissioner Joyce Hampers. Hager finished fourth in the Republican
primary for U.S. Senate in New Hampshire in 1980.
   U.S. Attorney Frank L. McNamara said Friday that the endangered
animals, which were hunted in Mexico, were two ocelots, a mountain
lion and two jaguars. It is legal to kill jaguars and ocelots in
Mexico with proper permits, but it is illegal to return them to the
United States.
   The ocelot and the jaguar are on the endangered species list.
The mountain lion is on the protected species list.
   ``If the reports are true, it shows a shocking insensitivity to
these endangered species which cannot be countenanced,'' McNamara
said.
   Robert Keefe, a lawyer for Hampers, said his client ``maintains
his innocence. He will enter a plea of not guilty and expects to be
vindicated at the end of trial.'' Hager's home and office have
unlisted telephone numbers, and he could not be reached for comment
Friday evening.
   McNamara's office reportedly obtained search warrants for
Hampers' and Hager's homes and offices and confiscated three
mounted ocelots, two jaguars and a mountain lion. Chief Assistant
U.S. Attorney L.J. O'Neale of Nevada said the trophies will be used
as evidence.
   Hampers founded National Medical Care, a Waltham-based company
that was a pioneer in the artificial kidney field. His wife, who
was revenue commissioner in 1979-82, ran unsuccessfully against
Massachusetts State Treasurer Robert Crane two years ago.
   Hager is a former president of the New England Conservative
Action Committee.
   Hampers and Hager each is charged with two counts of conspiracy
to smuggle wildlife, two counts of smuggling, six counts of illegal
importation of wildlife and four counts of unlawful transportation
of wildlife.
   If convicted, they could be sentenced to five years in prison
and fined $100,000 each.
   The indictment said Hampers and Hager knew they were acting
illegally when they paid Antonio Rivera, a Mexican national who was
their hunting guide, to bring the pelts into the United States.
   Hampers and Hager allegedly arranged to have the pelts stuffed
by a taxidermist in Colorado, who sent the mounted trophies to the
men's homes in New Hampshire. The indictment charges that Rivera
met the men in Las Vegas to deliver the pelts.
   The taxidermist, James Bensley, reportedly cooperated with
authorities, allowing his telephone calls with Hampers and Hager to
be recorded by federal agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
