<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JetBlast-Attendant     04-29 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Blast-Attendant,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Stewardess Was 37-Year Airline Employee</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Jet Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAHULUI, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clarabelle Lansing, the Aloha Airlines
flight attendant presumed dead after a jet blew open at 24,000
feet, was a 37-year employee who wore a tropical flower in her hair
and appeared in ads for the airline.
   ``She was very personable. She reminds you of the
top-of-the-line flight attendants you see on the major carriers,''
said Dale Randles, a Honolulu resident who flies Aloha to Maui once
a week. ``She was very attractive, a beautiful woman. You could ask
her anything and she'd answer your questions.''
   Mrs. Lansing, 57, apparently was sucked out of an Aloha jet
carrying 95 people Thursday after a third of the Boeing 737's
fuselage tore away during a Hilo-to-Honolulu flight, officials said.
   The jet safely at Kahului Airport 15 minutes later. Sixty-one
people were injured. Air and sea crews searched the Pacific Ocean
for Mrs. Lansing without success.
   Mrs. Lansing, who was known to friends as C.B., was born on the
island of Kauai, called the Garden Island for its unspoiled beauty.
She joined Aloha after high school and was among the its first
flight attendants.
   ``She was a wonderful employee, a great lady,'' said Stephanie
Ackerman, a spokeswoman for Aloha Airlines. ``Our passengers loved
her.''
   Mrs. Lansing's husband, Robert E. Lansing, works for the
University of Hawaii in Honolulu. The couple had no children.
</TEXT>
