<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceMeeting     04-29 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Meeting,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists From More Than 17 Countries Plan International Space
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from around the globe gathered
Friday to plan for International Space Year in 1992 and were called
the spiritual descendants of Christopher Columbus.
   ``You are explorers who know of enduring hardship ... to triumph
over great natural obstacles,'' said Harvey Meyerson, president of
the U.S.-ISY Association, which is supervising the planning.
   The organization is orchestrating a series of space projects to
commemorate the 500th anniversary of Columbus' first voyage to the
New World in 1492.
   ``This effort unites the universal themes ... that have powered
the human spirit in the past and continue to point to a future of
unlimited horizons,'' added James C. Fletcher, the chief of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Nearly 90 scientists from 17 space agencies, including those of
the Soviet Union, China and Western European, opened the three-day
meeting at the University of New Hampshire.
   The scientists are planning projects that will use space
satellites to research global problems including acid rain, ozone
depletion and the apparent gradual warming of the Earth's climate,
known as the greenhouse effect.
   Images of the planet from space, Fletcher said, have ``triggered
an awareness of Earth as a fragile and most precious life support
system, one made even more precious because ... it is the only body
in our solar system to harbor and nourish life.''
   The space year will include TV specials, expositions and trade
fairs. The events will help persuade people and governments that
space technology is worth its high cost, said Philip Goldsmith of
the European Space Agency, a consortium of several western European
nations.
   ``It's easy to convince the public and political masters of the
glamor projects like space travel ... but harder to maintain the
enthusiasm and funding levels for the long period needed to observe
Earth,'' Goldsmith said.
</TEXT>
