<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IllegalSalmon     04-29 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illegal Salmon,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shelters Serving 52,000 Pounds of Impounded Salmon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soup kitchens and shelters in the San
Francisco Bay area are serving mouth-watering red salmon steak
courtesy of government agents who had seized the fish caught
illegally near Taiwan.
   The Food Bank of Santa Clara County received 52,000 pounds free
and sold it it for 10 cents a pound to cover their costs to
agencies that serve the needy in Santa Clara, San Mateo and San
Francisco counties.
   Salmon steaks at one local supermarket chain Friday were selling
for $8.99.
   ``I sure hope they think it's wonderful,'' said Colleen Lukoff,
development coordinator for the Food Bank. ``We're just delighted
to have it. We don't usually get food like this here.''
   Federal officials impounded 372,000 pounds of salmon in early
1987 at the Port of Oakland and in cold storage plants in Riverside
and Watsonville. Federal inspectors approved the fish for human
consumption.
   Robert Taylor, an attorney with the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, said the government sold off most of
the fish to cover the costs of the investigation and litigation.
   The rest was donated to Second Harvest of Chicago, a national
food bank network.
