<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 3rdLd-Writethru a0875 04-29 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0875,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Make New Proposal In Talks With Sandinistas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-14 ``As the...the coordinate'' with 8 grafs to
UPDATE with more arrests, Borge incident. Pickup 15th graf pvs
``The weapons...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rebels on Friday removed a major
obstacle to agreement in their talks with the government to work
out details of a cease-fire pact signed last month.
   The top rebel leader announced that the insurgents, known as
Contras, will not insist that their fighters be resupplied with
weapons and ammunition when they gather in seven cease-fire zones
during a permanent truce that is being considered.
   ``We have desisted from receiving replacements of weapons and
ammunition in the zones and we accept the concept of sovereignty
and indivisibility of national territory,'' Adolfo Calero told a
news conference.
   Previously the Contras insisted that the cease-fire zones be
autonomous.
   But Calero also said the Contras rejected the Sandinista
government's demand that all humanitarian aid to the rebels be
channeled through the International Red Cross. The rebels expect
$17.7 million in humanitarian aid already approved by the U.S.
Congress.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco told reporters
earlier Friday that the rebels have suffered deep internal
divisions and some segments have rejected disarming and returning
to civilian life.
   The rebels on Friday rejected a government proposal to extend by
30 days a 60-day cease-fire that began April 1. They said the
extension showed ``a lack of good will to fulfill the agreements.''
   The cease-fire agreement was signed on March 23.
   Sandinista officials said the rebel refusal to agree to an
extension showed the Contras were more interested in a truce than a
permanent peace.
   The interim cease-fire accord calls for the Contras to move into
cease-fire zones while talks continue on a long-term accord.
   Contra leaders insist the sides agree upon just how much freedom
the rebels will have within those zones.
   As the two sides continued their talks in the Nicaraguan
capital, police used rubber truncheons to break up a demonstration
at the headquarters of the General Workers Confederation, an
umbrella group for anti-Sandinista unions, and detained seven
people.
   Carlos Huembes, chairman of the Democratic Coordinate, a
coalition of unions and parties opposed to the government, said
four workers were arrested outside the Social Democratic Party
headquarters.
   He said they were en route to the demonstration in front of the
confederation building. Both the construction workers and the
Social Democratic Party belong to the coordinate.
   The arrests came five days after 38 construction workers and
auto mechanics began a hunger strike for higher salaries.
   Police cordoned off the entrance of the union headquarters where
about 150 people, including the hunger strikers, huddled behind the
metal grates of the building. A banner strung across the building
said: ``We prefer to die of hunger fighting with dignity than to
die working as slaves.''
   About 1,500 workers from both industries have staged wildcat
strikes since Feb. 25 demanding higher wages.
   Jose Castillo Osejo, head of privately-owned Radio Corporation,
which broadcast the news of the police actions, said Interior
Minister Tomas Borge punched him in the mouth when he was summoned
to the minister's office on Friday. He said Borge apologized later.
   Castillo is also a leader of the opposition Conservative Party
and the Permanent Commission on Human Rights, a private watchdog
group.
   The weapons issue has been a major one in the Contra-Sandinista
talks, particularly whether the rebels can keep their arms.
   The rebels say they will disarm when Nicaragua is on the
``irreversible road to democracy.'' The Sandinistas say disarming
is fundamental to the pact.
   But Tinoco said an apparent split among Contra leaders made such
negotiations more difficult. The rebels deny the split.
   The rebels had been supplied arms and weapons since 1981 through
CIA-operated air drops that stopped earlier this year when Congress
rejected President Reagan's request for renewed military aid.
   Government newspapers on Friday quoted President Daniel Ortega
as saying that $17.9 million in U.S.-approved aid for children
orphaned or injured in the war would be permitted only if channeled
through neutral organizations.
   Ortega was quoted as saying his side understood the ``good
intentions'' involved in Congress' approving the money, ``but we
cannot allow it to arrive through political organisms that are
clearly against the revolution.''
   The aid, part of a nearly $48 million Contra aid package, was to
be funneled to Nicaragua through the U.S. Agency for International
Development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
