<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador     04-29 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rey Prendes Gets Governing Party Nod To Be Next President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Christian
Democrats on Friday named Julio Adolfo Rey Prendes their candidate
in next year's presidential elections, ignoring warnings that the
party may split.
   The party chief and former Cabinet minister was acclaimed by an
overwhelming majority of the delegates in a raucous congress
punctuated by insults and derisive whistles.
   No other name was proposed. Supporters of Fidel Chavez Mena, Rey
Prendes' bitter rival in the centrist party fight, boycotted the
nominating congress, claiming it was stacked in favor of Rey
Prendes.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte, the party's honorary president,
did not attend. He had urged both Rey Prendes and Chavez Mena to
step aside and let Abraham Gonzalez, an elderly party leader, be
the unity candidate. Both candidates rejected that suggestion.
   Under law, Duarte could not run for a second five-year term. He
won the presidency in the midst of a leftist civil war against the
U.S.-supported conservative government that began in 1980 and
continues.
   The number of delegates eligible to vote was 1,099. Some had
left the Sheraton Hotel auditorium by the time the vote was taken,
but hundreds of delegates raised their credentials when Rey
Prendes' name was put to the vote.
   Those opposed, including some of the party's top leaders,
mustered only 56 votes in favor of postponing the decision on a
candidate.
   The National Convention comprising about 180 delegates later
unanimously ratified Rey Prendes' nomination.
   ``If this congress makes a decision today, this party is not
going to divide, it is going to shatter,'' said Aquilino Duarte, a
member of the party's 10-member Political Committee, or
directorate. He is the minister of commerce and the president's
nephew.
   He and three other committee members urged delaying a decision
to give party leaders time to heal deep rifts caused by the rivalry.
   Roberto Viera of the Political Committee said the Christian
Democrats were dooming themselves to defeat in the March election.
   He was booed as he warned, ``If we make this decision and the
party splits, the people will not have a democratic option in the
presidential election.''
   The rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, defeated
the Christian Democrats last month in legislative and municipal
elections, putting Arena in a good position to win the presidential
election.
   Arena's detractors accuse it of being authoritarian. The party
rejects the charge, likening its ideology to that of the U.S.
Republicans.
   Arena will choose its presidential candidate in September.
   When Rey Prendes, a wealthy businessman and full-time
politician, mounted the podium to accept the nomination, most of
those who had supported postponement walked out.
   ``I'm sure that once tempers cool, we'll all be together again
in the struggle,'' Rey Prendes told the delegates. ``Let the anger
end today.''
   ``My arms are open. There is no need to exclude anyone,'' he
said in what was taken as a reference to Chavez Mena.
   But Guillermo Guevara Lacayo, a Political Committee member,
predicted Chavez Mena would try to have the congress and convention
annulled.
   Rey Prendes controls most of the party bureaucracy. He is a
former minister of communications, former mayor of San Salvador and
a member of the Political Committee. He and Chavez Mena helped
found the party in 1960.
</TEXT>
