<2ND_LINE>AM-School Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0774,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Accident in Schoolyard Claims Third Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with third person dying;
PICKS UP 10th graf pvs, `The driver ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old girl hit by a car that careened
across a crowded schoolyard died Friday, bringing the death toll
from the accident to three.
   A 4-year-old and a woman waiting for her grandchildren were
killed Thursday in the accident at the Cyrus H. McCormick
Elementary School. Seven other children were injured.
   On Friday, grieving children and teachers gathered quietly at
the school. Many of the 800 students stayed home, said kindergarten
teacher Argelia Vera, tearful as she hugged a parent on the
sidewalk before classes began.
   ``We are very sorry. We don't know what to think. It's
horrible,'' she said.
   ``It was awful. I didn't even want to come to school today. I
thought the car would still be there,'' said Sam Galarza, 12, a
sixth-grader.
   Galarza said he saw the accident that occurred just after the
school bell signaled the end of classes. A woman's car jumped the
curb, crashed through a chain-link fence and slammed into the
entrance of an annex as children were leaving.
   ``I seen the lady fly up in the air when the car hit her,'' the
boy said, adding he watched Principal Jim Crowe and others lift the
car to free people trapped underneath.
   The third person fatally injured in the accident, 10-year-old
Maria Moya, who had suffered head and chest injuries, died at Cook
County Hospital Friday afternoon, said night administrator Don
Trotter.
   Six other children, ages 5 to 9, remained hospitalized Friday in
good or fair condition, while a 29-year-old woman who was at the
school to pick up her son was treated and released Thursday.
   The driver of the car, Isabel Fuentes, 37, was charged with
leaving the scene of an accident and negligent driving, according
to Police Officer Terry Pickens. She was released after posting
$100 cash bond and her driver's license.
   Police said they believe Mrs. Fuentes was driving above the 20
mph speed limit. There was no evidence of intoxication or other
drug use, they said.
   An examination of the car revealed no evidence of mechanical
malfunction, Sgt. Thomas Reynolds said Friday. ``It's apparent
driver error,'' he said.
   Mrs. Fuentes' attorney, Lawrence Morrissey, said the facts in
the case would emerge eventually, but declined further comment.
   Eighth-grader Paul Reyna, 15, whose younger cousin attends the
school, was waiting there for his bus as usual Friday morning.
   ``It feels like a nasty nightmare. The little kids _ they're all
scared,'' he said.
   Third-grade teacher James Bailey, who helped pull people from
underneath the car, said he himself was grieving as he contemplated
trying to help youngsters get over the trauma.
   ``You do the best job you can,'' he said. ``You're not God and
you can't bring them back and heal them.''
   The dead woman was identified as Dolores Torres, between 60 and
65, who suffered severe leg injuries, said Mount Sinai hospital
spokeswoman Diann Smith.
   Crowe said Mrs. Torres, whose grandchildren attended the school,
``waits there every day faithfully to make sure her kids get home
safety.''
   The dead child was Veronica Marquez, 4, who suffered head and
abdominal injuries, said Cook County Hospital spokeswoman Wanda
Robertson.
</TEXT>
