<1ST_LINE>u w AM-OSHA-Warnings 1stLd-Writethru a0769 04-29 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA-Warnings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Rule Proposed 9 Years, 1,000 Deaths After Unions Requested
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS number of workers who would be affected by rules to
39 million, sted 3 million, in 8th graf bgng, `The agency'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department proposed Friday making
employers put warning tags or locks on machinery as it is being
cleaned or serviced _ nine years after unions requested the
regulation and more than 1,000 deaths later as a result of its
absence.
   The proposed regulations, which the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration estimates will save 122 lives and prevent
60,000 injuries annually, had languished at the White House for
nearly a year.
   Their publication in the Federal Register on Friday occurred
just one week after Senate Labor Committee Chairman Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., cited them in congressional hearings as an
example of the Reagan administration's ``decision to let workers
die while waiting on a standard.''
   Employers under the proposal would have to adopt uniform
procedures to ``lock out'' or ``tag out'' switches, valves or other
controls to prevent the start up of machines while they are being
cleaned or serviced.
   OSHA officials estimated about 7 percent of all occupational
fatalities and 2 per cent of accident-caused injuries in the
workplace occur now because such equipment is inadvertently
restarted while someone is working on it.
   ``This rule would mean safer working conditions for millions of
employees in general industry,'' Assistant Labor Secretary and OSHA
Administrator John A. Pendergrass said Friday.
   ``Very simple lockout, tagout measures, which take only a few
minutes, can prevent up to 10 percent of all the serious injuries
in some major manufacturing industries,'' Pendergrass said.
   The agency said the regulations will apply to some 1.6 million
employers and cover an estimated 39 million workers at an estimated
total annual cost of $135 million to businesses.
   They are aimed chiefly at machine operators and laborers who
work around packaging and wrapping equipment, conveyors and
printing presses, which are associated with the highest proportion
of the accidents, OSHA officials said.
   As an example, the agency cited one worker who had leaned his
head into a flour batch mixer and whose neck was crushed when
another worker inadvertently turned the machine on.
   The so-called ``performance-oriented'' regulations would require
employers only to follow certain steps in turning off equipment and
``minimize'' the potential for inadvertently reactivating it.
   Unions that began petitioning the agency for the regulations in
1979 had wanted it to mandate as law specific procedures developed
by the American National Standards Institute in 1982.
   However, OSHA said it would include the ANSI standards only as
``detailed voluntary guidelines'' in an appendix to the
regulations. The agency noted that business groups had wanted the
ANSI standards eliminated entirely from the appendix out of fears
that a court might later interpret them as mandatory.
   John Molovich, a safety specialist for the United Steelworkers
Union, predicted employers will ignore the voluntary guidelines and
``take the cheapest way out'' by using cardboard warning tags
instead of locks to prevent a machine from being turned on.
   ``There will be no positive means of assuring that the equipment
won't start,'' Molovich said of the proposed regulations. ``They
would be better off cutting it into four-inch squares and putting
it in the outhouse.''
   The proposal also exempts millions of companies and workers in
agriculture, oil and gas drilling, electric utilities, the maritime
industry and construction.
   OSHA officials said protections for them will be included in
other regulations to be proposed later.
   James Scully, an OSHA official who worked on the regulations for
more than a decade, testified at the Senate Labor Committee
hearings last week that the agency had first seen a need for them
back in 1977.
   But OSHA took no serious action until 1979, when the United Auto
Workers Union, reacting to the deaths of 22 of its members in
related accidents the previous five years, formally asked the
government for emergency action.
   OSHA denied that request and similar pleas in 1982 and 1986 from
other unions. And Scully told the Senate panel that officials in
the agency were taken off any work on them at all in 1981 and 1982.
   However, OSHA promised in 1983 to issue in 1984 what was
published Friday. Copies of the agency's regulatory agenda showed
similar promises in 1984, 1985 and 1986.
   OSHA officials said Friday that the proposed regulation was sent
to the White House Office of Management and Budget in May 1987 for
approval but was not acted on there until last month.
   The agency estimates it will be a minimum of another year before
the regulations are actually enacted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
