<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Fauci-AIDSDrugs     04-29 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fauci-AIDS Drugs,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fauci Praises Scientists, But Says Staff Shortages Have Delayed
Drug Trials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the federal agency researching
AIDS drugs said Friday he is basically satisfied with the job
scientists are doing, but acknowledged that some human trials have
been delayed due to lack of money.
   Dr. Anthony S. Fauci, director of the National Institute of
Allergy and Infectious Diseases, told the House subcommittee on
human resources that about 3,500 AIDS patients are involved in some
30 clinical trials financed with National Institutes of Health
grants.
   ``We're never satisfied, but we think we've done a pretty good
job under the circumstances,'' Fauci said under questioning from
Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., the panel chairman, and other committee
members.
   Pressed by Weiss, Fauci estimated that some trials of AIDS drugs
that could have been started this year were delayed for a year,
pending the new budget cycle, due to staff shortages.
   Fauci said that lack of personnel was ``almost exclusively'' the
reason why still more experimental drugs have not yet entered
clinical trials.
   He said his institute _ one arm of the National Institutes of
Health _ had requested 127 additional staff members for the current
fiscal year, but had received only 11 new slots in the budget
approved by Congress.
   ``The dimension of the shortfall is such that you can't possibly
meet your needs,'' concluded Weiss.
   A bill passed overwhelmingly by the Senate on Thursday would
authorize up to 300 new full-time employees to work on AIDS at the
NIH during the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
   However, the level of funds actually appropriated in any budget
hinges on recommendations from the House and Senate appropriations
subcommittees with jurisdiction over NIH. Those panels, under
overall budgetary constraints not imposed by congressional
budgetary rules on committees with jurisdiction over
authorizations, typically recommend lower levels.
   Those panels have yet to shape their recommendations on the NIH
budget for fiscal 1989.
</TEXT>
