<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:TalesofHofmann Adv03   04-29 0963</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Tales of Hofmann, Adv 03,0983</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, May 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Forgery Murders Inspire Rash of Books and TV Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One not-yet-published book about the Mark
Hofmann forgery murders has been sold to television and another to
film, but that doesn't bother authors Linda Sillitoe and Allen
Roberts.
   They believe their own volume, ``Salamander: The Story of the
Mormon Forgery Murders,'' is the one that will be read by the
Mormon community which Hofmann betrayed.
   ``The Mormon Murders: A True Story of Greed, Forgery, Deceit and
Death,'' by Steven Naifeh and Gregory White Smith and published by
Weidenfeld and Nicolson, is scheduled for August release. It has
been sold to CBS as a possible miniseries.
   ``A Gathering of Saints: A True Story of Money, Murder and
Deceit,'' by Robert Lindsey, has a September publishing date. Film
rights were purchased by 20th Century Fox.
   Roberts, a writer and architect, was a friend of Hofmann's first
victim, a fellow history buff. Sillitoe was a newspaper reporter
who used Roberts as a source early in the Hofmann story.
   Their collaboration began as an effort to explain Hofmann to the
Mormons. Two years and 556 pages later, Signature Books of Salt
Lake City, is seeking to beat two New York publishers out of a
share of the national market.
   ``I think both of us were motivated by a need to know and to
communicate with our own subculture,'' Roberts said, but they
decided later to write for non-Mormon readers as well.
   For six years that unstructured Mormon subculture of about 3,000
scholars, writers, artists and historians had been dazzled and
intrigued by Hofmann's finds of supposedly historical documents
that forced a sometimes painful re-examination of Mormon origins.
   The enigmatic Hofmann's success gave him ready access to the
high church officials numbered among his most avid customers. He
had begun to forge lucrative American historical and literary
documents when, under pressure to produce promised documents that
didn't exist, he turned to murder to cover his tracks.
   His first bomb on Oct. 15, 1985, killed a young Mormon bishop,
Steve Christensen, who had bought and donated Hofmann's most famous
creation, the so-called ``Salamander Letter,'' to the church.
   The ``Salamander Letter'' was purported to have been written by
Martin Harris, an early associate of church founder Joseph Smith.
It gives an account of Smith's finding of gold plates _ from which
he said he translated the ``Book of Mormon'' _ which is contrary to
the official church version. The letter said an ``old spirit''
directed Smith to the plates, then transformed itself into a white
salamander. The official church version has it that an angel named
Moroni directed Smith to the plates in 1827.
   A second bomb, intended to divert suspicion from Hofmann, killed
Kathy Sheets, wife of a former Christensen business partner.
   But a third bomb the next day _ which Hofmann called a suicide
device _ seriously injured its maker and exposed him as the likely
killer. Fifteen months later, in a controversial pre-trial plea
bargain, Hofmann admitted his guilt, detailed his forgeries and was
sentenced to five years to life in prison.
   ``Hofmann was such an equal opportunity rip-off artist ...
because he took everybody for what they were worth,'' said
Sillitoe, who quit her job at the Deseret News in order to work on
the book.
   ``It's not just that he exploited the (Mormon Church's) secrecy
or the paranoia that people criticize, but he also exploited the
faith, and the values and the trust and the belief. Whatever people
had to give, he exploited,'' she said.
   But ``Salamander'' is not merely an indictment of a master
manipulator and forger. The authors sought in their interviews with
some 200 sources to explain who and what had shaped a man for whom
deceit was the means and the end.
   ``I think he had a double difficulty,'' Roberts said. ``His
parentage was first-generation German and very authoritarian. And
then you add to that the fact they were orthodox, conservative
Mormons, which carres another layer of authoritarianism.''
   An inquisitive boy, Hofmann couldn't raise questions in that
environment, Roberts said. Thus, he was a secret agnostic while
serving a mission for The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints and, more than a decade later, fooled a lie detector about
the bombings.
   ``He comes right out of the heart of the culture in every way,''
Sillitoe said. ``And that's what was so fascinating to me about the
story is that everything fed into it _ the history, the theology,
the polygamy, everything. And you've got it right there on the
doorstep of the Church Office Building.''
   The authors sought to interview Hofmann, 33, at Utah State
Prison, where the state Board of Pardons recently told him he will
spend the rest of his life. But the inmate refused.
   Sillitoe and Roberts were somewhat more successful with three
church leaders who figured in the Hofmann story. They provided
written answers to a dozen typed questions. Their reticence was
understandable; Hofmann had cast them, as he had friends and
family, in the role of dupe.
   ``I think there was a strong instinct to protect the
institution,'' said Sillitoe, who regrets that the Hofmann case
seems to have invigorated the faith's ``traditional,
anti-intellectual segment.''
   For Signature Books, ``Salamander'' is unique. The company,
founded in 1981 to publish Mormon-related works, produced just six
titles in 1987 and never has spent more than $15,000 to promote any
one book.
   The Roberts-Sillitoe work has up to $100,000 in advertising. A
publicist has been hired, the authors are touring and there is a
first printing of 15,000 copies, more than double Signature's
previous high.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMTues May 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880429-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Travanti Adv04   04-29 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Travanti, Adv 04,0726</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, May 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Breaching the Acting Barrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel J. Travanti, no longer the
tight-lipped Furillo of ``Hill Street Blues,'' is entering a new
phase in his campaign to breach ``that mythical, mystical,
invisible barrier'' that separates television from movie actors.
   Travanti can be seen in theaters this month in ``Midnight
Crossing,'' a mystery thriller from Vestron Pictures. He plays the
husband of Faye Dunaway, who is blinded with glaucoma, and both
embark on a Caribbean yacht cruise that becomes enmeshed in stolen
treasure and murder.
   Travanti discussed his life after ``Hill Street Blues'' at his
Pacific Palisades home where his neighbors are John Forsythe and
Arnold Schwarzenegger. The series has obviously provided Travanti
with prosperity. But it also left him with a new challenge.
   ``The problem for many actors,'' he said, ``is that mystical,
mythical barrier that you have to cross through a misty field.
You're on this side of it and you're called `a television actor.'
Or you're called `a theater actor.' On the other side is the cinema
_ motion pictures, feature films.
   ``Somehow they see you coming and they don't want you to cross
over. I don't know why. Nobody has been able to explain it. They
used to say: `People don't want to pay to see someone when they can
see him free.' That's all changed.
   ``And so you face that strange phenomenon of crossing over that
foggy field and coming out the other side and becoming a `movie
actor.' It has nothing to do with ability necessarily, or how you
look or how you sound. Some make it, and some don't.
   ``Since I finished the series last year, I've done what I wished
I could do. I went from `Midnight Crossing' to a play, `I Never
Sang for My Father,' which had a successful six-month tour. And now
I'm doing another movie with Kris Kristofferson and Cheryl Ladd,
`Millennium.' So by summer I will have done two feature films and a
successful play tour. And my next television appearance will be an
American Playhouse version of the play in June.''
   The actor doesn't worry about escaping the persona of Frank
Furillo.
   ``I did that in the first season of `Hill Street Blues,''' he
said, ``by playing totally different characters in television
movies, `Adam' and `A Case of Libel.' And I also played Edward R.
Murrow on television.
   ``Not all of the characters have been straight-arrow like the
captain. The guy I played in `A Matter of Libel' was ... complex.
... The guy in `Midnight Crossing' is maybe a less-controlled
cousin of that fellow, so to speak. Ed Murrow, one of the heroes of
our time, was also a complicated man, though we couldn't show much
of that in a two-hour movie.''
   Daniel J. Travanti is a late bloomer as an actor.
   ``I charged through college (University of Wisconsin) in three
years with Phi Beta Kappa and every other honor. I knocked my
brains out. I don't know what ... I was rushing toward. No matter
how fast I ran, it turned out I couldn't get there any faster than
I was supposed to.
   ``In New York, it all screeched to a crawl,'' he said. ``Many
actors, who are told they are talented in school or regional
theaters, get to New York City and get stonewalled _ not frozen
out; I worked all the time. I was just so confused and so neurotic
that I drove myself crazy. And I drove others around me crazy.
   ``For a long time I limped along and bumped along and hiccupped
along. I always made a living _ this fall will mark 25 years as an
actor, never having to work as anything else. The big turning point
came 15 years ago when I found sobriety,'' he said, referring to
his alcoholism.
   ``I don't want to belabor that, because I don't want it to be an
overpowering identity of mine. But I am willing to mention it and
talk about it privately.
   ``Since then it's been a matter of patiently trudging, chugging,
moving steadily along and hoping for a break.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Wed May 4</NOTE>
