<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0819EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Malden Adv13-15   04-29 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Malden, Adv 13-15,0787</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13-15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 13-15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karl Malden says ``My Father, My Son'' is the
story of a close-knit family rather than a story of Vietnam and the
tragedy of Agent Orange.
   Malden plays Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., who ordered the use of
the chemical defoliant Agent Orange to cler the jungle away from
Vietnam's rivers to protect Navy patrol boats. Keith Carradine
plays his son, Elmo R. Zumwalt III, a former patrol boat skipper,
who believes his cancer was caused by the defoliant.
   ``I think what you're going to see is a terrific family love
story,'' said Malden. ``I've never seen a family so tight.''
   The two-hour film is based on the book the Zumwalts wrote about
their experiences. The movie, which CBS will televise Sunday, May
22, was shot in Georgia.
   ``It's a fascinating story,'' said Malden. ``When the admiral
was assigned to Vietnam, his son wanted to go, too. And when the
admiral gets there he realizes the Viet Cong are knocking off the
boat crews left and right because the jungle goes right down to the
river. It was giving them protection.
   ``The admiral heard they were using Agent Orange in Missouri and
Kansas to kill weeds on some farms. He looked into it and then
ordered its use. The irony is that his son was captain of one of
those little river boats, and his son was the only one on his boat
to get sick.''
   Elmo III was afflicted with two kinds of cancer, lymphoma and
Hodgkin's Disease, which both Zumwalts believe was caused by Agent
Orange. He has undergone chemotherapy, radiation and bone marrow
transplants.
   ``The admiral did some investigating later and found the
government had led him astray about Agent Orange,'' said Malden.
``The government knew there was a higher rate of cancer in those
areas where it was used as a defoliant and withheld the
information.''
   In addition, the younger Zumwalt has a son with a learning
disability.
   ``Elmo and his wife came with their two children when we were
shooting the boat scenes,'' said Malden. ``They built a little
village in the swamp. The boy was so excited. I was in uniform and
wearing the admiral's name badge. Elmo told his son, who's about 10
or 12, `This is grandpa.'
   ``All that day I was grandpa to the boy and he kept kissing me.
On the boat going back he sat next to me. His affection was so
touching. I had to look the other way. I think the admiral feels
he's the cause of Elmo's and the boy's problem. I think he feels
guilty.''
   This was not Malden's first military role. He played Gen. Omar
Bradley in ``Patton.'' He was in ``Winged Victory,'' the Army Air
Corps stage show in World War II that was also filmed as a movie.
   ``After the war, I was in every kind of war movie,'' he said.
``I was a private, a corporal and I was the good sergeant to
Richard Widmark's tough sergeant in `Take the High Ground.'''
   Malden, who had made his movie debut before the war, won an
Oscar as best supporting actor for ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
Three years later, he teamed up with Marlon Brando again for ``On
the Waterfront.''
   Most recently, he co-starred in the Barbra Streisand movie
``Nuts.''
   Malden, well-known to television audiences for his 15 years as
spokesman for American Express travelers checks, played Lt. Mike
Stone in the TV series ``Streets of San Francisco.'' His co-star,
Michael Douglas, just won an Academy Award as best actor for ``Wall
Street.'' Malden's only other series was ``Skag,'' in which he
played a steel mill worker. That was a role he played in real life
in his hometown of Gary, Ind., before he became an actor.
   ``My father was an amateur actor in Europe and after he came to
this country he organized 30 church choirs,'' he said. ``He was
president for six years of the Serbian Singing Society of the U.S.
and Canada. He was a milkman and did that when he had time off.
   ``I decided to become an actor because I wasn't getting anywhere
in the mills. I had friends at the Art Institute in Chicago and
decided to go there. When I told my father he said, `Are you crazy?
You want to give up a good job in the middle of the Depression?'
Thank God for my mother. She said to give it a try.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 13-15</NOTE>
