<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Brazil-ForeignBusiness     04-29 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Foreign Business,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mineral Mining Limited To Brazilian Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a victory for Brazil's left,
lawmakers re-writing Brazil's authoritarian constitution have voted
overwhelmingly to limit mineral mining to domestic companies.
   The Thursday night vote came on the heels of a Wednesday vote to
give special protections to certain domestically-owned enterprises,
a move that foreign businessmen indicated may discourage the influx
of foreign capital to Brazil's beleaguered economy.
   Legislators doubling as a constituent assembly sang the national
anthem Thursday night after voting to prohibit foreign companies
from mining for minerals or drilling for hydraulic energy.
   The constitutional article would give foreign companies such as
subsidiaries of British Petroleum, bauxite mining companies such as
Alcan and Alcoa and South Africa's Anglo-American Company a
five-year grace period to adapt to the new legislation.
   Foreign-owned companies control 20 percent of mining rights or
requests for mining rights in Brazil. Private domestic companies
own 52 percent and state-run companies own 18 percent.
   Also on Thursday, legislators voted 303-156 to maintain present
legislation allowing foreign participation in petroleum
distribution.
   A radical proposal that was rejected would have barred Royal
Dutch Shell, Atlantic Richfield, Texaco and Exxon from selling
gasoline in Brazil. Foreign companies now hold 55 percent of the
market here.
   The Thursday votes followed Wednesday's equally radical
decisions making it harder and less inviting for foreign companies
to operate in Brazil. In a bipartisan agreement, law-makers voted
to define what constitutes a ``Brazilian company'' and a
``domestic-capital Brazilian company.''
   The key distinction is that domestic-capital companies will
enjoy as yet-undetermined ``protection and special benefits'' and
will be allowed to develop the also yet-undetermined ``strategic or
essential'' areas of the economy.
   Legislators decided that a domestic-capital company must have a
majority of its voting capital and its decision-making power
belonging permanently to residents of this country. A Brazilian
company would be simply any company established under Brazilian law.
   The congress is expected to finish Brazil's eighth constitution
late this year.
   Rep. Sandra Cavalcanti, of the conservative Liberal Front Party,
said the new laws prevent multinationals from being considered
national, that is Brazilian, concerns.
   ``It's not fair that, say, a General Motors has the right and
the access to Brazilian savings,'' she said. ``This way, they can
come in but with their own investments and own foreign savings.''
   But the new statutes were widely considered nationalistic, and
the initial reaction of foreign businessmen was negative.
   ``The red flag is up for foreign capital,'' said Christopher
Lund, president of the Sao Paulo American Chamber of Commerce in a
telephone interview. ``It is unfortunate because they made it more
difficult to do business in Brazil.''
   Lund, a businessman who has lived in Brazil since 1962, said the
law will be harmful to the Brazilian economy by limiting the vital
influx of foreign capital.
   Brazil is strapped with a huge foreign debt of $121 billion,
inflation of over 16 percent monthly and one of the world's most
unequal distributions of wealth. About two-thirds of the nation's
143 million people earn less than $40 a week.
   ``Brazilians have the right to change their own laws, but if
their true objective is to change the life of millions of
Brazilians, you first have to have an economy that will generate
wealth,'' said Lund. ``You can't do that by limiting foreign
capital.''
   Wolfgang Sauer, a West German-born naturalized Brazilian who is
president of Autolatina, the local holding group for Ford and
Volkswagen, said ``discrimination will not resolve the economic
problems of this country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
