<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned in a mixed performance in Europe
early today as traders awaited release of economic data from the
United States and Britain.
   Gold prices dipped below $450 a troy ounce.
   The dollar drifted within a narrow range in the first hours of
European trading.
   Late month commercial dealings kept the market moderately
active, but many players were staying to the sidelines prior to the
release later today of the U.S. index of leading economic
indicators for March.
   In London, the pound was quoted at 1.8765 dollars, up slightly
from 1.8755 dollars late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at midmorning, compared with late
Thursday, were: 1.6675 West German marks, down from 1.6705; 1.3865
Swiss francs, up from 1.3832; 5.6680 French francs, down from
5.6685; 1.8700 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8715; 1,241.20 Italian
lire, up from 1,240.50; 1.2295 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2297
   Japanese markets were closed for Emperor Hirohito's birthday.
The dollar was quoted 124.65 yen in London, fractionally down from
124.82 yen at the close of business in Tokyo on Thursday.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of
$449.75 dollars a troy ounce at midmorning, down from $451 late
Thursday.
   A trader said buying interest began to wane in New York on
Thursday as hopes faded that an oil-price stabilization pact would
emerge from the meeting in Vienna of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $449.70, down from $452.
   Earlier, closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $451.17, down from
$453.54.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.47 a troy
ounce, down from $6.50.
</TEXT>
