<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BritishStocks     04-29 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Boosted By Trade Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices moved higher Friday when Britain's
unexpectedly good trade figures for March briefly energized the
market.
   The Financial Times-Stock Excahnge 100-share index was up 1
point, or 0.06 percent at 1,805.4, at about noon (1100 GMT).
   The market jumped about 5 points immediately after the release
of the trade data.
   Volume was a modest 273.3 million shares, with investors
disinclined to take major positions ahead of a three-day holiday
weekend in Britain. Monday is a bank holiday.
   By the same time Thursday, volume was 276.8 million shares.
   Although the market moved upward following the government's
release of its trade report, share prices fell back when little
follow-through buying appeared.
   ``The figures were good but we didn't see any substantive buying
because it's in front of a long weekend,'' said Jim Young, a trader
at Alexanders Laing and Cruickshank Ltd.
   Britain's merchandise trade balance narrowed unexpectedly
sharply in March to a seasonally adjusted 854 million pounds, or
$1.61 billion, from 1.32 billion pounds, or $2.48 billion, in
February, the government said.
   Private economists had predicted a merchandise trade deficit of
1.1 billion pounds, or $2.07 billion.
</TEXT>
