<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoRecall     04-29 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Recall,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Announces Recall of Nearly 26,000 Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. announced it was recalling
nearly 26,000 1988-model cars to fix possible problems with a
transmission cable that could cause false readings in the gear
shift indicator.
   Included in the recall were about 17,500 Buick Regals and about
8,400 Pontiac Grand Prix models, GM said Thursday in a written
statement.
   Both models have potential problems with the transmission cable
that could cause the cars to be in a gear other than that displayed
on the shift indicator, GM said.
   Some Regals also may have a faulty stoplamp switch, which could
make the brake lights inoperative when the brake pedal is
depressed, GM said.
   In addition, the secondary hood latch of some of the cars may
not engage properly, presenting the danger of the hood opening
unexpectedly if the primary latch were to malfunction.
   GM said it was unaware of any accidents or injuries due to the
potential problems. Owners were being notified to take the cars to
dealers, who will make repairs at no cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
