<DOCNO> AP880429-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-U.S.-Japan     04-29 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-U.S.-Japan,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Progress in Beef-Orange Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese officials have reported no
progress after a third day of meetings to break a deadlock over
lowering Japanese trade barriers against American beef and oranges.
   They agreed to meet again today, but no one on the U.S.
delegation was optimistic about the outcome, said Gary Holmes,
spokesman for the chief American negotiator, Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter.
   The differences between the two sides ``have not been
narrowed,'' said Hidero Maki, spokesman and economic affairs chief
for Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato, Japan's negotiator. The
negotiations are going to take longer than anticipated, Maki told
reporters Thursday.
   Adding to the gloom, U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker told
a gathering of Washington visitors, ``chances are not as bright as
I'd like to see,'' that Japan will further open its market to beef
and oranges.
   Baker repeated warnings that the U.S. government will try to
have the Japanese import quotas declared illegal under the rules of
GATT, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The United States had been requesting that Japan end the quotas
that the two countries agreed to in a four-year pact that expired
at the end of March with the collapse of an earlier round of
Sato-Yeutter negotiations.
   U.S. officials said ending the quotas was still the demand. They
declined to comment on Japanese reports that a compromise was under
discussion.
   The talks have been centering on ``the timing of
liberalization'' of imports into Japan, said Japanese Embassy
spokesman Toshiyuki Takano.
   According to Maki, four specific topics are covered in the
negotiations.
   They are: improvement of access to the Japanese market; future
role of Japan's Livestock Industry Promotion Corporation, the
semigovernment body that now handles 80 percent of beef imports;
interim measures pending liberalization and measures to follow
lifting of the quotas, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
