<DOCNO> AP880429-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NC-RanchoSeco     04-29 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NC-Rancho Seco,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Carolina's Duke Power Agrees to Run California Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Duke Power Co. has tentatively agreed to
operate the troubled Rancho Seco nuclear plant in California,
company officials said.
   The deal is dependent on approval by Sacramento voters to
restart the troubled facility, idled since an emergency shutdown in
December 1985, said Bill Lee, Duke's chairman and chief executive
officer.
   ``If the Sacramento voters approve, we are confident that we can
operate Rancho Seco in a safe and efficient manner,'' Lee said in
announcing the agreement Thursday at the company's annual meeting
in Charlotte.
   ``Competition is increasing and the shackles of regulation seem
to be loosening in some quarters,'' Lee told shareholders. ``There
is risk, but also great opportunity.''
   Three of Duke's seven nuclear units have the same Babcock &
Wilcox Co. reactor design as the Rancho Seco plant.
   Details of the agreement in principle with the Sacramento
Municipal Utility District were not disclosed.
   Lee said operating Rancho Seco, about 25 miles south of
Sacramento, would enable the Charlotte-based utility to diversify
and market its engineering and technical services _ and thus
increase diversified earnings.
   A negotiating team headed by Doug Booth, Duke's president and
chief operating officer, met for several hours Wednesday in
Charlotte with Richard Byrne, SMUD's genera manager, and other SMUD
officials to discuss an operating arrangement, Duke officials said.
   The plant currently is the object of two competing local
initiatives on June 7 in California and one, offered by SMUD and
supported by Duke, would authorize an 18-month test operating
period. The other would close the plant permanently.
   Ed Smeloff, one of SMUD's five directors, attended Duke's annual
meeting and accused Duke of interfering with SMUD's internal
affairs and ``meddling'' with the ballot measure.
   Smeloff criticized Duke for contributing $100,000 to the
campaign to keep the plant running and pleaded with shareholders:
``Please let us make that decision ourselves.''
   In a subsequent interview, Smeloff said, ``I don't have a
problem with Duke wanting to come out and run a plant efficiently.
I don't have a problem with Duke wanting to make some money in
Sacramento. My problem is the integrity of the Sacramento political
process.''
   Duke abandoned its interest in owning the plant after it failed
to find a California partner.
   But Lee, in an interview Thursday, said, ``We think we're doing
what's in our interests and the interests of those consumers.''
   ``The plant hasn't run well,'' he conceded. ``But they have
invested $1 billion in it. The incremental cost of running it, now
that they've already got that investment, is very little and lower
than any other source of electricity in California.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
