<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade,0125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Narrows Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed
unexpectedly and sharply in March to a seasonally adjusted $1.61
billion from $$2.48 billion in February, the government said Friday.
   However, the deficit was much wider than the deficit a year ago,
which came to $703 million.
   Britain's total trade deficit also narrowed sharply. That
figure, which includes merchandise, services, overseas investment
earnings and transfer payments, showed a $478 million deficit in
March compared with a $1.35 billion deficit in February and a $556
million surplus in March 1987, the Department of Trade and Industry
said.
   Private economists had predicted a merchandise deficit of $1.1
billion and a total deficit of $1.02 billion for March.
</TEXT>
