<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 1102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Texas     04-29 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Texas,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Railroad Commissioner Says OPEC Shows Interest In Visiting
Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC's president is interested in either visiting
Texas or sending representatives to learn better ways of monitoring
the cartel's oil production, Texas Railroad Commissioner Kent Hance
says.
   In a telephone interview Thursday with The Houston Post from
Vienna, Austria, Hance said he met for about 90 minutes with
Rilwanu Lukman, OPEC president and oil minister of Nigeria.
   ``We discussed the monitoring procedures we use at the
commission to know what everyone is producing,'' Hance was quoted
as saying. ``He expressed interest in coming to Texas or at least
sending some of his staff to see how we do that.''
   The Texas Railroad Commission regulates oil production in the
state, which was devastated economically by a collapse in world oil
prices two years ago.
   Alleged quota cheating by some members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries has been blamed for the current
global oil glut and the weak prices. Members of the cartel have
been meeting with non-member nations in Vienna to discuss ways to
stabilize prices.
   Hance did not participate in the meetings, but came to hold
private talks with participants. His presence received widespread
attention and incited speculation of a possible strategic
relationship between OPEC and Texas, which would be the cartel's
fourth-largest oil producer if it were a member.
   Non-OPEC producers attending the meeting have suggested both
OPEC and non-OPEC oil producers agree to 5 percent oil production
cuts in order to boost prices.
   ``They've never really asked about Texas making cuts,'' Hance
said. ``But I told them we could not, would not consider making
cuts because we consume more than we produce.''
   Earlier this week, Hance said he saw his mission as `opening a
dialogue'' with the cartel.
   ``We're not in love with OPEC, but we need to have input'' into
decisions by an organization that controls about 35 percent of the
world's oil supplies, he said.
   ``I look at what's happened to our Texas economy'' since oil
prices crashed in 1986, he said. ``No one else is going to be
speaking up for the state of Texas, and someone had to do
something.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
