<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Colgate-Palmolive     04-29 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Colgate-Palmolive,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plans to Sell Kendall Health Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer-products giant Colgate-Palmolive Co. is
putting the Kendall Health Care unit up for sale as part of a
previously announced strategy to concentrate on its other
businesses.
   Colgate-Palmolive's decision to sell Kendall, which had sales of
$1 billion lat year, came several months after the company sold two
divisions of Kendall for approximately $200 million.
   The company said in a statement Thursday that the sale of
Kendall's remaining operations would ``provide Colgate with
significantly greater financial flexibility.''
   Prospective buyers or a sale price were not disclosed. But
industry analysts have said Kendall could bring in at least $1
billion.
   Kendall makes hospital supplies and home health-care products,
including medical bandages, intravenous solutions and respiratory
therapy devices.
   Based in New York, Colgate-Palmolive is one of the largest
consumer-product and personal care companies, with sales of $5.6
billion in 1987.
   Its home cleansing products include Fresh Start, Fab, Dynamo and
Ajax; personal-care products include Colgate and Ultra Brite
toothpastes, Irish Spring and Palmolive soaps and Curad bandages.
   Other operations include Princess House crystal and Hill's pet
products.
</TEXT>
