<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The main negative influence was the unusally large number of
notices posted Thursday at the exchange of intent to deliver wheat,
corn, soybeans and soybean oil against the May contracts for those
commodities, analysts said.
   The notices indicate ample supplies exist.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.05\ a bushel; corn was { cent to
1 cent lower with May at $1.99\ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to
{ cent higher with May at $1.61 a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents
lower to \ cent higher with May at $6.76 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .13 cent lower with June at 70.77
cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .25 cent higher with
May at 78.70 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent to .10 cent lower
with June at 48.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .25 cent
to .30 cent lower with May at 51.30 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
