<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Corning-RevereWare 1stLd-Writehtru f0028 04-29 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Corning-Revere Ware, 1st Ld-Writehtru, f0028,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corning To Purchase Revere Ware</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, Revere Ware ..., with one graf to UPDATE
withcomments from Revere Ware president. Picks up 5th graf pvs,
About a ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works, the nation's leading
maker of cookware, said Friday it has signed a definitive agreement
to purchase Revere Ware Inc., the second-largest manufacturer of
range-top cookware.
   Corning said the acquisition would be made in cash, but
spokesman Eugene Saunders would not comment on a report that the
price was $120 million.
   Revere Ware, a Clinton, Ill.-based maker of stainless steel and
copper cookware, is a subsidiary of the privately held Revere
Copper and Brass Inc., founded by Paul Revere in 1801.
   ``The sale was very good for our company,'' Revere Ware
President Peter Cameron said Friday from his Illinois office. ``The
two companies are very well alligned. There's little redundancy.''
   About a quarter of Corning's $2.1 billion in annual revenue
comes from consumer products made of glass or glass-ceramics sold
under the Pyrex Corning Ware Visions and Corelle trademarks,
Corning said.
   The acquisition, to be completed by the end of June, would add
more than 10 percent to Corning's consumer products sales. The
company's consumer products division reported sales of $547.9
million in 1987.
   Corning Chairman James R. Houghton said the acquisition ``offers
us a strong brand name and a business that complements our own,
affording us added value in the consumer marketplace.''
   He said the deal will not dilute earnings in the first 12 months
of operation and after that period, would be a contributor to
earnings.
   ``We know that Revere will substantially strengthen Corning's
position in department stores, and that Corning can significantly
broaden Revere's position in other markets,'' Houghton said.
   In addition to consumer housewares, Corning manufactures
automobile pollution control devices, fiber optics and specialty
glass and ceramics. It also operates a network of clinical testing
labs.
   Corning recently was outbid by pharmaceutical giant SmithKline
Beckman Corp. in an attempt to purchase International Clinical
Laboratories Inc. of Nashville, Tenn.
</TEXT>
