<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Ecuador-Oil     04-29 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ecuador-Oil,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecuador Signs Oil Contract U.S.-Dutch Consortium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Dutch consortium has signed a
contract with the government here to explore for and produce oil in
Ecuador's eastern Amazon River basin, the government said.
   The agreement calls for a four-year exploration stage and a $58
million investment, the government said in a press release issued
after a signing ceremony presided over by President Leon Febres
Cordero on Thursday.
   The consortium is composed of Unocal Corp. and a subsidary of
Union Pacific Resources Co. of the United States and Ned Lloyd
Energy BV of Holland.
   More than a dozen foreign oil firms or consortiums have begun
working in Ecuador since Febres Cordero, a pro-business
conservative, took office four years ago and embarked on a policy
of attracting oil companies through risk investment contracts.
   Ecuador, a member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, currently produces 300,000 42-gallon barrels of oil a
day and exports about half of that.
</TEXT>
