<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
Europe on Friday, reflecting a belief among traders that the
American economy is strengthening and U.S. interest rates are
rising. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the announcement that the March
U.S. index of leading indicators rose 0.8 percent, together with
other signs of upturn, gave a positive picture of the U.S. economy.
   They said the announcement that the Riggs National Bank of
Washington increased its prime lending rate to 8.75 percent from
8.5 percent further convinced the market that U.S. interest rates
are rising. Higher interest rates make the dollar more attractive
to foreigners.
   The day's dramatic moves appeared in British sterling trading,
following the announcement of better-than-expected British trade
data. Dealers said the Bank of England intervened to smooth the
pound's rise.
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed unexpectedly in
March to a seasonally adjusted $1.61 billion from $2.48 billion in
February, the government said Friday.
   In late trading, the pound was quoted at $1.8785, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.8755 late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe late Friday compared with late
Thursday included: 1.6725 West German marks, up from 1.6705; 1.3910
Swiss francs, up from 1.3832; 5.6805 French francs, up from 5.6685;
1.8745 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8715; 1,242.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,240.50; 1.2280 Canadian dollars, down from 1.22965.
   Japanese markets were closed for Emperor Hirohito's birthday.
The dollar was quoted at 124.80 yen in London, fractionally down
from 124.82 yen at the close of business Thursday in Tokyo.
   Gold prices in London late Friday were quoted at a price of
$449.25 a troy ounce, down from $451 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $449.00, down from $452.00.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid $451.17, down from
$453.54.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid $6.45, down from
$6.50.
</TEXT>
