<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AsianBank     04-29 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asian Bank,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan and United States Clash at Regional Bank Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan called Friday for raising the
Asian Development Bank's capital but faced opposition from the
United States, in what appeared to be a struggle for influence over
the financial institution.
   In a speech to 1,500 bankers and finance officials from 47
countries, Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita said his country wants
to recycle up to $30 billion in trade surplus funds. One way is by
increasing its stock in the 21-year-old development bank, Sumita
said.
   He said the bank, established to hasten economic development of
poor Asia-Pacific countries, has to expand technical assistance to
developing countries and increase loans not only to governments but
also to private businesses to reduce poverty in the region.
   ``If ADB is to respond to these issues and to achieve growth, it
is imperative that the bank's own financial base be strengthened,
for it is upon this foundation that all operations rest,'' he said.
``And I believe that a general capital increase is urgently
needed.''
   The bank currently has an authorized capital of $22.8 billion.
   Sumita told the annual meeting of the bank's board of governors
that Japan wants to increase its share in the bank's capital from
15 percent at present to at least 16.41 percent. ``And I hope the
governors will give this request their favorable consideration,''
he added.
   But M. Peter McPherson, deputy U.S. Treasury secretary, opposed
any capital increase, saying, ``Financially, the bank remains in
excellent shape.''
   ``At this time, my government does not foresee agreement on a
(general capital increase) before early 1990, and clearly our
position on these negotiations will be much influenced by our
perceptions of the bank's plans for using its resources,'' he said.
   Sources at the bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Japan is trying to expand its influence over the bank by increasing
its shareholdings and thus have the most votes at a time when the
United States is faced with budgetary difficulties and cutting back
on expenses.
   The bank, set up in 1966, is owned and controlled by the
governments of 18 developed states and 29 developing Asian and
Pacific countries. Policy is formulated by the board of governors,
which meets every year and is composed of the 47 member-countries'
finance ministers or central bank chiefs.
   The bank's annual report for 1987 shows that Japan had a slight
edge over the United States, controlling 15 percent of total shares
and 12.4 percent of total voting power, against 14.7 percent and
12.2 percent for the United States.
</TEXT>
