<HEAD>London Share Prices End Almost Unchanged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange ended
almost unchanged Friday as a fickle market shrugged off some good
news about the nation's trade outlook.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed at
1,802.2, off 2.2 points, or 0.1 percent.
   There was a slight, short-lived rally after the government
reported an unexpected sharp drop in Britain's merchandise trade
deficit in March, to a seasonally adjusted 854 million pounds, or
$1.61 billion, from 1.32 billion pounds, or $2.48 billion, in
February.
   Private economists had expected a deficit of 1.1 billion pounds,
or $2.07 billion.
   ``There was a reasonable bit of euphoria after the trade
figures, but the main institutions didn't buy with any
follow-through,'' said one equity salesman, adding that when Wall
Street opened lower, it added pressure to the London market.
   Around midafternoon, share prices continued their slump after
news that a U.S. regional bank, Riggs National Bank of Washington,
D.C., raised its prime lending rate to 8.75 percent from 8.5
percent, troubling market players about the outlook for U.S.
interest rates.
