<HEAD>Soybean Futures Post Big Gain; Grains Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rallied in the last hour
of trading to close sharply higher Friday on the Chicago Board of
Trade. Grain futures were mixed.
   No single factor sparked the runup in soybean futures but
revised weather forecasts, predicting less rain in the Corn Belt
than previous reports played a role, said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Government estimates for a low carryover of U.S. soybean stocks
into the next marketing year have put the market on edge,
Lespinasse said.
   ``The soybean market is extremely sensitive to weather because
if we don't have a good crop this year they're going to cut that
carryover down to the bone,'' he said.
   Overall support stemmed from persistently bullish underlying
fundamental and technical factors, he said.
   ``First and foremost, you've got to remember that we're in a
bull market and in a bull market, prices go up,'' Lespinasse said.
   Wheat futures closed mixed while corn futures finished slightly
higher.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.04{ a bushel; corn was } cent to
2{ cents higher with May at $2.02\ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1}
cents lower with May at $1.59\ a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents to
13{ cents higher with May at $6.89 a bushel.
