<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HolmesaCourt Bjt   04-29 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holmes a Court, Bjt,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Tycoon Sells His Empire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Robert Holmes a Court, whose
fortune dwindled from billions to millions in October's market
crash, sold most of his stake in his Bell Group Ltd. business
empire Friday.
   Two investor groups said they paid a total of 333 million
Australian dollars, or about $253 million, for a nearly 40 percent
interest in Bell Group, which has interests in a variety of
industries.
   The sale reduced Holmes a Court's stake in Bell Group, which
controls 43 percent of Bell Resources Ltd., to about 3 percent.
   The announcement ended days of speculation about the future of
the once-feared corporate raider and also tolled the end of an era
in Australian business.
   Holmes a Court, who at the peak of his success was one of
Australia's wealthiest men, earning an estimated $43 every second,
is reported to have become tired of corporate life, particularly in
the wake of the stock market crash.
   The companies he controlled lost about $380 million, the biggest
corporate loss in Australian history, due to investment writedowns
in the wake of the global market collapse.
   Under the deal announced Friday, the Western Australian State
Government Insurance Commission and Alan Bond, a brewing and media
magnate who won the America's Cup in 1983, each purchased 19.9
percent stakes in Bell Group.
   The commission said it paid the equivalent of $1.90 a share for
its stake, or about $122 million. Bond, who made his purchase
through Bond Corp., paid $2.05 a share, or about $131.5 million.
   Both parties said they regarded their holdings as investments
only and noted that they did not collaborate in purchasing Bell
shares.
   SGIC Chairman Wyvern Rees said the government authority would
not interfere with Bell Group's management.
   Holmes a Court is expected to remain chairman and chief
executive of Bell Group, said Peter Mitchell, Bond Corp.'s
executive director.
   Calling Holmes a Court's decision to sell most of his Bell Group
holdings ``undoubtedly difficult,'' Mitchell said Bond Corp. was
satisfied with its investment and had no plans to try to acquire
the rest of the company.
   Since the market crash Holmes a Court has been selling assets to
help ease his cash crunch. Bell Group and Bell Resources have sold
off assets valued at about $3.42 billion.
   In November, Holmes a Court sold Bell's 12.3 percent stake in
U.S. oil giant Texaco Inc. to takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn for
$795.5 million, taking an esimtated $96 million loss on the
transaction.
   Earlier that month he also sold a 2.5 percent stake in Broken
Hill Proprietary Co., Australia's largest company, to other
interests for nearly $200 million. He sold some of his properties
in Perth for about $140 million.
   Broken Hill, which has major interests in the United States,
South America and elsewhere, had been threatened in recent years by
Bell Resources, which amassed an 11 percent stake in the company
through several takeover bids. Mitchell said Bond Corp. approved of
Bell Group's asset sales so far but did not want the company to
divest its West Australian Newspapers Ltd.
   Bond Corp. owns one of Australia's three commerical national
television networks. Its stake in Bell Group could raise questions
as to whether Bond Corp. is in violation of the government's media
cross-ownership laws, which limit the size of investments in
television and newspaper concerns in the same city.
   Separately, Holmes a Court dropped his plan to merge Bell Group
with Bell Resources, giving way to a pair of corporate raiders
bidding for Bell Resources.
   Bell Resources, a mining and investment concern, is the subject
of a $684 million takeover bid by Sir Ronald Brierley's Industrial
Equity Ltd. and Kerry Packer's Consolidated Press Holdings Ltd.
   The merger proposal was seen by many analysts as a move to
simplify Holmes a Court's corporate structure after the October
stock market crash, to put togther Bell Resource's cash and
investments with Bell Group's industrial operations, and therefore
to reduce Bell Group's heavy borrowings.
</TEXT>
