<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Prices Ease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against most major
currencies Friday, boosted slightly by fresh data indicating the
U.S. economy remains healthy.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National ~ank quoted bullion at
$450 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, unchanged from late Wednesday.
   Traders said the dollar firmed on a government report that the
Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.8 percent in March.
   The announcement that the Riggs National Bank of Washington
increased its prime lending rate to 8.75 percent from 8.5 percentZfurther
convinced the market that U.S. interest res are rising.
Higher interest rates make the dollar more attractive to foreigners.
   But despite the apparent {trength of the U.S. economy, investors
are shying away from aggressive dollar-buying because of|the
implications strong indicators have on the trade picture.
   ``A good U.S. economy is not good for the trade deficit''
because it means Americans are continuing to buy foreign goods,
said Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice president at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co.
   Much of the day's activity occurred in her currencies.
Investors bought the British pound following the announcement of
better-than-expectedpFritish trade data.
   The government announced that Britain's merchandise trade
deficit narrowed une~pectedly in March to a seqsonally adjusted
$1.61 billion from $2.48 billion in February.
   Dealers said the Bank of England intervened to smooth the
pound's rise. ``Sterling weakened a bit on profit-taking, which
encouraged the dollar to move up a bit higher,'' Flanagan said.
   Overall, however, the dollar traded in a narrow range. ``There
still is not enough reason to get out of the trading range,'' said
Earl Johnson, a vice president at Harris Trust and Savings Bank in
Chicago.
   ``There is   ...   to buy or sell dollars at
this point,'' he said.
   Japanese markets were closed for Emperor Hirohito's birthday.
Traders said activity was light, particularly because of the
absence of Japanese investors.
   In European dealings, the dollar rose against most major
currencies.
   In late trading, the ...  was quoted at $1.8785, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.8755 late Thursday. In New York it
cost $1.8755 to buy one pound, more expensive than Thursday's
$1.87385.
   In London the dollar was quoted at 124.80 Japanese yen,
fractionally down from 124.82 yen at the close of business Thursday
in Tokyo. In New York the dollar closed at 125.135 yen, up from
124.515 yen on Thursday.
  `her late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.6773 West German marks, up from 1.6694;
1.39775 Swiss francs, up from 1.38425; 5.6965 French francs, up
from 5.6710; 1,248.00 Italian lire, up from 1,242.375, and 1.22895
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2302.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday: 1.6725
West German marks, up from 1.6705; 1.3910 Swiss francs, up from
1.3832; 5.6805 French francs, up from 5.6685; 1.8745 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8715; 1,242.00 Italian lire, up from 1,240.50;
1.2280 Canadian dollars, down from 1.22965.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold closed at $451 a troy
ounce, up from $450.60 on Thursday.
   In London, gold was quoted at a late price of $449.25 an ounce,
