<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Airlines     04-29 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Parent, Pan Am Post First-Quarter Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. and the parent of Northwest Airlines on Friday
reported losses for the first quarter which they blamed on higher
costs.
   New York-based Pan Am, the eighth-largest airline, said its
first quarter net loss narrowed to $83.3 million from $93.6 million
a year earlier.
   Revenue jumped 18 percent, to $900.8 million from $763.1 million
in the first three months of 1987.
   St. Paul-based NWA Inc., which operates Northwest, said it had a
first quarter net loss of $43.5 million, widened from a loss of $35
million in the first three months of 1987.
   The loss occurred despite an increase in first-quarter revenue,
to $1.24 billion from $1.17 billion a year earlier.
   Pan Am said an improved performance by its Northeast shuttle
service and Pan Am World Services helped narrow its loss from a
year earlier. The air shuttle links New York, Boston and
Washington, while Pan Am World Services provides ground services to
other carriers in airports around the world.
   The company's main subsidiary, Pan American World Airways,
posted an operating loss of $62 million in the first quarter,
widened from a $51.1 million loss a year earlier. The deterioration
was blamed on increases in the costs of fuel, advertising, aircraft
rentals and other expenses.
   The loss at Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest airline, was
attributed to rising costs and a strike threat by flight
attendants. The company said its earnings also were affected by a
$10 million one-time writedown of accounts receivable from a travel
wholesaler.
   ``Higher fuel, payroll, travel agent commission and maintenance
costs combined with the threat of a flight attendant strike
contributed to the increased operating loss,'' said Steven G.
Rothmeier, NWA's chairman and chief executive officer.
   He said that compared with the first quarter of 1987, the price
of fuel for the airline jumped by 7.3 cents a gallon to 59.2 cents,
payroll expenses increased 7.4 percent to $407.8 million, and
commissions paid to agents were up 22.1 percent to $192 million.
   Maintenance salaries and material expenses rose as the airline
accelerated its overhaul of spare engines, NWA said.
   The company reached a tentative contract agreement with its
6,700 flight attendants on March 22, averting a strike set for
March 29. The Teamsters union local representing the attendants
announced earlier Friday that the contract had been ratified
through a mail-in vote.
   Pan Am also said it was informed Friday by its flight attendants
union that the attendants had voted to reject a new contract
calling for $90 million in wage cuts and other labor concessions.
The contract has been ratified by the unions representing pilots
and flight engineers at the airline, and negotiations are ongoing
between management and the Transport Workers Union.
   The company underwent a major management shakeup in January in
which the chairman and other top executives were replaced. To
ensure its financial recovery, Pan Am would need labor concessions
totaling around $540 million over three years, analysts and company
sources estimate.
   The concessions agreed to by the pilots and flight engineers
represent about $240 million over three years, while the Teamsters
union has informally accepted $35 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
