<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some late buying of smaller ``secondary'' issues
enabled the stock market to finish mixed Friday in another
slow-motion session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 8.95 to
2,032.33, closing out the week with a net gain of 17.24 points.
   Advancing issues and declines were evenly balanced in the daily
tally on the New York Stock Exchange, with 748 up, 738 down and 491
unchanged. Declines had earlier predominated by as much as a 5-2
ratio.
   Big Board volume came to 135.62 million shares, just a bit above
the 1988 low of 128.68 million recorded Thursday. The NYSE's
composite index lost .46 to 147.87.
   Riggs National Bank of Washington raised its prime lending rate
from 8{ to 8} percent. Analysts said the increase came as no real
surprise, given the recent rise of open-market money rates that
help determine banks' cost of funds, and no large money-center
banks moved to match it.
   In fact, interest rates in the credit markets showed signs of
steadying after rising on Thursday.
   Nevertheless, analysts said stocks were still suffering from a
dearth of buying interest among both individual investors and
professional money managers.
   The market showed little reaction to the Commerce Department's
report that the index of leading economic indicators rose 0.8
percent in March. The figure came in close to advance estimates.
   MGM-UA Communications rose 1| to 18]. The Wall Street Journal
quoted entertainment industry executives as saying several foreign
companies were looking MGM-UA over as a possible acquisition
candidate.
   Aetna Life & Casualty dropped 1[ to 42. The company reported
lower operating earnings for the first quarter, and said it didn't
expect its operating profits for the full year to equal its 1987
results.
   Ford Motor dropped ] to 47\ despite the company's report
Thursday of record first-quarter profits.
   Other losers among the blue chip and glamor issues included
Procter & Gamble, down 1[ at 77[; General Motors, down { at 75;
Digital Equipment, down 1[ at 104~, and Exxon, down [ at 44~.
   Golden Nugget gained 1] to 15\ on top of a 1{-point jump
Thursday. The company said it would follow its policy of declining
to comment on unusual market activity or rumors.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market dropped $6.56 billion, or 0.25
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 157.64 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index lost 1.61 to 304.48, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 1.28 at 261.33.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.47 to 379.24. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 303.14, up 1.64.
