<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 2126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-JapanFoodstuffs     04-29 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Foodstuffs,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beef-Orange Talks to Continue Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's agriculture minister will remain in
Washington until next week in efforts to break the deadlock in
negotiations over barriers against the sale of more U.S. beef and
oranges in Japan, a spokesman said Friday.
   Takashi Sato, minister of agriculture, fisheries and forestry
and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter met for the third
consecutive day Friday and decided to continue their talks Monday,
said Sato's spokesman and economic director, Hidero Maki.
   Maki told reporters many points were covered and there were
differences between the two sides that were difficult to bridge,
especially in the case of beef. He would not say if there was any
progress.
   The United States has been demanding that Japan end the quotas
that the two countries agreed to in a four-year accord that expired
at the end of March with the collapse of an earlier round of
Sato-Yeutter talks.
   Japanese beef and citrus producers have argued that removal of
the quotas would threaten their livelihood. U.S. exporters counter
that Japanese consumers are being deprived of meat and fruit
costing less than half the prices charged for the protected
domestic products.
</TEXT>
