<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0538</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic leaders of Congress are urging
President Reagan to sign a sweeping trade bill, but the White House
says he will veto it.
   Reagan's opposition to the bill centers on a provision requiring
companies to give workers 60 days' notice of plant closings or
major layoffs.
   ``As an old labor union president, I suggest that's a matter
that belongs in the management-labor contracts between the unions
and the people,'' the president said Thursday.
   Meanwhile, Asian and European Common Market officials warned
that the measure likely would invite retaliation harmful to the
world economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
earned millions in quick profits by buying and then selling
high-yield, high-risk ``junk'' bonds marketed by the firm,
congressional investigators say.
   Documents released Thursday by the House Energy and Commerce
investigations subcommittee showed that on several occasions
partnerships owned by Drexel employees were permitted to buy bonds
from much-sought issues at the same time the firm's public
customers were being turned away.
   Drexel chief executive Frederick H. Joseph defended the firm's
practice, telling the subcommittee Drexel used the same criteria
for deciding how many bonds employees could purchase as it did for
its other customers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc. spurned a takeover by
rival American Stores Inc. that would have created the nation's
largest supermarket chain and agreed to a $2.2 billion buyout by a
New York investment firm.
   The announcement Thursday sent Lucky's stock climbing $5.37{ a
share to $61.50 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The $61-per-share deal is worth about $600 million more than the
initial $45-per-share offer by American Stores. The Salt Lake
City-based suitor sweetened the offer to $60 earlier Thursday but
again was rebuffed.
</TEXT>
