<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Lower Again In Antsy Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nervousness about the outcome of talks between
OPEC and non-OPEC producers has sent oil futures prices lower for a
second straight day.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, contracts for June
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, fell
29 cents to close at $17.98 a barrel. The contract lost 33 cents on
Wednesday.
   Among May contracts for refined products, wholesale unleaded
gasoline fell 0.53 cent to 51.83 cents a gallon, and wholesale
heating oil fell 0.80 cent a gallon to 50.97 cents.
   Analysts said traders were reluctant to take strong positions
before the completion of OPEC meetings going on in Vienna, Austria.
   Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
were faced with a Wednesday offer by six non-cartel producers to
cut their output by 5 percent for two months, if OPEC did likewise.
   The move would be intended to reduce world supplies and bolster
prices.
   Talks among the cartel members over the proposal adjourned with
no decisions and were to resume late today.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said traders remained skeptical ``about whether these
meetings will accomplish anything,''
   Accordingly, Thursday's market was dominated by ``a lot of
profit-taking by traders who believed the market had come up too
quickly'' in recent week, he said.
</TEXT>
