<FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   04-29 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Of NY Says Nearly Half Of Irving Shares Tendered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's second largest bank remains committed to
acquiring a large stake in Irving Bank Corp. but acknowledges its
chances have dimmed given strong shareholder reception of the rival
hostile tender offer by Bank of New York.
   Bank of New York disclosed Thursday that nearly half of Irving's
outstanding shares had been tendered so far under its $1.08 billion
buyout offer of roughly $64 a share in cash and stock.
   Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, which is offering to acquire a
45 percent stake in Irving for $75 a share, has no immediate plans
to raise its offer but still believes it is the better deal, Lino
Benassi, BCA deputy general manager, said Thursday.
   Irving stock fell $2 to $60.62{ a share Thursday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   ``We believe that our (current) offer is the best offer because
we provide a lot of cash ...,'' Benassi said in an interview.
   He also conceded, ``I don't think our chances are extremely
good'' of winning Irving shareholder approval of BCA's proposal.
   The Italian bank's stock purchase is part of a complex
restructuring proposed by Irving. Banca Commerciale also would have
the right to buy an additional 10 percent of Irving stock on the
open market after the deal was consummated.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 5 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding. The tender offer, which
has been extended three times, was set to expire today.
   Bank of New York said that at the close of business Wednesday,
9.03 million of Irving's outstanding shares had been tendered.
Those, along with the 888,634 shares Bank of New York already owns,
give it 53.96 percent of Irving's shares, the company said.
   ``We feel we're right on track, but we don't want to become
overconfident. We're still engaged in a proxy fight,'' said
spokesman Owen Brady.
   The bank is running a slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board of
directors. The Irving shareholders' meeting is scheduled for May 6.
   Banking experts noted that the shareholders who had tendered
their stock to Bank of New York still could change their minds
should another, better proposal surface, but said another offer
appeared unlikely.
   ``I think they (Bank of New York) are definitely in a strong
position. They have the inside track, so to speak,'' said Michael
Starr, an analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc.
   Irving spokesman Hal Phillips said his company has no comment on
Bank of New York's latest announcement.
   Irving's proposed restructuring includes the sale of assets,
such as its 50-story Wall Street headquarters, cost-cutting
measures, and a $10-a- share special cash dividend. Banca
Commerciale values the entire Irving plan at around $69.50 a share.
   The Banca Commerciale proposal still needs regulatory approval
from both U.S. and Italian authorities. Some analysts say that
could work in Bank of New York's favor because it already has
received conditional approval from the Federal Reserve and New York
State Banking boards for its merger plan.
   Benassi said he was confident Banca Commerciale would receive
all the necessary approval, although he admitted it could take a
few months to achieve. The Federal Reserve Bank of New York
recently noted in a four-page internal memorandum that it would
have to ``revisit'' the policy issues posed by the fact that 62
percent of the Italian bank is owned by the government agency
Instituto per la Recostruzione Industriale.
   There are no clear-cut policies for foreign government-owned
banks seeking to merge with domestic banks.
   The last time the Fed examined such issues was in 1982, when
Banca Commerciale acquried Long Island Trust Co. The Fed took 15
months to approve that application.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
